.censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/paper2/data_files/India2/Table_2_PR_Cities_1Lakh_and_Above.pdf|archivedate=23 July 2013}}</ref>\n| population_density_km2          = auto\n| population_metro                = 1,216,719\n| population_metro_footnotes      = <ref name=\"UA population\">{{cite web|title=Urban Agglomerations/Cities having population 1 lakh and above|url=http://censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/paper2/data_files/India2/Table_3_PR_UA_Citiees_1Lakh_and_Above.allahabad|website=Census India|publisher=The Registrar General & Census Commissioner|accessdate=25 June 2014|format=PDF|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017153124/http://censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/paper2/data_files/India2/Table_3_PR_UA_Citiees_1Lakh_and_Above.pdf|archivedate=17 October 2013}}</ref>\n| population_rank                 = [[List of most populous cities in India|36th]]\n| population_blank1_title         = Metro rank\n| population_blank1               = [[List of million-plus agglomerations in India|40th]]\n| population_demonyms             = Allahabadi, Ilahabadi, Prayagraji\n| timezone1                       = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1                     = +5:30\n| postal_code_type                = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code                     = 211001-18\n| area_code                       = +91-532\n| area_code_type                  = Telephone code\n| registration_plate              = UP-70\n| blank1_name_sec1                = [[Human sex ratio|Sex ratio]]\n| blank1_info_sec1                = 852 [[Female|\u2640]]/1000[[Male|\u2642]]\n| website                         = {{URL|1=https://prayagraj.nic.in/|2=Official district website}}\n| footnotes                       = {{Reflist|group=upper-alpha}}\n| leader_name2                    = Bhanu Chandra Goswami, [[Indian Administrative Service|IAS]]\n| leader_title2                   = [[District collector (India)|District Magistrate]]\n| leader_name3                    = Mohit Aggarwal, [[Indian Police Service|IPS]]\n| leader_title3                   = [[Inspector general of police#India|Inspector General]], Allahabad Range\n| leader_name4                    = Nitin Tiwari, [[Indian Police Service|IPS]]\n| leader_title4                   = [[Superintendent of police (India)|Senior Superintendent of Police]]\n| demographics_type1              = Language\n| demographics1_title1            = Official\n| demographics1_info1             = [[Hindi language|Hindi]]<ref name=\"langoff\">{{cite web|title=52nd REPORT OF THE COMMISSIONER FOR LINGUISTIC MINORITIES IN INDIA|url=http://nclm.nic.in/shared/linkimages/NCLM52ndReport.pdf|website=nclm.nic.in|publisher=[[Ministry of Minority Affairs]]|accessdate=20 December 2018|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525141614/http://nclm.nic.in/shared/linkimages/NCLM52ndReport.pdf|archivedate=25 May 2017}}</ref>\n| demographics1_title2            = Additional&nbsp;official\n| demographics1_info2             = [[Urdu]]<ref name=\"langoff\" />\n| demographics1_title3            = Regional\n| demographics1_info3             = [[Awadhi language|Awadhi]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ethnologue.com/language/awa |title=Awadhi |website=[[Ethnologue]] |accessdate=7 May 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Allahabad''' ({{audio|Allahabad.ogg|pronunciation}}),<!-- Allahabad is the COMMONNAME, as per the article title, do no change the common name to official name Prayagraj. See the discussion on the talk page. --> officially known as '''Prayagraj''', and also known as '''Illahabad''' and '''Prayag''', is a city in the [[India]]n state of [[Uttar Pradesh]]. It is the administrative headquarters of [[Allahabad district]]\u2014the most populous district in the state and 13th most populous district in India\u2014and the [[Allahabad division]].\n\nThe city is the judicial capital of [[Uttar Pradesh]] with [[Allahabad High Court]] being the highest judicial body in the state. As of 2011, Allahabad is the [[List of cities in Uttar Pradesh by population|fifth most populous city]] in the state, [[list of North Indian cities by population|eighth]] in [[Northern India]] and [[List of most populous cities in India|twenty-fourth]] in India, with an estimated population of 1.11&nbsp;million in the city and 1.21 million in [[Allahabad Metropolitan Area|its metropolitan region]].<ref name=\"census2011\">{{cite web |url=http://www.census2011.co.in/census/city/138-allahabad.html |title=Allahabad City Population Census 2011 &#124; Uttar Pradesh |publisher=Census2011.co.in |date= |accessdate=26 May 2014 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140517183230/http://www.census2011.co.in/census/city/138-allahabad.html |archivedate=17 May 2014  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.census2011.co.in/census/metropolitan/87-allahabad.html |title=Allahabad Metropolitan Urban Region Population 2011 Census |publisher=Census2011.co.in |accessdate=26 May 2014 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140518234508/http://www.census2011.co.in/census/metropolitan/87-allahabad.html |archivedate=18 May 2014  }}</ref> In 2011 it was ranked the world's 40th fastest-growing city.<ref name=\"fastest growing\">{{cite web|title=The world's fastest growing cities and urban areas from 2006 to 2020|url=http://www.citymayors.com/statistics/urban_growth2.html|work=City Mayors Statistics|accessdate=11 February 2014|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014181201/http://www.citymayors.com/statistics/urban_growth2.html|archivedate=14 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.walkthroughindia.com/walkthroughs/10-twin-towns-and-sister-cities-of-indian-states/|title= 10 Twin Towns and Sister Cities of Indian States|author= <!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|website= walkthroughindia.com|publisher= |accessdate= 9 January 2014|url-status = live|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140109083014/http://www.walkthroughindia.com/walkthroughs/10-twin-towns-and-sister-cities-of-indian-states/|archivedate= 9 January 2014|df= dmy-all}}</ref> Allahabad, in 2016, was also ranked the third most liveable city in the state (after [[Noida]] and [[Lucknow]]) and sixteenth in the country.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://competitiveness.in/publications/reports/liveability-index/ |title=Liveability Index |accessdate=1 August 2015 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150912165115/http://competitiveness.in/publications/reports/liveability-index/ |archivedate=12 September 2015 |publisher=Institute for Competitiveness, India}}</ref> The city experiences one of the highest levels of [[air pollution]] worldwide, with the 2016 update of the [[World Health Organization]]'s ''Global Urban Ambient Air Pollution Database'' finding Allahabad to have the third highest mean concentration of \"PM2.5\" (&lt;2.5&nbsp;\u03bcm diameter) [[particulates|particulate matter]] in the ambient air among all the 2972 cities tested (after [[Zabol]] and [[Gwalior]]).<ref>''[http://www.who.int/phe/health_topics/outdoorair/databases/cities/en/ WHO Global Urban Ambient Air Pollution Database (update 2016)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170301221905/http://who.int/phe/health_topics/outdoorair/databases/cities/en/ |date=1 March 2017 }}'', World Health Organization. See the spreadsheet \"Ambient (outdoor) air pollution database, by country and city\" to which this page links. Retrieved 11 July 2018.</ref>\n\nThe city lies close to [[Triveni Sangam]], \"three-river confluence\", original name&nbsp;\u2013 ''Prayag'', \"place of sacrifice or offering\"&nbsp;\u2013 which lies at the ''sangam'' (confluence) of the [[Ganges]], [[Yamuna]] and [[Sarasvati River|Sarasvati]] rivers,<ref name=sangam /> a propitious place to conduct sacrifices. It plays a central role in [[Hindu scriptures]]. Allahabad was originally called Kaushambi (now a [[Kaushambi District|separate district]]) by the Kuru rulers of [[Hastinapur]], who developed it as their capital. Since then, the city has been a political, cultural and administrative centre of the [[Doab]] region. In the early 17th century, Allahabad was a provincial capital in the [[Mughal Empire]] under the reign of [[Jahangir]].<ref name=\"Pletcher 2010 128\">{{cite book |last=Pletcher |first=Kenneth |date=15 August 2010 |title=The Geography of India: Sacred and Historic Places |url=https://books.google.com/?id=Mjr0X-8jrLAC&pg=PA128&dq=Allahabad+massacre#v=onepage&q=Allahabad%20massacre |location= |publisher=The Rosen Publishing Group |page=128 |isbn= 978-1-61530-142-3|accessdate=21 March 2014 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181115154619/https://books.google.com/books?id=Mjr0X-8jrLAC&pg=PA128&dq=Allahabad+massacre#v=onepage&q=Allahabad|archivedate=15 November 2018  }}</ref>\n\n''[[Akbarnama]]'' mentions that the [[Mughal emperor]] [[Akbar]] founded a great city in Allahabad. [[`Abd al-Qadir Bada'uni]] and [[Nizamuddin Ahmad]] mention that Akbar laid the foundations of an imperial city there which was called ''Ilahabas'' or ''Ilahabad''.<ref name=Ujagir /><ref name=Kumbh67 /> He was said to be impressed by its strategic location and built a fort there, later renaming it ''Ilahabas'' by 1584 which was changed to Allahabad by [[Shah Jahan]].{{Vague|date=November 2018}}<!-- Should this be \"which was changed in 1584\"? --><ref name=Univ />\n\nIn 1580, Akbar created the \"[[Subah]] of Ilahabas\" with Allahabad as its capital.<ref name=Surendra /> In mid-1600, [[Jahangir|Salim]] had made an abortive attempt to seize Agra's treasury and came to Allahabad, seizing its treasury and setting himself up as a virtually independent ruler.<ref name=Eraly /> He was, however, reconciled with Akbar and returned to Allahabad where he stayed before returning to the royal court in 1604.<ref name=Richards />\n\nIn 1833 it became the seat of the [[Ceded and Conquered Provinces]] region before its capital was moved to [[Agra]] in 1835.<ref name=\"MHBI\">{{cite book|author=H.S. Bhatia|title=Military History of British India: 1607\u20131947|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Lrjr7P2HMfkC&pg=PA96&dq=history+of+allahabad#v=onepage&q=history%20of%20allahabad|accessdate=16 February 2014|publisher=Deep and Deep Publications'|isbn=978-81-8450-079-0|page=97|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181115154711/https://books.google.com/books?id=Lrjr7P2HMfkC&pg=PA96&dq=history+of+allahabad#v=onepage&q=history|archivedate=15 November 2018|year=2008}}</ref>{{better source|date=April 2018}} Allahabad became the capital of the [[North-Western Provinces]] in 1858 and was the [[List of capitals of India|capital of India]] for a day.<ref name=\"Ashutosh Joshi 1 January 2008 237\">{{cite book|title=Town Planning Regeneration of Cities|author=Ashutosh Joshi|publisher=New India Publishing|date=1 January 2008|isbn=978-81-89422-82-0|page=237|url=https://books.google.com/?id=UFaGME0XDBkC&pg=PA151&dq=Naini#v=onepage&q=Allahabad%20capital|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181115154758/https://books.google.com/books?id=UFaGME0XDBkC&pg=PA151&dq=Naini#v=onepage&q=Allahabad|archivedate=15 November 2018}}</ref> The city was the capital of the [[United Provinces of Agra and Oudh|United Provinces]] from 1902<ref name=\"Ashutosh Joshi 1 January 2008 237\" /> to 1920<ref name=\"Ward2008\">{{cite book|author=Kerry Ward|title=Networks of Empire: Forced Migration in the Dutch East India Company|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YNBmIu5m6hAC|accessdate=3 August 2012|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-88586-7|page=340|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523054906/http://books.google.com/books?id=YNBmIu5m6hAC|archivedate=23 May 2013|year=2009}}</ref> and remained at the forefront of national importance during the [[Indian independence movement|struggle for Indian independence]].<ref name=\"Desai1986\" />\n\nLocated in southern Uttar Pradesh, the city's metropolitan area covers 70.5&nbsp;km<sup>2 </sup>(27.22 sq miles).<ref name=\"timesofindia.indiatimes.com\">{{cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/allahabad/City-generates-534760-kg-domestic-waste-daily/articleshow/7463898.cms |title=City generates 5,34,760 kg domestic waste daily |accessdate=29 August 2015 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151218090413/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/allahabad/City-generates-534760-kg-domestic-waste-daily/articleshow/7463898.cms |archivedate=18 December 2015 }}</ref> Although the city and its surrounding area are governed by several municipalities, a large portion of Allahabad District is governed by the Allahabad City Council. The city is home to colleges, research institutions and 2 dozen [[Central government|central]] and [[Government of Uttar Pradesh|state government]] offices. Allahabad has hosted cultural and sporting events, including the [[Prayag Kumbh Mela]] and the [[Indira Marathon]]. Although the city's economy was built on tourism, most of its income now derives from real estate and financial services. The Allahabad district is the second-most revenue providing district in Uttar Pradesh.{{Citation needed|reason=This is a claim, not a fact. Remove this tav only when proper citation is provided to this.|date=October 2018}}\n\n== Etymology ==\nThe location at the confluence of Ganges and Yamuna rivers has been known in ancient times as Pray\u0101ga, which means \"place of a sacrifice\" in Sanskrit (''pra-,'' \"fore-\" + ''yaj-'', \"to sacrifice\").<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sanskrit-lexicon.uni-koeln.de/scans/MWScan/2014/web/webtc/servepdf.php?page=687|title=A Sanskrit\u2013English Dictionary|last=Monier-Williams|first=Monier|date=|website=www.sanskrit-lexicon.uni-koeln.de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> It was believed that god [[Brahma]] performed the very first sacrifice ([[yajna|''yajna'']]) in this place.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/yogi-adityanath-takes-allahabad-to-prayagraj-after-443-years-a-recap-of-history-1368216-2018-10-15|title=Yogi Adityanath takes Allahabad to Prayagraj after 443 years: A recap of History|website=[[India Today]]|author=India Today Web Desk|date=15 October 2018|access-date=12 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190213011029/https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/yogi-adityanath-takes-allahabad-to-prayagraj-after-443-years-a-recap-of-history-1368216-2018-10-15|archive-date=13 February 2019|url-status = live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hindi.timesnownews.com/spiritual/article/what-is-the-meaning-of-prayagraj-new-name-of-allahabad-city-how-is-brahma-connected/300287|title=\u0915\u094d\u092f\u093e \u0939\u0948 \u092a\u094d\u0930\u092f\u093e\u0917\u0930\u093e\u091c \u0915\u093e \u092e\u0924\u0932\u092c? \u0938\u0943\u0937\u094d\u091f\u093f \u0915\u0940 \u0930\u091a\u0928\u093e \u0915\u0947 \u092c\u093e\u0926 \u091c\u0939\u093e\u0902 \u092c\u094d\u0930\u0939\u094d\u092e\u093e \u0928\u0947 \u0938\u092c\u0938\u0947 \u092a\u0939\u0932\u0947 \u0938\u0902\u092a\u0928\u094d\u0928 \u0915\u093f\u092f\u093e \u0925\u093e \u092f\u091c\u094d\u091e|website=[[Times Now]]|author=\u091f\u093e\u0907\u092e\u094d\u0938 \u0928\u093e\u0909 \u0921\u093f\u091c\u093f\u091f\u0932|language=hi|access-date=12 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190213005748/https://hindi.timesnownews.com/spiritual/article/what-is-the-meaning-of-prayagraj-new-name-of-allahabad-city-how-is-brahma-connected/300287|archive-date=13 February 2019|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nThe word ''pray\u0101ga'' has been traditionally used to mean \"a confluence of rivers\". For Allahabad, it denoted the physical meeting point of the rivers [[Ganges]] and [[Yamuna]] in the city. An ancient tradition has it that a third river, invisible [[Sarasvati river|Sarasvati]], also meets there with the two. Today, [[Triveni Sangam]] (or simply Sangam) is a more frequently used name.\n\nPrayagraj (Sanskirt: ''Pray\u0101gar\u0101ja'') means \"the king among the five ''pray\u0101gas''\" and is used to denote the superiority of this confluence over [[Panch Prayag|the other four sacred confluencies in India]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/videos/news/india/what-does-prayagraj-actually-mean-times-now-exclusive/12779|title=What does 'Prayagraj' actually mean?|website=[[Times Now]]|author=Akrita Reyar|date=17 October 2018|access-date=12 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190213005706/https://www.timesnownews.com/videos/news/india/what-does-prayagraj-actually-mean-times-now-exclusive/12779|archive-date=13 February 2019|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nIt is said that the Mughal emperor [[Akbar]] visited the region in 1575 and was so impressed by the strategic location of the site that he ordered a fort be constructed. The fort was constructed by 1584 and called ''Ilahabas'' or \"Abode of God\", later changed to ''Allahabad'' under [[Shah Jahan]]. Speculations regarding its name however, exist. Because of the surrounding people calling it ''Alhabas'', has led to some people{{Who|date=April 2020}} holding the view that it was named after [[Alha]] from [[Alha-Khand|Alha's story]].<ref name=\"Univ\">{{cite book|title=University of Allahabad Studies|publisher=[[University of Allahabad]]|year=1962|page=8}}</ref> [[James Forbes (artist)|James Forbes]]' account of the early 1800s claims that it was renamed Allahabad or \"Abode of God\" by [[Jahangir]] after he failed to destroy the [[Akshayavat]] tree. The name, however, predates him, with ''Ilahabas'' and ''Ilahabad'' mentioned on coins minted in the city since Akbar's rule, the latter name became predominant after the emperor's death. It has also been thought to not have been named after [[Allah]] but ''ilaha'' (the gods). Shaligram Shrivastav claimed in ''Prayag Pradip'' that the name was deliberately given by Akbar to be construed as both Hindu (\"ilaha\") and Muslim (\"Allah\").<ref name=\"Kumbh67\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MALacgnsroMC&pg=PA67|title=Pilgrimage and Power: The Kumbh Mela in Allahabad, 1765\u20131954|page=67|publisher=Oxford University Press|author=Kama Maclean|year=2008|isbn=9780195338942}}</ref>\n\nOver the years, a number of attempts were made by the [[BJP]]-led governments of Uttar Pradesh to rename Allahabad to Prayagraj. In 1992, the planned rename was shelved when the chief minister, [[Kalyan Singh]], was forced to resign following the [[Babri Masjid demolition]]. 2001 saw another attempt led by the government of [[Rajnath Singh]] which remained unfulfilled.<ref name=\"Kumbh672\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MALacgnsroMC&pg=PA67|title=Pilgrimage and Power: The Kumbh Mela in Allahabad, 1765\u20131954|author=Kama Maclean|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2008|page=67|isbn=9780195338942}}</ref> The rename finally succeeded in October 2018 when the [[Yogi Adityanath]]-led government officially changed the name of the city to Prayagraj.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/allahabad-renamed-prayagraj-1368913-2018-10-16|title=Allahabad to Prayagraj: UP cabinet okays name change|work=India Today|language=en|access-date=16 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181016165043/https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/allahabad-renamed-prayagraj-1368913-2018-10-16|archive-date=16 October 2018|url-status = live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ndtv.com/allahabad-news/up-government-issues-notification-renaming-allahabad-to-prayagraj-1935038|title=UP Government Issues Notification Renaming Allahabad To Prayagraj|work=NDTV.com|accessdate=24 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181021151149/https://www.ndtv.com/allahabad-news/up-government-issues-notification-renaming-allahabad-to-prayagraj-1935038|archive-date=21 October 2018|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n{{Main|History of Allahabad}}\n{{See also|Timeline of Allahabad history}}\n\n=== Antiquity ===\nThe earliest mention of Pray\u0101ga and the associated pilgrimage is found in ''[[Rigveda]] Pari\u015bi\u1e63\u1e6da'' (supplement to the ''Rigveda'', c. 1200\u20131000 BCE).{{sfn|Krishnaswamy|Ghosh|1935|pp=698\u2013699, 702\u2013703}} It is also mentioned in the [[Pali]] canons of [[Buddhism]], such as in section 1.7 of ''[[Majjhima Nikaya]]'' (c. 500 BCE), wherein the Buddha states that bathing in ''Payaga'' (Skt: Prayaga) cannot wash away cruel and evil deeds, rather the virtuous one should be pure in heart and fair in action.<ref>{{cite book|title= Teachings of The Buddha: Majjhima Nikaya |author1 = Bhikkhu Nanamoli (Tr)|author2 = Bhikkhu Bodhi(Tr)|year = 1995|isbn = 978-0861710720| url = https://archive.org/details/MajjhimaNikaya| page=[https://archive.org/details/MajjhimaNikaya/page/n483 121]}}</ref> The ''[[Mahabharata]]'' (c. 400 BCE\u2013300 CE) mentions a bathing pilgrimage at Prayag as a means of ''pr\u0101ya\u015bcitta'' (atonement, penance) for past mistakes and guilt.{{Sfn|Kane|1953|pp=55\u201356}} In ''Tirthayatra Parva'', before the great war, the epic states \"the one who observes firm [ethical] vows, having bathed at Prayaga during Magha, O best of the Bharatas, becomes spotless and reaches heaven.\"<ref>{{cite book|author=Diana L. Eck|title=India: A Sacred Geography|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PyC4o7i9tnEC|year=2013|publisher=Three Rivers Press|isbn=978-0-385-53192-4|page=153}}</ref> In ''Anushasana parva'', after the war, the epic elaborates this bathing pilgrimage as \"geographical tirtha\" that must be combined with ''manasa-tirtha'' (tirtha of the heart) whereby one lives by values such as truth, charity, self-control, patience and others.<ref>Diane Eck (1981), India's \"T\u012brthas: \"Crossings\" in Sacred Geography, ''History of Religions'', Vol. 20, No. 4, pp. 340\u2013341 with footnote</ref>\n\nPray\u0101ga is mentioned in the ''[[Agni Purana]]'' and other [[Puranas]] with various legends, including being one of the places where [[Brahma]] attended a [[yajna]] (homa), and the confluence of river Ganges, Yamuna and mythical Saraswati site as the king of pilgrimage sites (''Tirtha Raj'').<ref name=\"Dubey2001\">{{cite book|author=Shiva Kumar Dubey|title=Kumbh city Prayag|url=https://archive.org/details/kumbhcityprayag00unse|accessdate=3 August 2012|publisher=Centre for Cultural Resources and Training|pages=[https://archive.org/details/kumbhcityprayag00unse/page/31 31]\u201341, 82|year=2001}}</ref> Other early accounts of the significance of Prayag to Hinduism is found in the various versions of the ''Prayaga Mahatmya'', dated to the late 1st-millennium CE. These Purana-genre Sanskrit texts describe Prayag as a place \"bustling with pilgrims, priests, vendors, beggars, guides\" and local citizens busy along the confluence of the rivers (''sangam'').<ref name=\"Glucklich2008p146\">{{cite book|author=Ariel Glucklich|title=The Strides of Vishnu: Hindu Culture in Historical Perspective|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KtLScrjrWiAC&pg=PA146|year=2008|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-971825-2|pages=146\u2013147}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Ludo Rocher|title=The Pur\u0101\u1e47as|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=n0-4RJh5FgoC&pg=PA71|year=1986|publisher=Otto Harrassowitz Verlag|isbn=978-3-447-02522-5 |pages=71\u201372 |quote=with footnotes}}</ref> Prayaga is also mentioned in the Hindu epic ''[[Ramayana]]'', a place with the legendary ''Ashram'' of sage [[Bharadwaj]].<ref name=\"Krishnamoorthy1991\">{{cite book|author=K. Krishnamoorthy|title=A Critical Inventory of R\u0101m\u0101ya\u1e47a Studies in the World: Indian languages and English|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iOtreyGBGHQC&pg=PA28|accessdate=3 August 2012|publisher=Sahitya Academy|isbn=978-81-7201-100-0|pages=28\u201351|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523070430/http://books.google.com/books?id=iOtreyGBGHQC&pg=PA28|archivedate=23 May 2013|year=1991}}</ref>\n\n====Archaeology and inscriptions====\n[[File:Ashoka pillar, Allahabad, c.1900.jpg|thumb|The [[Allahabad pillar|Ashoka pillar at Allahabad]] (photo c. 1900) contains many inscriptions since the 3rd-century BCE. Sometime about 1575 CE, [[Birbal]] of Akbar's era added an inscription that mentions the \"Magh mela at Prayag Tirth Raj\".{{sfn|Krishnaswamy|Ghosh|1935|pp=698\u2013699, 702\u2013703}}<ref>{{cite book|title= Corpus Inscriptionum Indicarum| volume= 1| year=1877| author= Alexander Cunningham|url= https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.62072|pp=[https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.62072/page/n55 37]\u201339}}</ref>]]\nInscription evidence from the famed Ashoka edicts containing [[Allahabad pillar]] \u2013 also referred to as the Prayaga Bull pillar \u2013 adds to the confusion about the antiquity of this city.<ref name=irwin1/><ref name=irwin2/> Excavations have revealed [[Northern Black Polished Ware]] dating to 600\u2013700 BCE.<ref name=\"Dubey2001\" /> According to [[Dilip Kumar Chakrabarti]], there is nothing to suggest that \"modern Prayag (modern Allahabad) was an ancient city\", but it is also inconceivable that there was no city at the holiest pilgrimage site in Hinduism. Chakrabarti suggests that the city of [[Jhusi]], opposite the confluence, must have been the \"ancient settlement of Prayag\".<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OEZe-wAIiKIC&pg=PA263|title=Archaeological Geography of the Ganga Plain: The Lower and the Middle Ganga|author=Dilip Kumar Chakrabarti|publisher=[[Orient Blackswan]]|year=2001| page=263|isbn=9788178240169|author-link=Dilip Kumar Chakrabarti}}</ref> Archaeological surveys since the 1950s has revealed the presence of human settlements near the ''sangam'' since about 800 BCE.<ref name=irwin1/><ref name=irwin2/>\n\nAlong with Ashoka's Brahmi script inscription from 3rd-century BCE, the pillar has a Samudragupta inscription, as well as a Magha Mela inscription of [[Birbal]] of Akbar's era. It states,\n\n{{quote|In the Samvat year 1632, Saka 1493, in Magha, the 5th of the waning moon, on Monday, Gangadas's son Maharaja [[Birbal]] made the auspicious pilgrimage to Tirth Raj Prayag. Saphal scripsit.<br>\u2013 Translated by Alexander Cunningham (1879){{sfn|Cunningham|1879|p=39}}\n}}\n\nThese dates correspond to about 1575 CE, and confirm the importance and the name Prayag.{{sfn|Cunningham|1879|p=39}}{{sfn|Krishnaswamy|Ghosh|1935|pp=698\u2013699}} According to Cunningham, this pillar was brought to Allahabad from Kaushambi by a Muslim Sultan, and that in some later century before Akbar, the old city of Prayag had been deserted.<ref>{{cite book|title=Allahabad: a study in urban geography|author=Ujagir Singh|publisher=[[Banaras Hindu University]]|year=1958|page=32}}</ref> Other scholars, such as Krishnaswamy and Ghosh disagree.{{sfn|Krishnaswamy|Ghosh|1935|pp=698\u2013699}} In a paper published in 1935, they state that the pillar was always at its current location based on the inscription dates on the pillar, lack of textual evidence for the move in records left by Muslim historians and the difficulty in moving the massive pillar.{{sfn|Krishnaswamy|Ghosh|1935|pp=698\u2013703}} Further, like Cunningham, they noted that many smaller inscriptions were added on the pillar over time. Quite many of these inscriptions include a date between 1319 CE and 1575 CE, and most of these refer to the month Magha. According to Krishnaswamy and Ghosh, these dates are likely related to the [[Kumbh Mela|Magh Mela]] pilgrimage at Prayag, as recommended in the ancient Hindu texts.{{sfn|Krishnaswamy|Ghosh|1935|pp=702\u2013703}} \n\nIn papers published about 1979, John Irwin \u2013 a scholar of Indian Art History and Archaeology, concurred with Krishnaswamy and Ghosh that the Allahabad pillar was never moved and was always at the confluence of the rivers Ganges and Yamuna.<ref name=irwin1/><ref name=irwin2/> According to Irwin, an analysis of the minor inscriptions and ancient scribblings on the pillar first observed by Cunningham, also noted by Krishnaswamy and Ghosh, reveals that these included years and months, and the latter \"always turns out to be Magha, which also gives it name to the [[Magh Mela]]\", the Prayaga bathing pilgrimage festival of the Hindus.<ref name=irwin2/> He further stated that the pillar origins were undoubtedly pre-Ashokan based on the new evidence from the archaeological and geological surveys of the triveni site (Prayaga), the major and minor inscriptions as well as textual evidence, taken together.<ref name=irwin1>{{cite book|author=John Irwin| editor=Herbert Hartel|title= South Asian Archaeology |year=1979|oclc= 8500702|isbn= 978-3-49600-1584|publisher = D. Reimer Verlag (Berlin)|pages=313\u2013340}}</ref><ref name=irwin2>{{cite journal|author=John Irwin| title= The ancient pillar-cult at Pray\u0101ga (Allahabad): its pre-A\u015bokan origins| journal= The Journal of the Royal Asiatic Society of Great Britain and Ireland| issue= 2| year=1983|jstor= 25211537|publisher = Cambridge University Press|pages=253\u2013280}}</ref> Archaeological and geological surveys done since the 1950s, states Irwin, have revealed that the rivers \u2013 particularly Ganges \u2013 had a different course in distant past than now. The original path of river Ganges at the Prayaga confluence had settlements dating from 8th-century BCE onwards.<ref name=irwin2/> According to [[Karel Werner]] \u2013 an Indologist known for his studies on religion particularly Buddhism, the Irwin papers \"showed conclusively that the pillar did not originate at Kaushambi\", but had been at Prayaga from pre-Buddhist times.<ref>{{cite book|author=Karel Werner|title=Symbols in Art and Religion: The Indian and the Comparative Perspectives |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aSGzDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT95 |year=1990|publisher=Routledge|isbn=0-7007-0215-6|pages=95\u201396}}</ref>\n\n=== Early medieval period ===\n\nThe 7th-century Buddhist Chinese traveller [[Xuanzang]] (Hiuen Tsang) mentions king Harsha and his capital of Prayag, which he states to be a sacred Hindu city with hundreds of \"[[Deva (Hinduism)|deva]] temples\" and two Buddhist institutions. His 644 CE memoir also mentions the Hindu bathing rituals at the junction of the rivers.<ref name=\"Glucklich2008p145\">{{cite book|author=Ariel Glucklich|title=The Strides of Vishnu: Hindu Culture in Historical Perspective|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KtLScrjrWiAC&pg=PA146|year=2008|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-971825-2|pages=145\u2013146}}</ref> Kama MacLean \u2013 an Indologist who has published articles on the Kumbh Mela predominantly based on the colonial archives and English-language media,<ref>{{cite journal| author= Christian Lee Novetzke| url= https://muse.jhu.edu/article/381707 | title= Review of Pilgrimage and Power: The Kumbh Mela in Allahabad, 1765\u20131954|journal= Journal of Interdisciplinary History| volume= 41| number= 1| year= 2010| pp= 174\u2013175}}</ref> states based on emails from other scholars and a more recent interpretation of the 7th-century Xuanzang memoir, that Prayag was an important site in 7th-century India, but that it might have been a Buddhist festival site then. She states that the alternative interpretation of Xuanzang suggests that the pilgrimage at Prayag featured a Buddha statue and involved alms giving, consistent with Buddhist practices.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Making the Colonial State Work for You: The Modern Beginnings of the Ancient Kumbh Mela in Allahabad| author=Kama MacLean| journal=The Journal of Asian Studies| year=2003| volume=62| number=3| page=877| doi=10.2307/3591863| jstor=3591863}}</ref>\n\nXuanzang mentions a tree, near which lay human bones of people who had committed suicide by jumping from it in the belief of going to heaven. [[Alexander Cunningham]] believed the tree described by Xuanzang was the [[Akshayavat]] tree and probably still existed at the time of [[Al-Biruni]] who called it the \"tree of Allahabad\". According to Ariel Glucklich \u2013 a scholar of Hinduism and Anthropology of Religion, the Xuanzang memoir mentions both the superstitious devotional suicide and how a Brahmin of a more ancient era successfully put an end to this practice.<ref name=\"Glucklich2008p145\"/> \n\nThe historic literature of Hinduism and Buddhism before the Mughal emperor [[Akbar]] use the term Prayag, and never use the term Allahabad or its variants. Its history before the [[Mughal Emperor]] [[Akbar]] is unclear.<ref>{{cite book|title=Allahabad: a study in urban geography|author=Ujagir Singh|publisher=[[Banaras Hindu University]]|year=1958|pages=29\u201330}}</ref> In contrast to the account of Xuanzang, the Muslim historians place the tree at the confluence of the rivers. The historian Dr. D. B. Dubey states that it appears that between this period, the sandy plain was washed away by the Ganges, to an extent that the temple and tree seen by the Chinese traveller too was washed away, with the river later changing its course to the east and the confluence shifting to the place where Akbar laid the foundations of his fort.<ref>{{cite book|title=Pray\u0101ga, the Site of Kumbha Mel\u0101: In Temporal and Traditional Space|author=D. B. Dubey|publisher=Aryan Books International|year=2001|page=57}}</ref>\n\n[[Henry Miers Elliot]] believed that a town existed before Allahabad was founded. He adds that after [[Mahmud of Ghazni]] captured Asn\u00ed near [[Fatehpur, Uttar Pradesh|Fatehpur]], he couldn't have crossed into [[Bundelkhand]] without visiting Allahabad had there been a city worth plundering. He further adds that its capture should have been heard when [[Muhammad of Ghor]] captured Benares. however, Ghori's historians never noticed it.  ''[[Akbarnama]]'' mentions that the [[Mughal emperor]] Akbar founded a great city in Allahabad. [[`Abd al-Qadir Bada'uni]] and [[Nizamuddin Ahmad]] mention that Akbar laid the foundations of an Imperial City there which he called ''Ilahabas''.<ref name=Ujagir>{{cite book|title=Allahabad: a study in urban geography|author=Ujagir Singh|publisher=[[Banaras Hindu University]]|year=1958|pages=31\u201332}}</ref>\n\n=== Mughal rule ===\n[[File:Akbar Fort Allahabad.jpg|thumb|[[Allahabad Fort]], built by Mughal Emperor [[Akbar]] in 1575 on the banks of the [[Yamuna River]].]]\n[[File:Tomb of Nisar Begum at Khusro Bagh Allahabad.jpg|thumb|Tomb of Nithar Begum (daughter of Mughal Emperor [[Jahangir]]) at [[Khusro Bagh]].]]\n[[Abul Fazal]] in his ''Ain-i-Akbari'' states, \"For a long time his (Akbar's) desire was to found a great city in the town of Piyag (Allahabad) where the rivers Ganges and Jamuna join... On 13th November 1583 (1st [[Azar]] 991 H.) he (Akbar) reached the wished spot and laid the foundations of the city and planned four forts.\" Abul Fazal adds, \"Ilahabad anciently called Prayag was distinguished by His Imperial Majesty [Akbar] by the former name\".<ref name=burnmint>{{cite journal|author=R Burn| title= The Mints of the Mughal Emperors| publisher=Royal Asiatic Society of Bengal|journal=Journal and Proceedings of the Royal Asiatic Society|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jyIYAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA78|year=1907|pages=78\u201379}}</ref> The role of Akbar in founding the Ilahabad \u2013 later called Allahabad \u2013 fort and city is mentioned by [[`Abd al-Qadir Bada'uni]] as well.<ref name=snsinha/>\n\n[[Nizamuddin Ahmad]] gives two different dates for Allahabad's foundation, in different sections of ''Tabaqat-i-Akbari''. He states that Akbar laid the foundation of the city at a place of the confluence of Ganges and Jumna which was a very sacred site of Hindus, then gives 1574 and 1584 as the year of its founding, and that it was named Ilahabas.<ref name=snsinha>{{cite book|title=Subah of Allahabad under the great Mughals, 1580\u20131707 |publisher=[[Jamia Millia Islamia]]|author=Surendra Nath Sinha|year=1974|url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.118676|pages=[https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.118676/page/n97 85]\u201386 |quote=with footnotes}}</ref>\n\nAkbar was impressed by its strategic location for a fort.<ref name=\"Univ\"/> According to William Pinch, Akbar's motive may have been twofold. One, the armed fort secured the control of fertile Doab region. Second, it greatly increased his visibility and power to the non-Muslims who gathered here for pilgrimage from distant places and who constituted the majority of his subjects.<ref>{{cite book|author=Kama Maclean|title=Pilgrimage and Power: The Kumbh Mela in Allahabad, 1765\u20131954|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MALacgnsroMC|year=2008|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-533894-2|pages=68\u201369}}</ref> Later, he declared Ilahabas as a capital of one of the twelve divisions (''subahs'').<ref name=Surendra>{{cite book|title=Subah of Allahabad under the great Mughals, 1580\u20131707|pages=25, 83\u201384|publisher=[[Jamia Millia Islamia]]|author=Surendra Nath Sinha|year=1974}}</ref> According to Richard Burn, the suffix \"\u2013bas\" was deemed to \"savouring too much of Hinduism\" and therefore the name was changed to ''Ilahabad'' by [[Shah Jahan]].<ref name=burnmint/> This evolved into the two variant colonial-era spellings of Ilahabad (Hindi: \u0907\u0932\u093e\u0939\u093e\u092c\u093e\u0926) and Allahabad.<ref name=burnmint/><ref name=\"Maclean2008p67\">{{cite book|author=Kama Maclean|title=Pilgrimage and Power: The Kumbh Mela in Allahabad, 1765\u20131954|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MALacgnsroMC|year=2008|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-533894-2|page=67}}</ref> According to Maclean, these variant spellings have a political basis, as \"Ilaha\u2013\" means \"the gods\" for Hindus, while Allah is the term for God to Muslims.<ref name=\"Maclean2008p67\"/>\n\nAfter [[Jahangir|Prince Salim]]'s coup against Akbar and a failed attempt to seize Agra's treasury, he came to Allahabad and seized its treasury while setting himself up as a virtually independent ruler.<ref name=Eraly>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=04ellRQx4nMC&printsec=frontcover&pg=PA223|title=Emperors of the Peacock Throne: The Saga of the Great Mughals|page=223|publisher=[[Penguin Books]] India|author=Abraham Eraly|year=2000|isbn=978-0-14-100143-2|author-link=Abraham Eraly}}</ref> In May 1602, he had his name read in [[Jumu'ah|Friday prayers]] and his name minted on coins in Allahabad. After reconciliation with Akbar, Salim returned to Allahabad, where he stayed before returning in 1604.<ref name=Richards>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HHyVh29gy4QC&pg=PA55|title=The Mughal Empire, Part 1, Volume 5|page=55|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|author=John F. Richards|year=1995|isbn=978-0-521-56603-2|access-date=5 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151128164007/https://books.google.com/books?id=HHyVh29gy4QC&pg=PA55|archive-date=28 November 2015|url-status = live|author-link=John F. Richards}}</ref> After capturing Jaunpur in 1624, [[Shah Jahan]] ordered the siege of Allahabad. The siege was however, lifted after [[Parviz Mirza|Parviz]] and [[Mahabat Khan]] came to assist the garrison.<ref>{{cite book|title=The History of India, 1000 A.D.-1707 A.D|author=Ashirbadi Lal Srivastava|publisher=Shiva Lal Agarwala|page=587|year=1964|author-link=Ashirbadi Lal Srivastava}}</ref> During the Mughal war of succession, the commandant of the fort who had joined [[Shah Shuja (Mughal prince)|Shah Shuja]] made an agreement with [[Aurangzeb]]'s officers and surrendered it to Khan Dauran on 12 January 1659.<ref>{{cite book|title=History of Bengal: The Reigns of Shah Jahan and Aurangzib|page=305|publisher=[[Institute of Bangladesh Studies]], [[University of Rajshahi]]|author=Abdul Karim|year=1995|author-link=Abdul Karim (historian)}}</ref>\n\n=== Nawabs of Awadh ===\n\nThe fort was coveted by the [[East India Company]] for the same reasons Akbar built it. British troops were first stationed at Allahabad fort in 1765 as part of the [[Treaty of Allahabad]] signed by Lord [[Robert Clive]], Mughal emperor [[Shah Alam II]], and [[Nawab of Awadh|Awadh's Nawab]] [[Shuja-ud-Daula]].<ref name=Kumbh62>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MALacgnsroMC&pg=PA62|title=Pilgrimage and Power: The Kumbh Mela in Allahabad, 1765\u20131954|page=62|publisher=Oxford University Press|author=Kama Maclean|year=2008|isbn=978-0-19-533894-2}}</ref> The combined forces of Bengal's Nawab [[Mir Qasim]], Shuja and Shah Alam were defeated by the English at [[Battle of Buxar|Buxar in October 1764]] and at Kora in May 1765. Alam, who was abandoned by Shuja after the defeats, surrendered to the English and was lodged at the fort, as they captured Allahabad, [[Benares]] and [[Chunar]] in his name. The territories of Allahabad and Kora were given to the emperor after the treaty was signed in 1765. He spent six years there and after the takeover of [[Delhi]] by the Marathas, left for his capital\nin 1771.<ref>{{cite book|title=A Comprehensive History of India: Volume Nine (1712\u20131772)|editor=A. C. Banerjee |editor2=D. K. Ghose|publisher=[[Indian History Congress]], [[Orient Longman]]|year=1978|pages=60\u201361}}</ref>\n\nUpon realising the Maratha intent of territorial encroachment, however, Shah Alam ordered his general [[Mirza Najaf Khan|Najaf Khan]] to drive them out. [[Tukoji Rao Holkar]] and [[Visaji Krushna Biniwale]] in return attacked Delhi and defeated his forces in 1772. The Marathas were granted an imperial ''[[deed|sanad]]'' for Kora and Allahabad. They turned their attention to Oudh to gain these two territories. Shuja was however, unwilling to give them up and made appeals to the English and the Marathas did not fare well at the battle of Ramghat.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=r4hHNz7T-AEC&pg=PA7|title=Anglo-Maratha relations during the administration of Warren Hastings 1772\u20131785, Volume 1|author=Sailendra Nath Sen|publisher=[[Popular Prakashan]]|year=1998|pages=7\u20138|isbn=9788171545780}}</ref> In August and September 1773, [[Warren Hastings]] met Shuja and concluded a treaty, under which Kora and Allahabad were ceded to the Nawab for a payment of 50 lakh rupees.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bXWiACEwPR8C&pg=PA27|title=An Advanced History of Modern India|author=Sailendra Nath Sen|publisher=[[Macmillan Publishers]]|year=2010|page=27|isbn=978-0-230-32885-3}}</ref>\n\n[[Saadat Ali Khan II]], after being made the Nawab by [[John Shore, 1st Baron Teignmouth|John Shore]], entered into a treaty with the Company and gave the fort to the British in 1798.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Kz1-mtazYqEC&pg=PA67|title=The Indian Princes and their States|author=Barbara N. Ramusack|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|year=2004|page=67|isbn=978-1-139-44908-3|author-link=Barbara Ramusack}}</ref> [[Richard Wellesley, 1st Marquess Wellesley|Lord Wellesley]] after threatening to annexe the entire Awadh, concluded a treaty with Saadat on abolishing the independent Awadhi army, imposing a larger subsidiary force and annexing [[Rohilkhand]], [[Gorakhpur, Uttar Pradesh|Gorakhpur]] and the Doab in 1801.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Kz1-mtazYqEC&pg=PA68|title=The Indian Princes and their States|author=Barbara N. Ramusack|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|year=2004|page=68|isbn=978-1-139-44908-3|author-link=Barbara Ramusack}}</ref>\n\n=== British rule ===\n[[File:Gandhi Patel 1940.jpg|thumb|[[Mahatma Gandhi]] at a January 1940 [[Congress Working Committee]] meeting with [[Vallabhbhai Patel]] and [[Vijaya Lakshmi Pandit]] at Anand Bhavan in Allahabad]]\n[[File:Au science faculty.jpg|thumb|[[Allahabad University]], established in 1887, is one of the oldest modern universities in the [[Indian subcontinent]].]]\nAcquired in 1801, Allahabad, aside from its importance as a pilgrimage centre, was a stepping stone to the agrarian track upcountry and the [[Grand Trunk Road]]. It also potentially  offered sizeable revenues to the Company. Initial [[Permanent Settlement|revenue settlements]] began in 1803.<ref>{{cite book|author=Hayden J. Bellenoit|title=The Formation of the Colonial State in India: Scribes, Paper and Taxes, 1760\u20131860|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9TElDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA115|accessdate=3 August 2012|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-134-49429-3|page=115|date=17 February 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180405090302/https://books.google.com/books?id=9TElDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA115|archive-date=5 April 2018|url-status = live}}</ref> Allahabad was a participant in the 1857 [[Indian Rebellion of 1857|Indian Mutiny]],<ref name=\"Menon2003\">{{cite book|author=Visalakshi Menon|title=From Movement To Government: The Congress in the United Provinces, 1937\u201342|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UO-OxAoL4YIC&pg=PA286|accessdate=25 September 2012|date=9 October 2003|publisher=SAGE Publications|isbn=978-0-7619-9620-0|page=286|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523052155/http://books.google.com/books?id=UO-OxAoL4YIC&pg=PA286|archivedate=23 May 2013}}</ref> when [[Maulvi Liaquat Ali]] unfurled the banner of revolt.<ref name=\"Bose2003\">{{cite book|author=Sugata Bose|title=Modern South Asia: History, Culture and Political Economy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PaKdsF8WzbcC&pg=PA74|accessdate=3 August 2012|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-0-415-30787-1|pages=74\u201377|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523075252/http://books.google.com/books?id=PaKdsF8WzbcC&pg=PA74|archivedate=23 May 2013|year=2004}}</ref> During the rebellion, Allahabad, with a number of European troops,<ref name=\"ThompsonGarratt1962\">{{cite book|author1=Edward John Thompson|author2=Geoffrey Theodore Garratt|title=Rise and Fulfilment of British rule in India|url=https://books.google.com/?id=6v4gAAAAMAAJ&q=%22European+troops%22|accessdate=16 August 2014|publisher=Central Book Depot|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171001092313/https://books.google.com/books?id=6v4gAAAAMAAJ&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22European+troops%22|archivedate=1 October 2017|year=1962}}</ref> was the scene of a massacre.<ref name=\"Pletcher 2010 128\" />\n\nAfter the mutiny, the British established a high court, a police headquarters and a public-service commission in Allahabad,<ref name=\"SinghSingh1995\">{{cite book|author1=Bhai Nahar Singh|author2=Bhai Kirpal Singh|title=Rebels Against the British Rule|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2lu7HatPQCoC&pg=PA290|accessdate=3 August 2012|publisher=Atlantic Publishers & Dist|isbn=978-81-7156-164-3|page=290|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523073151/http://books.google.com/books?id=2lu7HatPQCoC&pg=PA290|archivedate=23 May 2013|year=1995}}</ref> making the city an administrative centre.<ref name=administrative>{{cite web|title=Civil Disobedience|url=http://www.mkgandhi.org/civil_dis/dandi_march.htm|publisher=Gandhi Research Foundation|accessdate=25 September 2012|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120710130536/http://www.mkgandhi.org/civil_dis/dandi_march.htm|archivedate=10 July 2012}}</ref> They truncated the Delhi region of the state, merging it with [[Punjab, India|Punjab]] and moving the capital of the [[North-Western Provinces]] to Allahabad (where it remained for 20 years).<ref name=\"Ward2008\" /> In January 1858, [[Earl Canning]] departed [[Calcutta]] for Allahabad.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibiblio.org/britishraj/KayeMalleson4/bk12ch01.html|title=Progress of events in Eastern Bengal, Odisha, Bihar, Oudh, Rohilkhand and Rajputana|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|accessdate=21 March 2014|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130627043412/http://www.ibiblio.org/britishraj/KayeMalleson4/bk12ch01.html|archivedate=27 June 2013}}</ref> That year he read [[Queen Victoria#Empress of India|Queen Victoria's proclamation]], transferring control of India from the [[East India Company]] to the [[British Crown]] (beginning the [[British Raj]]), in [[Minto Park, Allahabad|Minto Park]].<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=FCG5hGZ-hJsC&pg=PA453&dq=minto+park+allahabad#v=onepage&q=minto%20park%20allahabad |title=Land and People of Indian States and Union Territories: In 36 Volumes. Uttar ... \u2013 Google Books |accessdate=26 May 2014 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181115155003/https://books.google.com/books?id=FCG5hGZ-hJsC&pg=PA453&dq=minto+park+allahabad#v=onepage&q=minto|archivedate=15 November 2018  |isbn=9788178353845 |last1=Bhatt |first1=Shankarlal C |year=2005 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bharatonline.com/uttar-pradesh/travel/allahabad/minto-park.html |title=Minto Park \u2013 Minto Park Allahabad \u2013 Allahabad Minto Park \u2013 Madan Mohan Malaviya Park Allahabad India |publisher=Bharatonline.com |date= |accessdate=26 May 2014 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140108123625/http://www.bharatonline.com/uttar-pradesh/travel/allahabad/minto-park.html |archivedate=8 January 2014  }}</ref> In 1877 the provinces of Agra and Awadh were merged to form the [[United Provinces of British India|United Provinces]],<ref name=\"Basham2008a\">{{cite book|author=A. L. Basham|title=The Wonder That Was India: A Survey of the Culture of the Indian Sub-Continent Before the Coming of the Muslims|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6OF-PwAACAAJ|accessdate=3 August 2012|date=30 November 2008|publisher=ACLS History E-Book Project|isbn=978-1-59740-599-7|page=696|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523061030/http://books.google.com/books?id=6OF-PwAACAAJ|archivedate=23 May 2013}}</ref> with Allahabad its capital until 1920.<ref name=\"Ward2008\" />\n\nThe 1888 session of the [[Indian National Congress]] was held in the city,<ref name=\"BhanaPandiri2007\">{{cite book|author1=Surendra Bhana|author2=Ananda M. Pandiri|author3=E. S. (FRW) Reddy|author4=Uma Dhupelia-Mesthrie|title=A Comprehensive, Annotated Bibliography on Mahatma Gandhi: Books And Pamphlets About Mahatma Gandhi|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_935ZKVzjW0C&pg=PA12|accessdate=3 August 2012|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-313-30217-6|pages=12\u201318|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523061521/http://books.google.com/books?id=_935ZKVzjW0C&pg=PA12|archivedate=23 May 2013|year=1995}}</ref> and by the turn of the 20th century, Allahabad was a revolutionary centre.<ref name=\"Committee1947\">{{cite book|author=All India Congress Committee|title=The Allahabad conference of the presidents and secretaries of provincial Congress committees|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TEU5AQAAIAAJ|accessdate=3 August 2012|publisher=Provincial Congress Committee Allahabad|page=57|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523075902/http://books.google.com/books?id=TEU5AQAAIAAJ|archivedate=23 May 2013|year=1947}}</ref> Nityanand Chatterji became a household name when he hurled a bomb at a European club.<ref name=Independence>{{cite web|title=Besides, locals still pride|url=http://zeenews.india.com/61Independenceday/story.aspx?aid=462215|work=[[Zee News]]|accessdate=3 August 2012|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523230338/http://zeenews.india.com/61Independenceday/story.aspx?aid=462215|archivedate=23 May 2013}}</ref> In [[Alfred Park]] in 1931, [[Chandrashekhar Azad]] died when surrounded by British police.<ref name=\"BhawanRana2005\">{{cite book | author=Bhawan Singh Rana | title=Chandra Shekhar Azad (An Immortal Revolutionary of India) | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sudu7qABntcC&pg=PA10 | accessdate=11 September 2012 | date=1 January 2005 | publisher=Diamond Pocket Books (P) Ltd. | isbn=978-81-288-0816-6 | page=10 |url-status = live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523064439/http://books.google.com/books?id=sudu7qABntcC&pg=PA10 | archivedate=23 May 2013 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> The [[Nehru\u2013Gandhi family|Nehru family]] homes, [[Anand Bhavan]] and [[Swaraj Bhavan]], were centres of Indian National Congress activity.<ref name=activities>{{cite web|title=The hub for freedom struggle|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-1196506911.html|work=High Beam Research|accessdate=28 September 2012|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130502190736/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-1196506911.html|archivedate=2 May 2013}}</ref> During the years before independence, Allahabad was home to thousands of [[Satyagraha|satyagrahis]] led by [[Purushottam Das Tandon]], [[Bishambhar Nath Pande]], [[Narayan Dutt Tiwari]] and others.<ref name=\"Desai1986\">{{cite book|author=Akshayakumar Ramanlal Desai|title=Violation of Democratic Rights in India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9i5sNMNh_uIC&pg=PA269|accessdate=25 September 2012|year=1986|publisher=Popular Prakashan|isbn=978-0-86132-130-8|page=269|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523052427/http://books.google.com/books?id=9i5sNMNh_uIC&pg=PA269|archivedate=23 May 2013}}</ref> The first seeds of the [[Pakistan]]i nation were sown in Allahabad:<ref name=\"Zakaria2004\">{{cite book|author=Rafiq Zakaria|title=The Man Who Divided India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2RdITXUpyVgC&pg=PA152|accessdate=3 August 2012|publisher=Popular Prakashan|isbn=978-81-7991-145-7|pages=152\u2013158|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523062504/http://books.google.com/books?id=2RdITXUpyVgC&pg=PA152|archivedate=23 May 2013|year=2004}}</ref> on 29 December 1930, [[Allama Muhammad Iqbal]]'s presidential address to the [[All-India Muslim League]] proposed a separate [[Muslim]] state for the Muslim-majority regions of India.<ref name=\"Singh2008\">{{cite book|author=Upinder Singh|title=A History of Ancient and Early Medieval India: From the Stone Age to the 12th Century|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GW5Gx0HSXKUC&pg=PA4|accessdate=3 August 2012|publisher=Pearson Education India|isbn=978-81-317-1677-9|pages=4\u20136|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523043139/http://books.google.com/books?id=GW5Gx0HSXKUC&pg=PA4|archivedate=23 May 2013|year=2008}}</ref>\n\n=== Post-independence ===\n\nAllahabad is known as the '''City of Prime Ministers''' because seven out of 15 prime ministers of India since independence have connections to Allahabad ([[Jawaharlal Nehru]], [[Lal Bahadur Shastri]], [[Indira Gandhi]], [[Rajiv Gandhi]], [[Gulzarilal Nanda]], [[Vishwanath Pratap Singh]] and [[Chandra Shekhar]]). All seven leaders were either born in Allahabad, were alumni of [[Allahabad University]] or were elected from an Allahabad constituency.<ref name=\"prime\" />\n\n== Geography ==\n\n=== Cityscape ===\nAllahabad's elevation is over 90&nbsp;m (295&nbsp;ft) above sea level. The old part of the city, at the south of Allahabad Junction Railway Station, consists of neighbourhoods like Chowk, [[Johnstongunj]], [[Dariyabad, Allahabad|Dariyabad]], [[Khuldabad, Allahabad|Khuldabad]] and many more.<ref>{{cite news |title=Uneasy calm prevails in old Allahabad areas |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-08-19/allahabad/33272775_1_flag-march-office-bearers-city-areas |newspaper=[[The Times of India]] |date=19 August 2012 |accessdate=13 September 2013}}</ref> In the north of the Railway Station, the new city consists of neighbourhoods like [[Lukergunj]], [[Civil Lines, Allahabad|Civil Lines]], [[Georgetown, Allahabad|Georgetown]], [[Tagoretown]], [[Allahpur]], [[Ashok Nagar, Allahabad|Ashok Nagar]], [[Mumfordgunj]], [[Bharadwaj Puram]] and others which are relatively new and were built during the [[British Raj|British rule]].<ref name=\"TGEIAAp57\">{{cite book |title=The Grove Encyclopedia of Islamic Art and Architecture, Volume 3 |author1=Jonathan M. Bloom |author2=Sheila Blai |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |year=2009 |isbn=978-8125013839 |page=57 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=un4WcfEASZwC&pg=PA57&dq=holy+trinity+church+allahabad#v=onepage&q=holy%20trinity%20church%20allahabad |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181115155217/https://books.google.com/books?id=un4WcfEASZwC&pg=PA57&dq=holy+trinity+church+allahabad#v=onepage&q=holy |archivedate=15 November 2018  }}</ref> [[Civil Lines, Allahabad|Civil Lines]] is the [[central business district]] of the city and is famous for its urban setting, [[gridiron plan]] roads<ref name=\"AHVLp14\">{{cite book|title=A Hand-book for Visitors to Lucknow: With Preliminary Notes on Allahabad and Cawnpore|author=Henry George Keene|publisher=J. Jetley|year=1875|isbn=978-8120615274|pages=14\u201315|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EfGFMpm8UbAC&pg=PA15|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180303145457/https://books.google.com/books?id=EfGFMpm8UbAC&pg=PA15|archivedate=3 March 2018|author-link=Henry George Keene (1826\u20131915)}}</ref> and high rise buildings. Built in 1857, it was the largest town-planning project carried out in India before the establishment of [[New Delhi]].<ref name=\"TGEIAAp57\" /><ref name=\"AHVLp14\" /> Allahabad has many buildings featuring [[Indo-Islamic architecture|Indo-Islamic]] and [[Indo-Saracenic architecture]]. Although several buildings from the colonial period have been declared \"heritage structures\", others are deteriorating.<ref name=\"Heritage\">{{cite web|title=Colonial period buildings in city |url=http://www.airallahabad.gov.in/inner.php?conf=1133 |work=All India Radio, Allahabad |accessdate=24 September 2012 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130615011052/http://www.airallahabad.gov.in/inner.php?conf=1133 |archivedate=15 June 2013 |df= }}</ref> Famous landmarks of the city are [[Allahabad Museum]], [[New Yamuna Bridge, Allahabad|New Yamuna Bridge]], [[Allahabad University]], [[Triveni Sangam]], [[All Saints Cathedral, Allahabad|All Saints Cathedral]], [[Anand Bhavan]], [[Alfred Park]] etc.<ref>{{Cite book | url=https://books.google.com/?id=oZ-Qa_jRVMYC&pg=PA140&dq=landmarks+of+allahabad#v=onepage&q=landmarks%20of%20allahabad | title=Middle Land, Middle Way: A Pilgrim's Guide to the Buddha's India| isbn=9789552401978| last1=Dhammika| first1=Shravasti| date=1 December 2008}}</ref>\n\n=== Triveni Sangam ===\n\n[[File:Triveni Sangam.JPG|right|thumb|300px|Pilgrims at the [[Triveni Sangam]], the confluence of the [[Ganges]] and the [[Yamuna]] rivers in Allahabad.]]\nIn Hindi, [[Triveni Sangam]] is a place where three rivers meet. The Allahabad Triveni Sangam is the meeting place of [[Ganges]], the [[Yamuna]] and invisible [[Sarasvati River|Saraswati River]], which according to Hindu legends, wells up from underground.<ref name=\"At the Three Rivers\">[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,798222,00.html At the Three Rivers] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130823175049/http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,798222,00.html |date=23 August 2013 }} ''[[TIME]]'', 23 February 1948.</ref><ref name=\"Triveni Sangam\">{{cite web | url=http://www.prayagdarshan.com/triveni-sangam.html | title=Triveni Sangam | accessdate=3 December 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208100930/http://www.prayagdarshan.com/triveni-sangam.html | archive-date=8 December 2015 |url-status = live| df=dmy-all }}</ref> A place of religious importance and the site for historic [[Prayag Kumbh Mela]] held every 12 years, over the years it has also been the site of immersion of ashes of several national leaders, including [[Mahatma Gandhi]] in 1948.<ref name=\"At the Three Rivers\" />\n\n==== Ghats ====\n\nThe main [[ghat]] in Allahabad is [[Saraswati Ghat]], on the banks of Yamuna. Stairs from three sides descend to the green water of the Yamuna. Above it is a park which is always covered with green grass. There are also facilities for boating here. There are also routes to reach Triveni Sangam by boat from here.<ref>{{cite web |author={{{names}}} |url=http://uttarpradesh.gov.in/en/details/sangam-and-the-ghats/39003900 |title=Sangam and the Ghats &#124; Allahabad &#124; UP Tourism |publisher=Uttarpradesh.gov.in |date= |accessdate=7 August 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180402225929/http://uttarpradesh.gov.in/en/details/sangam-and-the-ghats/39003900 |archive-date=2 April 2018 |url-status = live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/allahabad/work-for-renovating-ghats-of-allahabad-commemces/articleshow/56337486.cms|title=Work for renovating ghats of Allahabad commemces \u2013 Times of India|publisher=|access-date=7 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180613210721/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/allahabad/work-for-renovating-ghats-of-allahabad-commemces/articleshow/56337486.cms|archive-date=13 June 2018|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nApart from this, there are more than 100 raw ghats in Allahabad.\n\n=== Topography ===\n[[File:Yamuna river, Allahabad.jpg|thumb|alt=Large waterway, with small boats in the foreground and a long bridge in the background|The [[Yamuna]] in Allahabad during the rainy season]]\nAllahabad is in the southern part of Uttar Pradesh, at the confluence of the [[Ganges]] and Yamuna.<ref name=location>{{cite web|title=Location of city|url=http://geography.howstuffworks.com/asia/geography-of-allahabad.htm|website=[[HowStuffWorks]]|accessdate=3 August 2012|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120729030748/http://geography.howstuffworks.com/asia/geography-of-allahabad.htm|archivedate=29 July 2012|date=16 June 2008}}</ref><ref name=location001>{{cite web|title=Allahabad Location Guide|url=http://www.weather-forecast.com/locations/Allahabad|website=Weather-forecast|accessdate=3 August 2012|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120709010608/http://www.weather-forecast.com/locations/Allahabad|archivedate=9 July 2012}}</ref> The region was known in antiquity first as the Kuru, then as the Vats country.<ref name=\"Pletcher2010\">{{cite book|author=Kenneth Pletcher|title=The History of India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VsujRFvaHI8C&pg=PA63|accessdate=23 September 2012|date=15 August 2010|publisher=The Rosen Publishing Group|isbn=978-1-61530-122-5|page=63|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130620201000/http://books.google.com/books?id=VsujRFvaHI8C&pg=PA63|archivedate=20 June 2013}}</ref> To the southwest is [[Bundelkhand]], to the east and southeast is [[Baghelkhand]], to the north and northeast is [[Awadh]] and to the west is the lower [[doab]] (of which Allahabad is part).<ref name=location /> The city is divided by a railway line running east\u2013west.<ref name=junction>{{cite web|title=City or Locality infirmation|url=http://geography.howstuffworks.com/asia/geography-of-allahabad.htm|website=HowStuffWorks|accessdate=29 September 2012|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120729030748/http://geography.howstuffworks.com/asia/geography-of-allahabad.htm|archivedate=29 July 2012|date=16 June 2008}}</ref> South of the railway is the Old Chowk area, and the British-built [[Civil Lines, Allahabad|Civil Lines]] is north of it. Allahabad is well placed geographically and culturally.<ref name=\"Ganga-Yamuna Doab\">{{cite web|author=Deo Prakash Sharma|title=Archaeology of Lower Ganga-Yamuna Doab|url=http://www.vedicbooks.net/archaeology-lower-gangayamuna-doab-vols-p-997.html|work=Vedic Books|accessdate=24 September 2012|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120623050141/http://www.vedicbooks.net/archaeology-lower-gangayamuna-doab-vols-p-997.html|archivedate=23 June 2012}}</ref> Geographically part of the Ganga-Yamuna Doab (at the mouth of the Yamuna), culturally it is the terminus of the Indian west.<ref name=\"Sharma2006\">{{cite book|author=Deo Prakash Sharma|title=Archaeology of lower Ganga-Yamuna Doab (circa 1200 B.C. to 1200 A.D.)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EjtuAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=24 September 2012|date=1 January 2006|publisher=Bharatiya Kala Prakashan|isbn=978-81-8090-033-4|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523051350/http://books.google.com/books?id=EjtuAAAAMAAJ|archivedate=23 May 2013}}</ref>\nThe [[Indian Standard Time]] longitude (25.15\u00b0N 82.58\u00b0E) is near the city. According to a [[United Nations Development Programme]] report, Allahabad is in a \"low damage risk\" wind and cyclone zone.<ref name=hazardprofile>{{cite web|url=http://www.undp.org.in/dmweb/hazardprofile.pdf|title=Hazard profiles of Indian districts|accessdate=23 August 2006|website=National Capacity Building Project in Disaster Management |publisher=[[UNDP]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060519100611/http://www.undp.org.in/dmweb/hazardprofile.pdf|archivedate=19 May 2006}}</ref> In common with the rest of the [[doab]], its soil and water are primarily [[Alluvium|alluvial]].<ref name=Agricultural>{{cite web|title=Agricultural Productivity and Productivity Regions in Ganga-Yamuna Doab|url=http://www.connectjournals.com/file_full_text/314401H_02-10-21.pdf|publisher=Bharatiya Kala Prakashan|accessdate=24 September 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130502190727/http://www.connectjournals.com/file_full_text/314401H_02-10-21.pdf|archive-date=2 May 2013|url-status = live}}</ref> [[Pratapgarh, Uttar Pradesh|Pratapgarh]] is north of the city, [[Bhadohi]] is east, [[Rewa, Madhya Pradesh|Rewa]] is south, [[Chitrakoot district|Chitrakoot]] (earlier Banda) is west, and [[Kaushambi district|Kaushambi]], which was till recently a part of Allahabad, is North-West.\n\n=== Climate ===\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Allahabad Climate Graph.gif|left|thumb|alt=Climate timeline| Allahabad climate graph]] -->\nAllahabad has a [[humid subtropical climate]] common to cities in the plains of North India, designated ''Cwa'' in the [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]].<ref name=\"K\u00f6ppen\">{{cite web|title=Tropical Moist Climates|url=http://www.eoearth.org/article/Tropical_Moist_Climates_-_A_Climate_Type|publisher=The Encyclopedia of Earth|accessdate=29 September 2012|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120730025254/http://www.eoearth.org/article/Tropical_Moist_Climates_-_A_Climate_Type|archivedate=30 July 2012}}</ref> The annual mean temperature is {{Convert|26.1|C|F|abbr=on|1}}; monthly mean temperatures are {{Convert|18|-|29|C|F|abbr=on|0}}.<ref name=weatherbase>{{cite web|url=http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather.php3?s=57424&refer=&cityname=Allahabad-Uttar%20Pradesh-India|title=Weatherbase entry for Allahabad|publisher=Canty and Associates LLC|accessdate=3 August 2012|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130618023020/http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather.php3?s=57424&refer=&cityname=Allahabad-Uttar%20Pradesh-India|archivedate=18 June 2013}}</ref> Allahabad has three seasons: a hot, dry summer, a cool, dry winter and a hot, humid monsoon. Summer lasts from March to September with daily highs reaching up to 48&nbsp;\u00b0C in the dry summer (from March to May) and up to 40&nbsp;\u00b0C in the hot and extremely humid monsoon season (from June to September).<ref name=weatherbase /> The [[monsoon]] begins in June, and lasts till August; high humidity levels prevail well into September. Winter runs from December to February,<ref name=Season /> with temperatures rarely dropping to the freezing point. The daily average maximum temperature is about {{convert|22|C|abbr=on}} and the minimum about {{convert|9|C|abbr=on}}.<ref name=Forecast>{{cite web|title=Weather Report & Forecast |url=http://www.imd.gov.in/section/climate/allahabad2.htm |publisher=India Meteorological Department |accessdate=24 September 2012 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121031015105/http://www.imd.gov.in/section/climate/allahabad2.htm |archivedate=31 October 2012 |df= }}</ref> Allahabad never receives snow,<ref name=\"rainfall & snow\" /> but, experiences dense winter fog due to numerous wood fires, coal fires, and open burning of rubbish\u2014resulting in substantial traffic and travel delays.<ref name=Season>{{cite web|title=Allahabad Weather|url=http://www.mustseeindia.com/Allahabad-weather|publisher=India Weather|accessdate=25 September 2012|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090511155522/http://www.mustseeindia.com/Allahabad-weather|archivedate=11 May 2009}}</ref> Its highest recorded temperature is {{Convert|48|C|F|abbr=on|1}}, and its lowest is {{Convert|-2|C|F|abbr=on|0}}.<ref name=weatherbase /><ref name=climate>{{cite web|title=Allahabad climate|url=http://www.allahabad.climatemps.com/|publisher=Climate Maps India|accessdate=3 August 2012|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120712025748/http://www.allahabad.climatemps.com/|archivedate=12 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nRain from the Bay of Bengal or the Arabian Sea branches of the [[southwest monsoon]]<ref name=monsoontribune>{{cite news|last1=Khichar|first1=M. L.|last2=Niwas|first2=R.|title=Know your monsoon|newspaper=The Tribune|location=Chandigarh, India|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2003/20030714/agro.htm#2|accessdate=9 June 2007|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070618121810/http://www.tribuneindia.com/2003/20030714/agro.htm#2|archivedate=18 June 2007}}</ref> falls on Allahabad from June to September, supplying the city with most of its annual rainfall of {{Convert|1027|mm|in|abbr=on|0}}.<ref name=\"rainfall & snow\">{{cite web|title=Average monthly precipitation over the year (rainfall, snow)|url=http://www.weather-and-climate.com/average-monthly-precipitation-Rainfall,Allahabad,India|website=World Weather & Climate Information|accessdate=29 September 2012|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130512042542/http://www.weather-and-climate.com/average-monthly-precipitation-Rainfall,Allahabad,India|archivedate=12 May 2013}}</ref> The highest monthly rainfall total, {{convert|333|mm|in|abbr=on|0}}, occurs in August.<ref name=Tropical>{{cite web|title=Local weather report|url=http://www.tropmet.res.in/~lip/Publication/RR-pdf/RR-119.pdf|publisher=Indian Institute of Tropical Meteorology|accessdate=24 September 2012|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121028220223/http://www.tropmet.res.in/~lip/Publication/RR-pdf/RR-119.pdf|archivedate=28 October 2012}}</ref> The city receives 2,961&nbsp;hours of sunshine per year, with maximum [[Insolation|sunlight]] in May.<ref name=climate />\n\n{{Weather box\n|location = Allahabad\n|metric first = yes\n|single line = yes\n|Jan record high C = 32.8\n|Feb record high C = 36.3\n|Mar record high C = 42.5\n|Apr record high C = 45.8\n|May record high C = 48.4\n|Jun record high C = 48.8\n|Jul record high C = 45.6\n|Aug record high C = 42.7\n|Sep record high C = 39.6\n|Oct record high C = 40.6\n|Nov record high C = 36.0\n|Dec record high C = 31.9\n|year record high C = 48.8\n|Jan high C = 23.2\n|Feb high C = 26.7\n|Mar high C = 33.3\n|Apr high C = 39.4\n|May high C = 41.6\n|Jun high C = 39.6\n|Jul high C = 34.2\n|Aug high C = 32.9\n|Sep high C = 32.9\n|Oct high C = 32.9\n|Nov high C = 29.6\n|Dec high C = 24.8\n|year high C = 32.8\n|Jan low C = 8.9\n|Feb low C = 11.3\n|Mar low C = 16.2\n|Apr low C = 22.2\n|May low C = 26.3\n|Jun low C = 28.0\n|Jul low C = 26.5\n|Aug low C = 25.9\n|Sep low C = 24.7\n|Oct low C = 20.4\n|Nov low C = 14.3\n|Dec low C = 9.9\n|year low C = 19.4\n|Jan record low C = 1.1\n|Feb record low C = 1.1\n|Mar record low C = 7.2\n|Apr record low C = 12.7\n|May record low C = 17.2\n|Jun record low C = 18.7\n|Jul record low C = 18.8\n|Aug record low C = 21.1\n|Sep record low C = 18.3\n|Oct record low C = 11.7\n|Nov record low C = 5.6\n|Dec record low C = -0.7\n|year record low C = -0.7\n|Jan precipitation mm = 18.3\n|Feb precipitation mm = 15.2\n|Mar precipitation mm = 4.2\n|Apr precipitation mm = 5.9\n|May precipitation mm = 11.5\n|Jun precipitation mm = 126.6\n|Jul precipitation mm = 264.5\n|Aug precipitation mm = 279.0\n|Sep precipitation mm = 204.3\n|Oct precipitation mm = 27.4\n|Nov precipitation mm = 9.5\n|Dec precipitation mm = 12.1\n|year precipitation mm = 978.5\n| precipitation colour = green\n|Jan rain days = 1.8\n|Feb rain days = 1.4\n|Mar rain days = 0.4\n|Apr rain days = 0.7\n|May rain days = 1.1\n|Jun rain days = 5.4\n|Jul rain days = 12.7\n|Aug rain days = 12.1\n|Sep rain days = 9.1\n|Oct rain days = 1.8\n|Nov rain days = 0.6\n|Dec rain days = 0.7\n|year rain days = 47.9\n|Jan humidity = 69\n|Feb humidity = 57\n|Mar humidity = 39\n|Apr humidity = 29\n|May humidity = 33\n|Jun humidity = 50\n|Jul humidity = 77\n|Aug humidity = 81\n|Sep humidity = 78\n|Oct humidity = 67\n|Nov humidity = 61\n|Dec humidity = 68\n|year humidity = 59\n|Jan sun = 224.9\n|Feb sun = 244.2\n|Mar sun = 263.2\n|Apr sun = 274.1\n|May sun = 292.3\n|Jun sun = 206.4\n|Jul sun = 143.3\n|Aug sun = 180.6\n|Sep sun = 184.3\n|Oct sun = 259.7\n|Nov sun = 256.7\n|Dec sun = 244.0\n|year sun = 2773.7\n|source 1 = India Meteorological Department (record high and low up to 2010)<ref name=IMD>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.imd.gov.in/section/climate/extreme/allahabad2.htm\n |title       = Allahabad Climatological Table Period: 1971\u20132000\n |publisher   = [[India Meteorological Department]]\n |accessdate  = 15 April 2015\n |url-status = live\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20150416053039/http://www.imd.gov.in/section/climate/extreme/allahabad2.htm\n |archivedate = 16 April 2015\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref><ref name=IMD2>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.imdpune.gov.in/Temp_Extremes/histext2010.pdf\n |title=Ever recorded Maximum and minimum temperatures up to 2010\n |publisher=India Meteorological Department\n |accessdate=15 April 2015\n |url-status = dead\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140316064314/http://www.imdpune.gov.in/Temp_Extremes/histext2010.pdf\n |archivedate=16 March 2014\n \n}}</ref>\n|source 2 = NOAA (humidity, sun 1971\u20131990)<ref name= NOAA>{{cite web\n| url = ftp://ftp.atdd.noaa.gov/pub/GCOS/WMO-Normals/TABLES/REG_II/IN/42475.TXT\n| title = Allahabad Climate Normals 1971\u20131990\n| publisher = [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]]\n| accessdate = 15 April 2015}}</ref>\n|date= May 2012\n}}\n\n=== Biodiversity ===\n[[File:Indian Peacock Plumage.jpg|thumb|alt=Peacock displaying its tail feathers| A typical [[Indian peafowl|Indian peacock]], found in Allahabad on a large scale]]\nThe Ganga-Jamuna Doab, of which Allahabad is a part, is on the western [[Indus-Gangetic Plain]] region. The doab (including the [[Terai]]) is responsible for the city's unique flora and fauna.<ref name=\"KalaMuseum2000\">{{cite book|author1=Satish Chandra Kala|author2=Allahabad Municipal Museum|title=Flora and fauna in art: particularly in terracottas|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lP3VAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=4 August 2012|publisher=Allahabad Museum|page=86|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523073216/http://books.google.com/books?id=lP3VAAAAMAAJ|archivedate=23 May 2013|year=2000}}</ref><ref name=\"MisraVerma1992\">{{cite book|author1=Bal Krishna Misra|author2=Birendra Kumar Verma|title=Flora of Allahabad District, Uttar Pradesh, India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tBq1AAAAIAAJ|accessdate=4 August 2012|publisher=Bishen Singh Mahendra Pal Singh Publishing House|isbn=978-81-211-0077-9|page=530|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523062959/http://books.google.com/books?id=tBq1AAAAIAAJ|archivedate=23 May 2013|year=1992}}</ref> Since the arrival of humans, nearly half of the city's [[vertebrate]]s have become extinct. Others are [[endangered]] or have had their range severely reduced. Associated changes in habitat and the introduction of [[reptiles]], [[snakes]] and other [[mammals]] led to the extinction of bird species, including large birds such as [[eagle]]s.<ref name=\"KalaMuseum2000a\">{{cite book|author1=Satish Chandra Kala|author2=Allahabad Municipal Museum|title=Flora and fauna in art: particularly in terracottas|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lP3VAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=4 August 2012|publisher=Allahabad Museum|pages=22\u201338|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523073216/http://books.google.com/books?id=lP3VAAAAMAAJ|archivedate=23 May 2013|year=2000}}</ref> The [[Allahabad Museum]], one of four national museums in India, is documenting the flora and fauna of the Ganges and the Yamuna.<ref name=\"river belt\">{{cite news|title=Allahabad museum to document flora, fauna of Ganga-Yamuna belt|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/allahabad-museum-to-document-flora-fauna-of-gangayamuna-belt/854561/|accessdate=4 August 2012|newspaper=[[The Indian Express]]}}</ref>\nTo protect the rich aquatic biodiversity of river Ganges from escalating anthropogenic pressures, development of a [[Turtle]] sanctuary in Allahabad along with a River Biodiversity Park at [[Triveni Sangam|Sangam]] have been approved under Namami Gange programme.\n\nThe most common birds found in the city are [[Columbidae|doves]], [[Peafowl|peacocks]], [[junglefowl]], [[black partridge]], [[house sparrow]]s, [[songbirds]], [[blue jay]]s, [[parakeet]]s, [[quail]]s, [[bulbul]]s, and [[Knob-billed duck|comb ducks]].<ref name=\"S.k.agarwal\">{{cite book|author=S.K.Agarwal|title=Environment Biotechnology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0UeDTX6HEK8C&pg=PA61|accessdate=25 July 2012|publisher=APH Publishing|isbn=978-81-313-0294-1|pages=61\u2013|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523073400/http://books.google.com/books?id=0UeDTX6HEK8C&pg=PA61|archivedate=23 May 2013|year=1998}}</ref> Large numbers of Deer are found in the Trans Yamuna area of Allahabad. India's first conservation reserve for [[blackbuck]] is being created in Allahabad's [[Meja]] Forest Division. Other animals in the state include reptiles such as [[lizard]]s, [[cobra]]s, [[Bungarus|kraits]], and [[gharial]]s.<ref name=\"KalaMuseum2000\" /> During winter, large numbers of [[Siberia]]n birds are reported in the [[Triveni sangam|sangam]] and nearby wetlands.<ref name=\"Siberian birds\">{{cite news|last=Aarti|first=Aggarwal|title=Siberian birds flock Sangam, other wetlands|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2009-11-02/allahabad/28062841_1_migratory-birds-pond-heron-cattle-egret|accessdate=4 August 2012|newspaper=[[The Times of India]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130224054524/http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2009-11-02/allahabad/28062841_1_migratory-birds-pond-heron-cattle-egret|archive-date=24 February 2013|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\n== Demographics ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\nAllahabad population growth\n!Census\n!Total\n!%\u00b1\n|-\n!1981\n|642,200\n|25.2%\n|-\n![[1991 Census of India|1991]]\n|792,900\n|23.5%\n|-\n![[2001 census of India|2001]]\n|990,298\n|24.9%\n|-\n![[2011 census of India|2011]]\n|1,117,094\n|12.8%\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" |Source: [[Demographics of India|Census of India]]<ref name=\"censusdata2011\" /><ref name=\"censusindia1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.populstat.info/Asia/indiat.htm|title=Historical Census of India|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130217053707/http://www.populstat.info/Asia/indiat.htm|archivedate=17 February 2013|url-status = live}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=LclscNCTz9oC&pg=PA469&dq=allahabad+population+census+2001#v=onepage&q=allahabad%20population%20census%202001|title=The Far East and Australasia|publisher=Psychology Press|year=2002|isbn=978-1-85743-133-9|location=|page=469|accessdate=|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181115155544/https://books.google.com/books?id=LclscNCTz9oC&pg=PA469&dq=allahabad+population+census+2001#v=onepage&q=allahabad|archivedate=15 November 2018|url-status = live}}</ref>\n|}\n{{bar box\n|title=Religion in Allahabad<ref name=\"censusdata2011\">{{cite web\n |title       = Population by Religious Community\n |publisher   = Census of India\n |url         = http://www.census2011.co.in/census/city/138-allahabad.html\n |accessdate  = 27 April 2017\n |url-status = live\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20170505012949/http://www.census2011.co.in/census/city/138-allahabad.html\n |archivedate = 5 May 2017\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref>\n|titlebar=#Fcd116\n|left1=Religion\n|right1=Percent\n|float=right\n|bars=\n{{bar percent|[[Hinduism]]|orange|76.03}}\n{{bar percent|[[Islam]]|#009000|21.94}}\n{{bar percent|[[Christianity]]|#5218FA|0.68}}\n{{bar percent|[[Sikhism]]|#FFFF00|0.28}}\n{{bar percent|Others|#FF007F|1.07}}\n|caption=<small>Others include [[Buddhism]], [[Jainism]], other religions and no particular religion (0.63%)</small>\n}}\n\nThe [[2011 census of India|2011 census]] reported a population of 1,117,094 in Allahabad city.<ref name=census>{{cite web|title=Allahabad : Census 2011|url=http://www.census2011.co.in/census/city/138-allahabad.html|work=[[2011 census of India]]|accessdate=3 August 2012|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120702044839/http://www.census2011.co.in/census/city/138-allahabad.html|archivedate=2 July 2012}}</ref> Provisional data suggest a density of 1,086 people per km<sup>2</sup> in 2011 for [[Allahabad district]], compared to 901 in 2001.<ref name=census /> Natives of Uttar Pradesh form the majority of Allahabad's population. With regards to Houseless Census in Allahabad, total 5,672 families live on footpaths or without any roof cover, this is approximately 0.38% of the total population of Allahabad district. The sex ratio of Allahabad is 901 females per 1000 males and child sex ratio of is 893 girls per 1000 boys, lower than the national average.<ref name=census />\n\nHindi, the official state language, is the dominant language in Allahabad. Urdu and other languages are spoken by a sizeable minority. Hindus form the majority of Allahabad's population; Muslims compose a large minority. According to provisional results of the 2011 national census, [[Hinduism]] is majority religion in Allahabad city with 76.03% followers. [[Islam in Uttar Pradesh|Islam]] is the second most practiced religion in the city with approximately 21.94% following it. [[Christianity in Uttar Pradesh|Christianity]] is followed by 0.68%, [[Jainism in Uttar Pradesh|Jainism]] by 0.10%, [[Sikhism in India|Sikhism]] by 0.28% and [[Buddhism in India|Buddhism]] by 0.28%. Around 0.02% stated 'Other Religion', approximately 0.90% stated 'No Particular Religion'. Allahabad's [[Literacy in India|literacy rate]] at 86.50% is the highest in the region.<ref name=\"literacy rate\">{{cite news|title=Allahabad has highest literacy rate in region|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-04-15/allahabad/29421107_1_literacy-rate-female-population-males|accessdate=3 August 2012|newspaper=[[The Times of India]]|date=15 April 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130506182108/http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-04-15/allahabad/29421107_1_literacy-rate-female-population-males|archive-date=6 May 2013|url-status = live}}</ref> Male literacy is 90.21% and female literacy 82.17%.<ref name=literacy>{{cite web|title=Average literacy rate of Allahabad|url=http://www.census2011.co.in/questions/546/district-literacy/literacy-rate-of-allahabad-district-2011.html|work=[[Census of India]]|accessdate=3 August 2012|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120902045133/http://www.census2011.co.in/questions/546/district-literacy/literacy-rate-of-allahabad-district-2011.html|archivedate=2 September 2012}}</ref> Among [[Crime in India|35 major Indian cities]], Allahabad reported the highest rate of violations of special and local laws to the [[NCRB|National Crime Records Bureau]].<ref name=NCRB>{{cite web|url=http://ncrb.nic.in/CII2008/cii-2008/Snapshots.pdf |title=Snaphhots&nbsp;\u2013 2008 |publisher=[[National Crime Records Bureau]] |accessdate=5 May 2017 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110622023825/http://ncrb.nic.in/CII2008/cii-2008/Snapshots.pdf |archivedate=22 June 2011 |df= }}</ref>\n\n== Administration and politics ==\n\n=== General administration ===\n[[Allahabad division]], comprising four districts, is headed by the [[Divisional commissioner (India)|divisional commissioner]] of Allahabad, who is an [[Indian Administrative Service]] (IAS) officer of high seniority, the [[Divisional commissioner (India)|commissioner]] is the head of local government institutions (including [[Municipal corporations in India|municipal corporations]]) in the division, is in charge of infrastructure development in his division, and is also responsible for maintaining law and order in the division.<ref name=\":22\">{{cite web|url=http://up.gov.in/upconstitution.aspx|title=CONSTITUTIONAL SETUP|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Government of Uttar Pradesh]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170831000649/http://up.gov.in/upconstitution.aspx|archive-date=31 August 2017|url-status = live|access-date=30 August 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":42\">{{Cite book|title=Indian Administration|last=Maheshwari|first=S.R.|publisher=Orient Blackswan Private Ltd.|year=2000|isbn=9788125019886|location=[[New Delhi]]|pages=563\u2013572|edition=6th}}</ref><ref name=\":52\">{{Cite book|title=Revenue administration in India: A case study of Bihar|last=Singh|first=G.P.|publisher=Mittal Publications|year=1993|isbn=978-8170993810|location=[[Delhi]]|pages=26\u2013129}}</ref><ref name=\":62\">{{Cite book|title=Governance in India|last=Laxmikanth|first=M.|publisher=McGraw Hill Education|year=2014|isbn=978-9339204785|location=[[Noida]]|pages=5.1\u20135.2|edition=2nd}}</ref> The [[District collector (India)|district magistrate and collector]] of Allahabad reports to the [[Divisional commissioner (India)|divisional commissioner]]. The current commissioner is Ashish Kumar Goel.<ref name=\":02\">{{cite web|url=http://uphome.gov.in/DM-UP-Contact.htm|title=Contact Details Of Commissioners and District Magistrates Of U.P|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Department of Home (Uttar Pradesh)|Department of Home and Confidential]], [[Government of Uttar Pradesh]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170816061300/http://uphome.gov.in/DM-UP-Contact.htm|archive-date=16 August 2017|url-status = live|access-date=15 August 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":12\">{{cite web|url=http://niyuktionline.up.nic.in/DOCUMENTS/DMCFileCurrent.aspx|title=\u091c\u093f\u0932\u093e\u0927\u093f\u0915\u093e\u0930\u0940/\u092e\u0902\u0921\u0932\u093e\u092f\u0941\u0915\u094d\u0924 \u0915\u0940 \u0938\u0942\u091a\u0940|last=|first=|date=|website=Department of Appointments and Personnel, [[Government of Uttar Pradesh]]|language=Hindi|trans-title=List of District Magistrates and Divisional Commissioners|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110210045547/http://niyuktionline.up.nic.in/DOCUMENTS/DMCFileCurrent.aspx|archive-date=10 February 2011|url-status = dead|access-date=15 August 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://allahabad.nic.in/content/cug.pdf|title=C.U.G. Mobile No. of Allahabad Administration|last=|first=|date=|website=Allahabad District website|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170905060025/http://allahabad.nic.in/content/cug.pdf|archive-date=5 September 2017|url-status = dead|access-date=21 August 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|url=http://allahabad.nic.in/admin.html|title=DISTRICT ADMINISTRATION|last=|first=|date=|website=Allahabad District Website|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170905053739/http://allahabad.nic.in/admin.html|archive-date=5 September 2017|url-status = dead|access-date=5 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[Allahabad district]] administration is headed by the [[District collector (India)|district magistrate and collector]] (DM) of Allahabad, who is an [[Indian Administrative Service|IAS officer]]. The DM is in charge of property records and revenue collection for the central government and oversees the [[Elections in India|elections]] held in the district. The DM is also responsible for maintaining law and order in the district.<ref name=\":22\" /><ref name=\":43\">{{Cite book|title=Indian Administration|last=Maheshwari|first=S.R.|publisher=Orient Blackswan Private Ltd.|year=2000|isbn=9788125019886|location=[[New Delhi]]|pages=573\u2013597|edition=6th}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite book|title=Governance in India|last=Laxmikanth|first=M.|publisher=McGraw Hill Education|year=2014|isbn=978-9339204785|location=[[Noida]]|pages=6.1\u20136.6|edition=2nd}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|title=Revenue administration in India: A case study of Bihar|last=Singh|first=G.P.|publisher=Mittal Publications|year=1993|isbn=978-8170993810|location=[[Delhi]]|pages=50\u2013124}}</ref> The DM is assisted by a chief development officer; five additional district magistrates for finance/revenue, city, rural administration, land acquisition and civil supply; one chief revenue officer; one city magistrate; and three additional city magistrates.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> The district has eight [[Tehsil|teshils]] viz. Sadar, Soraon, Phulpur, Handia, Karchhana, Bara, Meja and Kuraon, each headed by a [[Sub-Divisional Magistrate (India)|sub-divisional magistrate]].<ref name=\":0\" /> The current DM of Allahabad is [[Suhas Lalinakere Yathiraj|Suhas L. Y.]]<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":12\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":4\" />\n\n=== Police administration ===\n\nAllahabad district comes under the Allahabad Police Zone and Allahabad Police Range, Allahabad Zone is headed by an [[Additional director general of police|additional director general]]-rank [[Indian Police Service]] (IPS) officer, and the Allahabad Range is headed [[Inspector-general of police#India|inspector general]]-rank IPS officer. The current ADG, Allahabad Zone is Satya Narain Sabat,<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=https://uppolice.gov.in/frmOfficials.aspx?zoneallhd&cd=MwAzADgA|title=Officers posted at Allahabad Zone|website=[[Uttar Pradesh Police]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180808012606/https://uppolice.gov.in/frmOfficials.aspx?zoneallhd&cd=MwAzADgA|archive-date=8 August 2018|url-status = live|access-date=17 October 2018}}</ref> and IG, Allahabad Range is Mohit Aggarwal.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://uppolice.gov.in/frmOfficials.aspx?rangeallhd&cd=MwA0ADUA|title=Officers posted at Allahabad Range|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Uttar Pradesh Police]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170821174826/https://uppolice.gov.in/frmOfficials.aspx?rangeallhd&cd=MwA0ADUA|archive-date=21 August 2017|url-status = live|access-date=16 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe district police is headed by a [[Superintendent of police (India)|senior superintendent of police]] (SSP), who is an [[Indian Police Service|IPS]] officer, and is assisted by eight [[Superintendent of police (India)|superintendents of police]] or [[Additional superintendent of police|additional superintendents of police]] for city, Gangapar, Yamunapar, crime, traffic, control room, protocol and security, either from the IPS or the [[Provincial Police Service (Uttar Pradesh)|Provincial Police Service]].<ref name=\":32\">{{cite web|url=https://uppolice.gov.in/frmOfficials.aspx?allahabad|title=Officers posted at ALLAHABAD|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Uttar Pradesh Police]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170821180136/https://uppolice.gov.in/frmOfficials.aspx?allahabad|archive-date=21 August 2017|url-status = live|access-date=16 August 2017}}</ref> Each of the several police circles is headed by a circle officer (CO) in the rank of [[Deputy superintendent of police#India|deputy superintendent of police]].<ref name=\":32\" /> The current SSP of Allahabad is Nitin Tiwari.<ref name=\":32\" />\n\n=== Infrastructure and civic administration ===\n\nThe development of infrastructure in the city is overseen by the Allahabad Development Authority (ADA), which comes under the [[Department of Housing and Urban Planning]] of [[Government of Uttar Pradesh|Uttar Pradesh government]]. The [[Divisional commissioner (India)|divisional commissioner]] of Allahabad acts as the ''[[ex-officio]]'' chairperson of ADA, whereas a vice chairperson, a government-appointed [[Indian Administrative Service|IAS officer]], looks after the daily matters of the authority.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://adaallahabad.in/structure.php|title=Structure|last=|first=|date=|website=Allahabad Development Authority|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170915023108/http://adaallahabad.in/structure.php|archive-date=15 September 2017|url-status = live|access-date=14 September 2017}}</ref> The current chairperson of ADA is Bhanu Chandra Goswami.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://adaallahabad.in/inner.php?conf=contact|title=CONTACT INFORMATION|last=|first=|date=|website=Allahabad Development Authority|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929133127/http://adaallahabad.in/inner.php?conf=contact|archive-date=29 September 2017|url-status = live|access-date=14 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Allahabad Nagar Nigam, also called [[Allahabad Municipal Corporation]], oversees the city's civic infrastructure. The corporation originated in 1864, when the Lucknow Municipal Act was passed by the [[Government of India]].<ref name=\"nagar nigam2\">{{cite web|url=http://allahabadnagarnigam.in/english/about_nagarnigam_allahabad.htm|title=Nagar Nigam \u2013 From the casement of history|publisher=Allahabad Nagar Nigam|accessdate=3 August 2012|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120702114727/http://allahabadnagarnigam.in/english/about_nagarnigam_allahabad.htm|archivedate=2 July 2012}}</ref> Allahabad is divided into 80 wards, with one member (or corporator) elected from each ward to form the municipal committee. The head of the corporation is the mayor, but, the executive and administration of the corporation are the responsibility of the municipal commissioner, who is a [[Government of Uttar Pradesh|Uttar Pradesh government]]-appointed [[Provincial Civil Service (Uttar Pradesh)|Provincial Civil Service]] officer of high seniority. The current mayor of Allahabad is [[Abhilasha Gupta]], whereas the current municipal commissioner is Avinash Singh.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://niyuktionline.up.nic.in/pcs/pcs_hod.aspx|title=PCS OFFICERS (Posted as HOD)|last=|first=|date=|website=Department of Appointment and Personnel, [[Government of Uttar Pradesh]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170821130444/http://niyuktionline.up.nic.in/pcs/pcs_hod.aspx|archive-date=21 August 2017|url-status = dead|access-date=21 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://allahabadmc.gov.in/documentslist/cug.pdf|title=Allahabad Municipal Corporation \u2014> Contact Details of CUG Mobile No.List|website=[[Allahabad Municipal Corporation]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180818063638/http://allahabadmc.gov.in/documentslist/cug.pdf|archive-date=18 August 2018|url-status = live|access-date=17 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==== Smart City ====\nA [[memorandum of understanding]] was signed on 25 January 2015 between the [[United States Trade and Development Agency]] (USTDA) and the [[Government of Uttar Pradesh]] for developing Allahabad as a [[smart city]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/india-us-sign-three-mous-on-smart-cities/article6821106.ece|title=India, U.S. sign three MoUs on smart cities|date=25 January 2015|newspaper=The Hindu|accessdate=28 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171028154058/http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/india-us-sign-three-mous-on-smart-cities/article6821106.ece|archive-date=28 October 2017|url-status = live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://activeindiatv.com/editorials/12807-now-world-bank-wants-to-turn-allahabad-into-a-smart-city-this-may-be-possible-if-plans-are-not-locally-executed|title=Now World Bank wants to turn Allahabad into a Smart City : THIS MAY BE POSSIBLE IF PLANS ARE NOT LOCALLY EXECUTED|author=|date=28 September 2013|publisher=Activeindiatv.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006132139/http://activeindiatv.com/editorials/12807-now-world-bank-wants-to-turn-allahabad-into-a-smart-city-this-may-be-possible-if-plans-are-not-locally-executed|archivedate=6 October 2014|url-status = live|accessdate=28 August 2015}}</ref> The pact came into existence after the bilateral meeting between the Indian Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] and the US President [[Barack Obama]] in October 2014, wherein it was announced that the US would assist India in developing three smart cities, Allahabad, [[Ajmer]] and [[Visakhapatnam]], in a boost to India's 100 smart city programme.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Modi-Obama-meet-US-to-help-India-develop-three-smart-cities/articleshow/43981483.cms|title=Modi-Obama meet: US to help India develop three smart cities|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|date=1 October 2014|newspaper=[[The Times of India]]|accessdate=1 October 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141002075549/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Modi-Obama-meet-US-to-help-India-develop-three-smart-cities/articleshow/43981483.cms|archivedate=2 October 2014|url-status = live|location=Washington}}</ref> On 27 August 2015 the official list of 98 cities to be developed as smart cities, including Allahabad, was announced by the [[Government of India]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Full-list-of-98-smart-cities/articleshow/48694723.cms|title=Full list of 98 smart cities |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150828210841/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Full-list-of-98-smart-cities/articleshow/48694723.cms|archivedate=28 August 2015|url-status = live|accessdate=29 August 2015}}</ref> Allahabad Task Force was set up by the [[Ministry of Urban Development|Minister of Urban Development]] [[Venkaiah Naidu]] which consists of  the [[Divisional commissioner (India)|divisional commissioner]] as chairperson, secretaries of housing and urban planning and urban development in [[Government of Uttar Pradesh]], the [[District collector (India)|district magistrate and collector]], the vice-chairperson of Allahabad Development Authority and the mayor in addition to the [[Additional secretary to the Government of India|Additional Secretary]] ([[Ministry of Housing and Urban Affairs|Urban Development]]) in the [[Ministry of Housing and Urban Affairs]] and representatives of the [[Ministry of External Affairs (India)|Ministry of External Affairs]] and the USTDA.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pib.nic.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=116383|title=Smart City Task Forces for Ajmer, Allahabad and Visakhapatnam set up |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150921011341/http://pib.nic.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=116383|archivedate=21 September 2015|url-status = live|accessdate=29 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150130145832/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2015-01-27/news/58508253_1_smart-cities-task-force-three-cities |url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2015-01-27/news/58508253_1_smart-cities-task-force-three-cities |archivedate=30 January 2015 |title=India, US to set up task force to develop three Smart Cities |work=Economic Times |date=27 January 2015}}</ref> The project is being assisted by the [[U.S.-India Business Council]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/allahabad/Smart-transport-for-a-smart-city/articleshow/46131377.cms|title=Smart transport for a 'smart city'|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150216074159/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/allahabad/Smart-transport-for-a-smart-city/articleshow/46131377.cms|archivedate=16 February 2015|url-status = live|accessdate=29 August 2015}}</ref>[[File:Allahabad high court.jpg|alt=Large building behind landscaped grounds|thumb|The [[Allahabad High Court]] is India's fourth-oldest high court]]\n\n=== Politics ===\nAllahabad is the seat of [[Allahabad High Court]], the highest judicial body in the state of Uttar Pradesh. The city is known as the \"Prime Minister Capital of India\", since, seven of fifteen [[Prime Minister of India|Indian prime ministers]] have been from the district.<ref name=\"prime\" /> Allahabad is administered by several [[Government agency|government agencies]]. As the seat of the [[Government of Uttar Pradesh]], Allahabad is home to local governing agencies and the [[Uttar Pradesh Legislative Assembly]] (housed in the [[Allahabad High Court]] building).<ref name=\"Checklist\">{{cite web|url=http://jnnurm.nic.in/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/Allahabad_MoA1.pdf|title='Urban Reforms Agenda' under JNNURM|work=[[Jawaharlal Nehru National Urban Renewal Mission]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121031123742/http://jnnurm.nic.in/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/Allahabad_MoA1.pdf|archivedate=31 October 2012|url-status = dead|accessdate=5 August 2012|df=}}</ref> The Allahabad district elects two representatives to the [[Parliament of India|Indian parliament]]'s lower house, the [[Lok Sabha]], and 12 representatives to the [[Uttar Pradesh Legislative Assembly]].<ref name=\"Legislative\">{{cite web|title=Bicameral legislature of the Indian state of Uttar Pradesh |url=http://www.uplegassembly.nic.in/16th%20UP%20legislative%20Assembly-Notification.html |publisher=[[Uttar Pradesh Legislative Assembly]] |accessdate=5 August 2012 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121102214703/http://www.uplegassembly.nic.in/16th%20UP%20legislative%20Assembly-Notification.html |archivedate=2 November 2012 |df= }}</ref>\n\n=== Central government offices/organisations ===\n\nAllahabad houses various central government offices and organisations, such as-\n\n'''[[Ministry of Home Affairs]]'''\n* Headquarters of [[Central Zonal Council]]\n* [[Rapid Action Force]] (101 Battalion).\n* [[Indo-Tibetan Border Police]], (Training Institute).\n'''[[Ministry of Minority Affairs]]'''\n* Special officer for Linguistic Minorities. (Regional Headquarters).\n'''[[Ministry of Defence (India)]]'''\n* Headquarters of [[Central Air Command]].\n* [[Services Selection Board]], (East Centre).\n'''[[Ministry of Civil Aviation (India)]]'''\n* Civil Aviation Training College.\n'''[[Ministry of Railways (India)]]'''\n* Headquarters of [[North Central Railway Zone]].\n* Headquarters of [[Central Organisation for Railway Electrification]].\n* [[Railway Recruitment Control Board]], (Selection Centre).\n'''[[Ministry of Finance (India)]]'''\n* Headquarters of Accountants General, Uttar Pradesh.\n'''[[Ministry of Human Resource Development]]'''\n* [[Central Board of Secondary Education]], (Regional office).\n'''[[Ministry of Environment, Forest and Climate Change]]'''\n* [[Botanical Survey of India]] (Central  Regional Centre, Allahabad).\n* [[Centre for Social Forestry and Eco-Rehabilitation]].\n'''[[Ministry of Science and Technology (India)]]'''\n* [[Harish Chandra Research Institute]].\n* [[Indian Institute of Geomagnetism]] (Regional Center).\n* [[National Academy of Sciences, India]].\n\n{{See also|Neighborhoods in Allahabad}}\n\n== Economy ==\nOverall Allahabad has a very stable and diverse economy comprising various sectors such as State and Central government offices, education and research institutions, real estate, retail, banking, tourism and hospitality, agriculture-based industries, railways, transport and logistics, miscellaneous service sectors, and manufacturing. [[Disposable household and per capita income|Average household income]] of the city is US$2,299.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mudraa.com/trading/52752/0/key-metros-with-high-per-capita-income.html |title=Key Metros with high per capita income |accessdate=28 August 2015 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305122308/http://www.mudraa.com/trading/52752/0/key-metros-with-high-per-capita-income.html |archivedate=5 March 2016  }}</ref>\n\nThe construction sector is a major part of Allahabad's economy.<ref name=\"Industrial units\">{{cite web|title=Industrial units in allahabad|url=http://uppcb.com/inventory2010/7_allahabad.pdf|publisher=U.P Pollution Control Board|accessdate=4 August 2012|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120128031316/http://uppcb.com/inventory2010/7_allahabad.pdf|archivedate=28 January 2012}}</ref> Secondary manufacturers and services may be registered or unregistered;<ref name=development>{{cite web|last=organizations|first=Significant industrial|title=Large scale industries|url=http://www.exploreallahabad.com/economy-of-allahabad|publisher=Explore Allahabad Press|accessdate=12 January 2014|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140112171203/http://www.exploreallahabad.com/economy-of-allahabad|archivedate=12 January 2014}}</ref> according to the third All India Census for Small Scale Industries, there are more than 10,000 unregistered small-scale industries in the city.<ref name=\"Small scale Industries\">{{cite web|title=Summary results of third census|url=http://dcmsme.gov.in/ssiindia/census/sumryres.htm|work=All India Census of Small scale Industries|accessdate=4 August 2012|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120505002618/http://dcmsme.gov.in/ssiindia/census/sumryres.htm|archivedate=5 May 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Industries2004\">{{cite book|author=Office of the Development Commissioner (Small Scale Industries)|title=Final results, third all India census of small scale industries, 2001\u20132002|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LRHtAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=4 August 2012|publisher=Development Commissioner, Ministry of Small Scale Industries, Govt. of India|isbn=978-81-88905-17-1|pages=13\u201318|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523075248/http://books.google.com/books?id=LRHtAAAAMAAJ|archivedate=23 May 2013|year=2004}}</ref> An integrated industrial township has been proposed for {{convert|1200|acre|ha}} in Allahabad by the [[Dedicated Freight Corridor Corporation of India]].<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Eastern dedicated freight corridor to get rs 42,000 cr investments to UP |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2013-12-17/lucknow/45293731_1_eastern-dedicated-freight-corridor-edfc-amritsar-delhi-kolkata-industrial-corridor |newspaper=The [[Times of India]] |location= |publisher=Swati Mathur |date=17 December 2013 |accessdate= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140108140422/http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2013-12-17/lucknow/45293731_1_eastern-dedicated-freight-corridor-edfc-amritsar-delhi-kolkata-industrial-corridor |archive-date=8 January 2014 |url-status = live }}</ref>\n\nThe city is also home to glass and [[wire]]-based industry.<ref name=industries>{{cite web|title=Minor industries|url=http://www.rediff.com/business/slide-show/slide-show-1-cities-that-will-shape-indias-future/20111012.htm|website=Rediff.com|accessdate=25 September 2012|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121010050631/http://www.rediff.com/business/slide-show/slide-show-1-cities-that-will-shape-indias-future/20111012.htm|archivedate=10 October 2012}}</ref> The main industrial areas of Allahabad are [[Naini]] and [[Phulpur, Allahabad|Phulpur]], where several [[Public sector|public]] and [[private sector]] companies have offices and factories.<ref name=\"Industries1993\">{{cite book|author=Office of the Development Commissioner (Small Scale Industries)|title=Report on the second all-India census of small scale industrial units|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9yLtAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=4 August 2012|publisher=Development Commissioner, Small Scale Industries, Ministry of Industry, Govt. of India|page=72|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523061131/http://books.google.com/books?id=9yLtAAAAMAAJ|archivedate=23 May 2013|year=1993}}</ref> [[BPCL|Bharat Petroleum Corporation Limited]], India's largest oil company (which is state-owned), is constructing a seven-million-tonnes-per-annum (MTPA) capacity refinery in Lohgara with an investment estimated at \u20b962&nbsp;billion.<ref name=GDP>{{cite news|title=GDP & per capita income of Allahabad|url=http://planningcommission.nic.in/plans/stateplan/upsdr/vol-1/chap%201.pdf|accessdate=4 August 2012|newspaper=Planning Commission of India|date=8 March 2010|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120904083127/http://planningcommission.nic.in/plans/stateplan/upsdr/vol-1/chap%201.pdf|archivedate=4 September 2012}}</ref> [[Allahabad Bank]], which began operations in 1865,<ref name=\"Small scale Industries\" /> [[Bharat Pumps & Compressors]] and A. H. Wheeler and Company have their headquarters in the city. Major companies in the city are [[Reliance Industries]], [[ITI Limited]], [[BPCL]], Dey's Medical, [[Food Corporation of India]], Raymond Synthetics, Triveni Sheet Glass, Triveni Electroplast, EMC Power Ltd, [[Steel Authority of India]], [[HCL Technologies]], [[Indian Farmers Fertiliser Cooperative]] (IFFCO), Vibgyor Laboratories, Geep Industries, Hindustan Cable, Indian Oil Corporation Ltd, Baidyanath Ayurved, Hindustan Laboratories.<ref name=Companies>{{cite web|last=of the city.|first=accelerating the development|title=significant industrial organizations|url=http://www.exploreallahabad.com/economy-of-allahabad|publisher=Explore Allahabad Press|accessdate=12 January 2014|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140112171203/http://www.exploreallahabad.com/economy-of-allahabad|archivedate=12 January 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Popular industries\">{{cite web|title=List of Companies|url=http://www.mca.gov.in/Ministry/pdf/Section25_Companies_6nov2008.pdf|publisher=Ministry of Corporate Affairs|accessdate=25 September 2012|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120916030108/http://www.mca.gov.in/Ministry/pdf/Section25_Companies_6nov2008.pdf|archivedate=16 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Industries that play a vital role in the economy of the district|url=http://www.mapsofindia.com/maps/uttarpradesh/districts/allahabad.htm|website=Maps of India|accessdate=24 September 2012|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120909031533/http://www.mapsofindia.com/maps/uttarpradesh/districts/allahabad.htm|archivedate=9 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe primary economic sectors of the district are tourism, fishing and agriculture, and the city is a hub for India's agricultural industry.<ref name=\"Agricultural industries\">{{cite web|title=Agricultural industries in Allahabad|url=http://planningcommission.nic.in/plans/stateplan/upsdr/vol-2/Chap_b1.pdf|publisher=Planning commission of India|accessdate=26 September 2012|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130410203237/http://planningcommission.nic.in/plans/stateplan/upsdr/vol-2/Chap_b1.pdf|archivedate=10 April 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Main Industries\">{{cite web|title=Key industries of Allahabad|url=http://www.districtsofindia.com/uttarpradesh/allahabad/industriesandmining/index.aspx|publisher=District Level Information of Allahabad (Uttar Pradesh)|accessdate=26 September 2012|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140108134546/http://www.districtsofindia.com/uttarpradesh/allahabad/industriesandmining/index.aspx|archivedate=8 January 2014}}</ref> in the case of agriculture crops, Paddy has the largest share followed by Bajra, Arhar, Urd and Moong, in declining order during the Kharif season. In Rabi, Wheat is predominantally followed by pulses and oilseed. Among oilseed crops, Mustard has very less area under pure farming and is grown mainly as a mixed crop. Linseed dominates the oilseed scenario of the district and is mainly grown in Jamunapar area. in the case of pulses, gram has the largest area followed by pea and lentil (''masoor''). There is fairly good acreage under barley.<ref name=agriculture>{{cite web|title=Agricultureinallahabad |url=http://zpdk.org.in/sites/default/files/districtprofile(2-2-10).pdf |website=zpdk.org.in |accessdate=5 November 2014 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150226170806/http://zpdk.org.in/sites/default/files/districtprofile%282-2-10%29.pdf |archivedate=26 February 2015 }}</ref>\n\n== Transportation and utilities ==\n[[File:On the banks of New Yamuna bridge, Allahabad.jpg|thumb|left|alt=Long bridge, with its lights reflected in the water|[[New Yamuna Bridge, Allahabad|New Yamuna Bridge]] in Allahabad]]\n\n=== Air transport ===\nAllahabad is served by [[Allahabad Airport]] {{Airport codes|IXD|VIAL}}, which began operations in February 1966. The airport is {{convert|12|km}} from the city centre and lies in Bamrauli, Allahabad. As of now, Allahabad is connected to six cities by flight, where [[Air India]]'s regional arm [[Alliance Air (India)|Alliance Air]] connects Allahabad to [[Delhi]] and [[Indigo]] connects it to [[Bangalore]].<ref name=\"Institute1937\">{{cite book|author=Allahabad Agricultural Institute|title=The Allahabad aviation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4oAsAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=3 August 2012|volume=11|publisher=Allahabad Agricultural Institute, Uttar Pradesh|page=44|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523044352/http://books.google.com/books?id=4oAsAQAAIAAJ|archivedate=23 May 2013|year=1937}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Ashwini Phadnis |url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/industry-and-economy/logistics/air-india-to-begin-new-services-from-sept-9/article5044189.ece |title=Air India to begin new services from Sept 9 &#124; Business Line |newspaper=The Hindu Business Line |date=21 August 2013 |accessdate=26 May 2014 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140109185203/http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/industry-and-economy/logistics/air-india-to-begin-new-services-from-sept-9/article5044189.ece |archivedate=9 January 2014  }}</ref> The nearest [[international airport]]s are in [[Varanasi]] and [[Lucknow]].<ref name=transport>{{cite web|title=Profile of UP State Unit|url=http://nicsu.up.nic.in/profile.htm|work=National Informatics Centre|accessdate=3 August 2012|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120512131658/http://nicsu.up.nic.in/profile.htm|archivedate=12 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Railways ===\n[[Allahabad Junction]] is one of the main railway junctions in northern India and headquarters of the [[North Central Railway Zone]].<ref>{{cite web|title=North Central Railways present network|url=http://www.ncr.indianrailways.gov.in/view_section.jsp?lang=0&id=0,1,261|work=[[North Central Railways]]|accessdate=3 August 2012|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120707094035/http://www.ncr.indianrailways.gov.in/view_section.jsp?lang=0&id=0,1,261|archivedate=7 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nAllahabad has following nine railway stations in its city limits :<ref name=\"Railways (India)\">{{cite book|title=Railways (India): return to an order from any correspondence|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yyVDAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA30|accessdate=3 August 2012|year=1853|pages=30\u201344|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523072631/http://books.google.com/books?id=yyVDAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA30|archivedate=23 May 2013}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"background:#fff;\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#ffd750;\"| Station Name\n! style=\"background:#ffd750;\"| Station Code\n! style=\"background:#ffd750;\"| Railway Zone\n! style=\"background:#ffd750;\"| Number of Platforms\n|-\n| [[Allahabad Junction|Prayagraj Junction]]<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/railway-stations-uttar-pradesh-prayagraj-renamed-1648577-2020-02-21|title=4 railway stations in Uttar Pradesh's Prayagraj get new names|last=PrayagrajFebruary 21|first=Asian News International|last2=February 21|first2=2020UPDATED:|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20|last3=Ist|first3=2020 10:07}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| PRYJ\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[North Central Railway zone|North Central Railway]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 10\n|-\n| [[Prayag Junction railway station|Prayag Junction]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | PRG\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[Northern Railway zone|Northern Railway]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 3\n|-\n|[[Allahabad City railway station|Prayagraj Rambag]]<ref name=\":3\" />\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | PRRB\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |[[North Eastern Railway zone|North Eastern Railway]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 5\n|-\n| Prayagraj Sangam<ref name=\":3\" />\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | PYGS\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |[[Northern Railway zone|Northern Railway]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 5\n|-\n|[[Allahabad Chheoki Junction railway station|Prayagraj Cheoki]]<ref name=\":3\" />\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | PCOI\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |[[North Central Railway zone|North Central Railway]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 3\n|-\n| [[Naini]] Railway Station\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| NYN\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[North Central Railway zone|North Central Railway]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 4\n|-\n| [[Subedarganj railway station|Subedarganj Railway Station]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| SFG\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[North Central Railway zone|North Central Railway]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 3\n|-\n| [[Phaphamau]] Railway Station\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| PFM\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Northern Railway zone|Northern Railway]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 3\n|-\n| [[Jhusi]] Railway Station\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| JI\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[North Eastern Railway zone|North Eastern Railway]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 3\n|-\n|}\nThe city is connected to most other Uttar Pradesh cities and major Indian cities such as [[Kolkata]], [[New Delhi]], [[Hyderabad, India|Hyderabad]], [[Patna]], [[Mumbai]], [[Visakhapatnam]], [[Chennai]], [[Bangalore]], [[Guwahati]], [[Thiruvananthapuram]], [[Pune]], [[Bhopal]], [[Kanpur]], [[Lucknow]] and [[Jaipur]].<ref name=\"The Railway magazine\">{{cite book|title=The Railway magazine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BCRWAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=3 August 2012|volume=124|publisher=IPC Business Press|page=178|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523060834/http://books.google.com/books?id=BCRWAAAAMAAJ|archivedate=23 May 2013|year=1978}}</ref>\n\n=== Roads ===\nBuses operated by [[Uttar Pradesh State Road Transport Corporation]] and Allahabad City Transport Service are an important means of public transport for travelling to various parts of the city, state and outskirts.<ref name=\"Bus services\">{{cite web|title=Important Service |url=http://www.upsrtc.com/allahabad/ald_dep.htm |work=[[Uttar Pradesh State Road Transport Corporation]] |accessdate=3 August 2012 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203055516/http://www.upsrtc.com/allahabad/ald_dep.htm |archivedate=3 December 2013 |df= }}</ref> Auto Rickshaws have been a popular mode of transportation.<ref name=mode>{{cite web|title=Allahabad Travel |url=http://www.thekumbhmela.com/allahabad-travel-advise.html |work=Kumbh Mela organizing committee |accessdate=5 August 2012 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120808000427/http://thekumbhmela.com/allahabad-travel-advise.html |archivedate=8 August 2012 |df= }}</ref> [[Cycle rickshaw]]s are the most economical means of transportation in Allahabad along with [[e-rickshaw]]s.<ref name=mode /><ref>{{cite news|last=Mohammad |first=Anas |date=21 October 2014 |title=Meet Tabassum Bano \u2013 the first female e-rickshaw driver of Allahabad |url=http://www.iamin.in/en/allahabad/news/meet-tabassum-bano-first-female-e-rickshaw-driver-allahabad-44796 |newspaper=[[I am in DNA of India]] |location=Allahabad |accessdate=29 October 2014 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141029122217/http://www.iamin.in/en/allahabad/news/meet-tabassum-bano-first-female-e-rickshaw-driver-allahabad-44796 |archivedate=29 October 2014 |df= }}</ref>\n\nThere are several important National Highways that pass through Allahabad:<ref name=Status>{{cite web|title=Completed Stretches on NH2|url=http://www.nhai.org/completednh2.htm|work=National Highways Authority of India|accessdate=20 September 2012|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090214185100/http://nhai.org/completednh2.htm|archivedate=14 February 2009}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!NH (acc. new numbering system)\n!NH (acc. old numbering system)\n!Route\n!Total Length\n|-\n|[[National Highway 19 (India)|NH 19]]\n|NH 2\n|[[Delhi]] \u00bb [[Mathura, Uttar Pradesh|Mathura]] \u00bb [[Agra]] \u00bb [[Kanpur]] \u00bb Allahabad \u00bb [[Varanasi]] \u00bb [[Mohania]] \u00bb [[Barhi, Hazaribagh|Barhi]] \u00bb [[Palsit]] \u00bb [[Dankuni]] (near [[Kolkata]])\n|2542\n|-\n|[[National Highway 30 (India)|NH 30]]\n|NH 24B & NH 27\n|[[Udham Singh Nagar]], [[Uttarakhand]] \u00bb [[Bareilly]] \u00bb [[Lucknow]] \u00bb [[Raebareli]] \u00bb Allahabad \u00bb [[Rewa, Madhya Pradesh|Rewa]] \u00bb [[Jabalpur]] \u00bb [[Raipur]] \u00bb [[Krishna District]], [[Andhra Pradesh]]\n|2022\n|-\n|[[National Highway 35 (India)|NH 35]]\n|NH 76 & NH 76 Extension\n|[[Mahoba]] \u00bb [[Banda, Uttar Pradesh|Banda]] \u00bb [[Chitrakoot district|Chitrakoot]] \u00bb Allahabad \u00bb [[Mirzapur]] \u00bb [[Varanasi]]\n|346\n|-\n|[[National Highway 330 (India)|NH 330]]\n|NH 96\n|Allahabad \u00bb [[Pratapgarh, Uttar Pradesh|Pratapgarh]] \u00bb [[Sultanpur, Uttar Pradesh|Sultanpur]] \u00bb [[Faizabad]] \u00bb [[Gonda, Uttar Pradesh|Gonda]] \u00bb [[Balrampur]]\n|263\n|-\n|}\n\n[[Cable-stayed bridge|Cable-stayed]], [[New Yamuna Bridge, Allahabad|New Yamuna Bridge]] (built 2001\u201304), is in Allahabad and connects the city to the suburb of [[Naini]] across the Yamuna.<ref name=Instrumentation>{{cite web|title=Structural Monitoring System|url=http://www.nhai.org/NIT.htm|work=National Highways Authority of India|accessdate=20 September 2012|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130524011643/http://www.nhai.org/NIT.htm|archivedate=24 May 2013}}</ref> The [[Old Naini Bridge]] now accommodates railway and auto traffic.<ref name=\"Dayaratnam2000\">{{cite book|author=P. Dayaratnam|title=Cable Stayed, Supported, and Suspension Bridges|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pb67nkDk4FMC&pg=PA9|accessdate=25 September 2012|year=2000|publisher=Universities Press|isbn=978-81-7371-271-5|page=9|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523064532/http://books.google.com/books?id=pb67nkDk4FMC&pg=PA9|archivedate=23 May 2013}}</ref><ref name=bridge>{{cite web|title=India's biggest cable-stayed bridge|url=http://www.maurer-soehne.de/files/bauwerkschutzsysteme/pdf/de/projektinfo/PI_NAINI_Bruecke_englisch.pdf|work=Murer Swivel Joist|accessdate=3 August 2012|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121016202936/http://maurer-soehne.de/files/bauwerkschutzsysteme/pdf/de/projektinfo/PI_NAINI_Bruecke_englisch.pdf|archivedate=16 October 2012}}</ref> A road bridge across the Ganges also connects Allahabad and [[Jhusi]].<ref name=\"Institute1958\">{{cite book|title=The Allahabad transportation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_nghAQAAIAAJ|publisher=Agricultural Institute, University of Allahabad|accessdate=3 August 2012|volume=32|page=68|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523064817/http://books.google.com/books?id=_nghAQAAIAAJ|archivedate=23 May 2013|year=1958}}</ref> [[National Waterway 1 (India)|National Waterway 1]], the longest Waterway in India, connects Allahabad and Haldia.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Union Government launched National Waterway-4 project in Tamil Nadu |url=http://www.jagranjosh.com/current-affairs/union-government-launched-national-waterway4-project-in-tamil-nadu-1390650157-1 |newspaper=JagranJosh |location= |date=25 January 2014 |accessdate=29 October 2014 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141029101633/http://www.jagranjosh.com/current-affairs/union-government-launched-national-waterway4-project-in-tamil-nadu-1390650157-1 |archivedate=29 October 2014  }}</ref> A [[Rapid transit|Metrorail]] project for the city covering the entire metropolitan region is also underway.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/other-states/up-cabinet-approves-metro-rail-project-for-allahabad/article9000536.ece |title=U.P. Cabinet approves metro rail project for Allahabad |accessdate=20 August 2016 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160818023903/http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/other-states/up-cabinet-approves-metro-rail-project-for-allahabad/article9000536.ece |archivedate=18 August 2016  |newspaper=The Hindu |date=18 August 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://inextlive.jagran.com/route-map-of-metro-rail-90760 |title=\u091a\u093e\u0930\u094b\u0902 \u0926\u093f\u0936\u093e\u0913\u0902 \u092e\u0947\u0902 \u0926\u094c\u0921\u093c\u0947\u0917\u0940 \u092e\u0947\u091f\u094d\u0930\u094b |accessdate=26 September 2016 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160927091022/http://inextlive.jagran.com/route-map-of-metro-rail-90760 |archivedate=27 September 2016  }}</ref>\n\nThe city generates 5,34,760&nbsp;kg of domestic solid wastes daily, while the per capita generation of waste is 0.40&nbsp;kg per day. The sewer service areas are divided into nine zones in the city.<ref name=\"timesofindia.indiatimes.com\" /> Allahabad Municipal Corporation oversees the solid waste management project.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/cities/lucknow/invitation-card-gives-mayor-a-miss-congmen-stall-ceremony/ |title=Invitation card gives Mayor a miss, Congmen stall ceremony |accessdate=29 August 2015 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305203728/http://indianexpress.com/article/cities/lucknow/invitation-card-gives-mayor-a-miss-congmen-stall-ceremony/ |archivedate=5 March 2016  |date=27 May 2010 }}</ref> Allahabad was the first city to get pre-paid meters for electricity bill in Uttar Pradesh.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/lucknow/Now-manage-your-power-usage-with-pre-paid-meters/articleshow/48209297.cms |title=Now, manage your power usage with pre-paid meters |accessdate=29 August 2015 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180303145638/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/lucknow/Now-manage-your-power-usage-with-pre-paid-meters/articleshow/48209297.cms |archivedate=3 March 2018  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bhaskar.com/news/UP-ALAH-in-uttar-pradesh-launch-first-prepaid-electricity-meter-allahabad-latest-news-4828056-NOR.html |title=\u0907\u0932\u093e\u0939\u093e\u092c\u093e\u0926 \u092e\u0947\u0902 \u0932\u0917\u0947\u0917\u093e \u092f\u0942\u092a\u0940 \u0915\u093e \u092a\u0939\u0932\u093e \u092a\u094d\u0930\u0940\u092a\u0947\u0921 \u092c\u093f\u091c\u0932\u0940 \u0915\u093e \u092e\u0940\u091f\u0930, \u0939\u0941\u0908 \u0932\u0949\u091a\u093f\u0902\u0917 |accessdate=29 August 2015 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923224141/http://www.bhaskar.com/news/UP-ALAH-in-uttar-pradesh-launch-first-prepaid-electricity-meter-allahabad-latest-news-4828056-NOR.html |archivedate=23 September 2015  |date=3 December 2014 }}</ref> The city is equipped with over 40 [[CCTV]]s at major crossings and markets.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/allahabad/Areas-of-Allahabad-to-come-under-CCTV-camera-surveillance/articleshow/48009052.cms |title=Areas of Allahabad to come under CCTV camera surveillance  |accessdate=29 August 2015 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150713195402/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/allahabad/Areas-of-Allahabad-to-come-under-CCTV-camera-surveillance/articleshow/48009052.cms |archivedate=13 July 2015  }}</ref>\n\n=== Allahabad Metro ===\nThe [[Allahabad Metro]] is a proposed [[rapid transit]] system for the city. The proposed system will consist of two lines, an east\u2013west line from [[Bamrauli]] to [[Jhunsi]] and a north\u2013south line from Shantipuram in [[Phaphamau]] to [[Naini]]. Both lines will be about 20&nbsp;km long. There will be a total of 39 stations, 20 on the east\u2013west line and 19 on the north\u2013south line. The project is expected to cost \u20b98000 crores. Operations are expected to be started by 2023\u20132024.\n\n== Projects ==\n[[IBM]] selected Allahabad among 16 other global cities for its smart cities programme to help it address challenges like waste management, disaster management, water management and citizen services.<ref>{{cite news |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150515192742/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2015-05-12/news/62082974_1_ibm-top-experts-smart-cities-mamtha-sharma |archivedate=15 May 2015 |url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2015-05-12/news/62082974_1_ibm-top-experts-smart-cities-mamtha-sharma |title=IBM picks Surat, Allahabad & Vizag among 16 global locations for smart cities project |work=Economic Times |date=12 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/andhra-pradesh/it-giant-to-chalk-out-disaster-management-plan/article7254158.ece |title=IT giant to chalk out disaster management plan |accessdate=29 August 2015 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180303145638/http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/andhra-pradesh/it-giant-to-chalk-out-disaster-management-plan/article7254158.ece |archivedate=3 March 2018  |newspaper=The Hindu |date=28 May 2015 |last1=Bhattacharjee |first1=Sumit }}</ref> The company commenced working on solid waste management and power sector in generating renewable energy.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.businessinsider.in/5-pillars-of-Smart-Cities-Top-honchos-finally-unveil-the-key-to-the-lock-called-Smart/articleshow/48544126.cms |title=5 pillars of Smart Cities: Top honchos finally unveil the key to the lock called 'Smart'! |accessdate=29 August 2015 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150823000857/http://www.businessinsider.in/5-pillars-of-Smart-Cities-Top-honchos-finally-unveil-the-key-to-the-lock-called-Smart/articleshow/48544126.cms |archivedate=23 August 2015  }}</ref>\n\nAs a part of Smart City Project, [[Civil Lines, Allahabad|Civil Lines]] is being developed on the lines of [[Lucknow]]'s [[Hazratganj]]. A sum of  \u20b920 [[crore]] (US$3,024,000) has been sanctioned to [[Beautification|beautify]] all prominent crossings of the city. As per the plan, the administration proposed uniformity in signage and colour of buildings and a parking lot to be set up to solve traffic congestion.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/allahabad/Civil-Lines-makeover-to-be-as-Lucknows-Hazratganj-market/articleshow/48420554.cms |title=Civil Lines makeover to be as Lucknow's Hazratganj market |accessdate=29 August 2015 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150823194513/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/allahabad/Civil-Lines-makeover-to-be-as-Lucknows-Hazratganj-market/articleshow/48420554.cms |archivedate=23 August 2015  }}</ref> A 1.35&nbsp;km long [[riverfront]] along [[Yamuna river]] would be developed by the Allahabad Development Authority, irrigation and power departments at a cost of \u20b9147.36 crore. The riverfront would be developed in two phases. In the first phase, around 650 metres at Arail would be developed along with the Yamuna, while in the second phase 700 metres of the stretch between [[New Yamuna Bridge]] and Boat Club in Kydganj would be taken up.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/allahabad/Citys-smart-journey-to-begin-with-riverfront-along-Yamuna/articleshow/48692413.cms |title=City's smart journey to begin with riverfront along Yamuna |accessdate=29 August 2015 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150927233720/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/allahabad/Citys-smart-journey-to-begin-with-riverfront-along-Yamuna/articleshow/48692413.cms |archivedate=27 September 2015  }}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\n{{Main|List of educational institutions in Allahabad}}\n[[File:Design Centre MNNIT.jpg|thumb|alt=Palm-tree-lined walkway to two-story building|[[Motilal Nehru National Institute of Technology Allahabad]], a public engineering and management school]]\n\nThe Allahabad educational system is distinct from Uttar Pradesh's other cities, with an emphasis on broad education.<ref name=education>{{cite web|title=Broad education system in city |url=https://www.dasanit.org/docs/DASA-2012-brochure.pdf |publisher=DASA UG |accessdate=26 September 2012 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120510234819/https://dasanit.org/docs/DASA-2012-brochure.pdf |archivedate=10 May 2012 |df= }}</ref> [[Board of High School and Intermediate Education Uttar Pradesh]], the world's biggest examining body, is headquartered in the city.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-upmspnicin-upresultsnicin-10th-result-2016-up-board-class-10th-x-high-school-results-2016-to-be-announced-today-on-may-15-at-1230-pm-2212457 |title=Upmsp.nic.in & Upresults.nic.in 10th Result 2016: UP Board class 10th X High School Results 2016 to be announced today on May 15 at 12:30 PM |accessdate=15 May 2016 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160518171957/http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-upmspnicin-upresultsnicin-10th-result-2016-up-board-class-10th-x-high-school-results-2016-to-be-announced-today-on-may-15-at-1230-pm-2212457 |archivedate=18 May 2016  |date=15 May 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://m.timesofindia.com/city/allahabad/UP-board-exam-the-worlds-biggest-to-start-on-February-18/articleshow/50220848.cms |title=UP board exam, the world's biggest, to start on February 18 |accessdate=15 May 2016 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160101191728/http://m.timesofindia.com/city/allahabad/UP-board-exam-the-worlds-biggest-to-start-on-February-18/articleshow/50220848.cms |archivedate=1 January 2016  }}</ref> Although English is the language of instruction in most private schools, government schools and colleges offer Hindi and [[English-medium education]].<ref name=\"Main university\">{{cite web|title=Allahabad University|url=http://www.allduniv.ac.in/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=141&Itemid=378|publisher=[[Allahabad University]]|accessdate=4 August 2012|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120717050032/http://www.allduniv.ac.in/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=141&Itemid=378|archivedate=17 July 2012}}</ref> Schools in Allahabad follow the [[10+2+3 plan]]. After completing their secondary education, students typically enrol in higher secondary schools affiliated with the Uttar Pradesh Board of High School and Intermediate Education, the [[Indian Certificate of Secondary Education|ICSE]] or the [[Central Board of Secondary Education|CBSE]].<ref name=\"Main university\" /> and focus on liberal arts, business or science. Vocational programs are also available.<ref name=Vocational>{{cite web|title=Center of Computer Education and Training|url=http://www.allduniv.ac.in/index.php?option=com_k2&view=item&layout=item&id=78&Itemid=223|publisher=[[Allahabad University]]|accessdate=4 August 2012|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120717051416/http://www.allduniv.ac.in/index.php?option=com_k2&view=item&layout=item&id=78&Itemid=223|archivedate=17 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nAllahabad attracts students from throughout India. As of 2017, the city has one [[Central University, India|central university]], two [[State University, India|State Universities]] and an [[Uttar Pradesh Rajarshi Tandon Open University|open university]].<ref name=\"Land Marks\">{{cite web|title=University history|url=http://www.allduniv.ac.in/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=143&Itemid=379|publisher=[[Allahabad University]]|accessdate=4 August 2012|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120717050042/http://www.allduniv.ac.in/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=143&Itemid=379|archivedate=17 July 2012}}</ref> [[Allahabad University]], founded in 1876, is the oldest university in the state.<ref name=\"Land Marks\" /> [[Motilal Nehru National Institute of Technology Allahabad]] is a noted technical institution.<ref name=\"Goel2009\">{{cite book|author=S.L. Goel Aruna Goel|title=Educational Administration And Management:An Integrated Approach|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=L71yhsLOqtsC&pg=PA94|accessdate=4 August 2012|publisher=Deep & Deep Publications|isbn=978-81-8450-143-8|page=94|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523043914/http://books.google.com/books?id=L71yhsLOqtsC&pg=PA94|archivedate=23 May 2013|year=2009}}</ref> [[Sam Higginbottom University of Agriculture, Technology and Sciences]], founded in 1910, as \"Agricultural Institute\", is an autonomous Christian minority university in Allahabad.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://mhrd.gov.in/sites/upload_files/mhrd/files/document-reports/TFR04032014.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=15 December 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141122091515/http://mhrd.gov.in/sites/upload_files/mhrd/files/document-reports/TFR04032014.pdf |archive-date=22 November 2014 |url-status = live }}</ref> Other notable institutions in Allahabad include the [[Indian Institute of Information Technology, Allahabad|Indian Institute of Information Technology \u2013 Allahabad]]; [[Motilal Nehru Medical College]]; [[Ewing Christian College]]; [[Harish-Chandra Research Institute]]; [[Govind Ballabh Pant Social Science Institute]]; [[Allahabad State University]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.alldstateuniversity.org/ |title=Allahabad State University |accessdate=6 July 2016 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160703030919/http://www.alldstateuniversity.org/ |archivedate=3 July 2016  }}</ref> and [[Institute of Engineering and Rural Technology]].\n\n== Culture ==\n{{See also|List of tourist attractions in Allahabad}}\n\nAlthough [[Hindu]] women have traditionally worn [[sari]]s, the [[shalwar kameez]] and Western attire are gaining acceptance among younger women.<ref name=dress>{{cite news|last=Rebika|first=Laishram|title=The city have a very rich culture|url=http://www.thehindu.com/opinion/open-page/article3364929.ece|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|accessdate=20 September 2012|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120909030055/http://www.thehindu.com/opinion/open-page/article3364929.ece|archivedate=9 September 2012}}</ref> Western dress is worn more by men, although the [[dhoti]] and [[kurta]] are seen during festivals. The formal male [[sherwani]] is often worn with [[chooridar]] on festive occasions.<ref name=dress /> [[Diwali]], [[Holi]], [[Eid al-Fitr|Eid]] and [[Vijayadashami|Vijayadasami]] are the four most popular festivals in Allahabad.<ref name=\"Quick facts\">{{cite web|last=Festivals |first=Fairs And |title=The Prayag Tirtha |url=http://www.cultural-heritage-india.com/cities/allahabad.html |publisher=Cultural and Heritage, india |accessdate=12 January 2014 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130823161941/http://www.cultural-heritage-india.com/cities/allahabad.html |archivedate=23 August 2013 }}</ref>\n\n=== Literature ===\n[[File:Anand Bhawan, Allahabad.jpg|thumb|alt=Ornate blue-and-white building, with plaque on a rock in the foreground|[[Anand Bhavan]], owned by Indian political leader [[Motilal Nehru]]]]\n\nAllahabad has a literary and artistic heritage; the former capital of the United Provinces, it was known as Prayag in the [[Vedas]], the ''[[Ramayana]]'' and the ''[[Mahabharata]]''.<ref name=\"Joshi2008\">{{cite book|author=Ashutosh Joshi|title=Town Planning Regeneration of Cities|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UFaGME0XDBkC&pg=PA151|date=1 January 2008|publisher=New India Publishing|isbn=978-81-89422-82-0|pages=238\u2013239|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180303145638/https://books.google.com/books?id=UFaGME0XDBkC&pg=PA151|archivedate=3 March 2018}}</ref><ref name=virtue>{{cite web|title=A city of many dimensions is what befits a description of Allahabad |url=http://www.up-tourism.com/destination/allahabad/about.htm |website=Uttar Pradesh Tourism |accessdate=24 September 2012 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120831053201/http://www.up-tourism.com/destination/allahabad/about.htm |archivedate=31 August 2012 |df= }}</ref> Allahabad has been called the \"literary capital of Uttar Pradesh\",<ref name=literary>{{cite web|title=Cultural importance of Allahabad|url=http://www.allahabadonline.in/city-guide/culture-of-allahabad|publisher=Allahabad Online Portal|accessdate=20 August 2014|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140821204529/http://www.allahabadonline.in/city-guide/culture-of-allahabad|archivedate=21 August 2014}}</ref> attracting visitors from East Asia;<ref name=Culture>{{cite web|title=Role in Ancient time |url=http://india.mapsofindia.com/destination-guides/culture-of-india/allahabad.html |publisher=Maps of India |accessdate=20 September 2012 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120718121026/http://india.mapsofindia.com/destination-guides/culture-of-india/allahabad.html |archivedate=18 July 2012 }}</ref> the Chinese travellers [[Faxian]] and [[Xuanzang]] found a flourishing city in the fifth and seventh centuries, respectively.<ref name=Culture /><ref name=HieunTsang>{{cite web|title=Hieun Tsang, sukapha to the treaty of Yandaboo|url=http://www.timesofassam.com/headlines/hiuen-tsang-sukapha-to-the-treaty-of-yandaboo/|work=The Times of Assam|accessdate=23 September 2012|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121210161957/http://www.timesofassam.com/headlines/hiuen-tsang-sukapha-to-the-treaty-of-yandaboo/|archivedate=10 December 2012|date=24 January 2012}}</ref> The number of foreign tourists, which mostly consisted of [[Asians]], visiting the city was 98,167 in 2010 which subsequently increased to 1,07,141 in 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://m.timesofindia.com/city/allahabad/European-US-tourists-skip-Sangam-city/articleshow/49300330.cms |title=European, US tourists skip Sangam city |accessdate=21 January 2016 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151025041320/http://m.timesofindia.com/city/allahabad/European-US-tourists-skip-Sangam-city/articleshow/49300330.cms |archivedate=25 October 2015  }}</ref> The city has a tradition of political graffiti which includes [[Limerick (poetry)|limericks]] and caricatures.<ref name=\"Committee1947\" /> In 1900, ''[[Saraswati (magazine)|Saraswati]]'', the first [[Hindi]]-language monthly magazine in India, was started by Chintamani Ghosh. [[Mahavir Prasad Dwivedi]], the doyen of modern Hindi literature, remained its editors from 1903 to 1920.<ref name=pib>{{cite web | title = Education will lay the foundation of India's future, says President | url = http://pib.nic.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=102161 | website = [[Press Information Bureau]], President's Secretariat | date = 25 December 2013 | accessdate = 19 September 2014 |url-status = live| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140924041508/http://pib.nic.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=102161 | archivedate = 24 September 2014 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> The [[Anand Bhavan]], built during the 1930s as a new home for the [[Nehru\u2013Gandhi family|Nehru family]] when the [[Swaraj Bhavan]] became the local [[Indian National Congress]] headquarters, has memorabilia from the Gandhi-Nehru family.<ref name=Palace>{{cite web|title=Swaraj Bhavan|url=http://pages.rediff.com/swaraj-bhavan/1439442|website=[[Rediff.com]]|accessdate=24 September 2012|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121016045940/http://pages.rediff.com/swaraj-bhavan/1439442|archivedate=16 October 2012}}</ref>\n[[File:Kumbh Mela2001.JPG|thumb|alt=Large group of people and vehicles crossing a pontoon bridge|A procession of pilgrims cross the Ganges during the 2001 Kumbh Mela in Allahabad]]\nDuring the 19th and 20th centuries, [[Hindi literature]] was modernised by authors such as [[Mahadevi Varma]], [[Sumitranandan Pant]], [[Suryakant Tripathi 'Nirala']] and [[Harivansh Rai Bachchan]].<ref name=\"Gaeffke1978\">{{cite book|author=Peter Gaeffke|title=Hindi Literature in the Twentieth Century|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=urN55PYoaSgC&pg=PA3|accessdate=20 September 2012|year=1978|publisher=Otto Harrassowitz Verlag|isbn=978-3-447-01614-8|page=3|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523051410/http://books.google.com/books?id=urN55PYoaSgC&pg=PA3|archivedate=23 May 2013}}</ref> A noted poet was Raghupati Sahay, better known as [[Firaq Gorakhpuri]].<ref name=writer>{{cite web |title=Raghupati Sahay, better known under his pen name Firaq Gorakhpuri |url=http://www.urdupoetry.com/firaq.html |publisher=Urdu Poetry Archive |accessdate=20 September 2012 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120909005046/http://www.urdupoetry.com/firaq.html |archivedate=9 September 2012  }}</ref> Gorakhpuri and Varma have received [[Jnanpith Award]]s.<ref name=\"Literary Award\">{{cite web|title=List of Jnanpith Award Winners|url=http://win2vin.wordpress.com/2009/09/02/list-of-jnanpith-award-winners-indias-highest-literary-award/|publisher=Word Press|accessdate=20 September 2012|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120718014202/http://win2vin.wordpress.com/2009/09/02/list-of-jnanpith-award-winners-indias-highest-literary-award/|archivedate=18 July 2012}}</ref><ref name=winners>{{cite web|title=List of all Bhartiya Jnanpith Award Winners|url=http://win2vin.wordpress.com/2009/09/02/list-of-jnanpith-award-winners-indias-highest-literary-award/|publisher=UPSC|accessdate=20 September 2012|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120718014202/http://win2vin.wordpress.com/2009/09/02/list-of-jnanpith-award-winners-indias-highest-literary-award/|archivedate=18 July 2012|date=2 September 2009}}</ref><ref name=award>{{cite web|title=Jnanpith Award Winners (1965\u20132012) |url=http://currentgk.com/gk/awards/jnanpith_award_winners.html |publisher=Creative Literary |accessdate=20 September 2012 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121011051147/http://currentgk.com/gk/awards/jnanpith_award_winners.html |archivedate=11 October 2012 |df= }}</ref> Allahabad is a publication centre for Hindi literature, including the Lok Bharti, Rajkamal and Neelabh. [[Persian language|Persian]] and [[Urdu literature]] are also studied in the city.<ref name=Literature>{{cite web |title=Urdu and Persian Literature in Allahabad |url=http://www.columbia.edu/itc/mealac/pritchett/00fwp/srf/txt_allahabad.html |publisher=Columbia Education |accessdate=20 September 2012 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121026133746/http://www.columbia.edu/itc/mealac/pritchett/00fwp/srf/txt_allahabad.html |archivedate=26 October 2012  }}</ref> [[Akbar Allahabadi]] is a noted modern Urdu poet, and Nooh Narwi, Tegh Allahabadi, Shabnam Naqvi and Rashid Allahabadi hail from Allahabad.<ref name=poet>{{cite web|title=Urdu writers and poets of Allahabad |url=http://www.upurduakademi.org/eng/writer.aspx |publisher=Uttar Pradesh Urdu Academy |accessdate=20 September 2012 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130322071218/http://www.upurduakademi.org/eng/writer.aspx |archivedate=22 March 2013 |df= }}</ref> English author and [[List of Nobel laureates#List of laureates|1907 Nobel laureate]] [[Rudyard Kipling]] was an assistant editor and overseas correspondent for ''[[The Pioneer (newspaper)|The Pioneer]]''.<ref name=\"nobel\">{{cite web|last=Alfred Nobel Foundation |url=http://nobelprize.org/contact/faq/index.html#3b |title=Who is the youngest ever to receive a Nobel Prize, and who is the oldest? |page=409 |work=Nobelprize |accessdate=30 September 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060925202706/http://nobelprize.org/contact/faq/index.html |archivedate=25 September 2006 |url-status = dead|df= }}</ref>\n\n=== Entertainment and recreation ===\nAllahabad is noted for historic, cultural and religious tourism. Historic sites include [[Alfred Park]], the [[Victoria Memorial|Victoria]] and [[Thornhill Mayne Memorial]]s, [[Minto Park]], [[Allahabad Fort]], the [[Allahabad Pillar|Ashoka Pillar]] and [[Khusro Bagh]]. Religious attractions include the [[Kumbh Mela]], the [[Triveni Sangam]] and [[All Saints Cathedral, Allahabad|All Saints Cathedral]]. The city hosts the ''Maha'' [[Kumbh Mela]], the largest religious gathering in the world, every twelve years and the ''Ardh'' (half) Kumbh Mela every six years.<ref name=\"festival\">{{cite web|title=Mythological Significance|url=http://www.indianembassy.org/new/maha_kumbh_mela_2001.htm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100403014350/http://www.indianembassy.org/new/maha_kumbh_mela_2001.htm|archivedate=3 April 2010|publisher=[[Embassy of India]]|accessdate=20 September 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"News\">{{cite news|title=Pilgrims visiting the Kumbh mela|url=http://www.ndtv.com/article/india/kumbh-mela-to-last-for-55-days-instead-of-44-this-year-230857|accessdate=25 September 2012|newspaper=[[NDTV]]|date=13 June 2012|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121214105728/http://www.ndtv.com/article/india/kumbh-mela-to-last-for-55-days-instead-of-44-this-year-230857|archivedate=14 December 2012}}</ref> Cultural attractions include the [[Allahabad Museum]], the [[Jawahar Planetarium]] and the [[University of Allahabad]]. North Central Zone Culture Centre, under the [[Ministry of Culture (India)|Ministry of Culture]] and [[Prayag Sangeet Samiti]] are nationally renowned centres of Arts, Dance, Music, local Folk Dance and Music, Plays/Theatre etc. and nurture upcoming artists. The city has also hosted the International Film Festival of Prayag.<ref>{{cite news|title=International Film Festival of Prayag (IFFP)|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/sagar-sarhadi-to-be-honoured-with-lifetime-achievement-award/|accessdate=1 September 2017|work=[[The Indian Express]]|agency=[[Indian Express Group]]|date=23 February 2016|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170902012439/http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/sagar-sarhadi-to-be-honoured-with-lifetime-achievement-award/|archivedate=2 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Media ===\n''[[The Leader (Allahabad newspaper)|The Leader]]'' and ''[[The Pioneer (Indian newspaper)|The Pioneer]]'' are two major English-language newspapers that are produced and published from the city;<ref name=\"The Pioneer\">{{cite web|title=History of The Pioneer |url=http://www.itopc.org/travel-requisite/newspapers/pioneer.html |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130415072512/http://www.itopc.org/travel-requisite/newspapers/pioneer.html |url-status = dead|archive-date=15 April 2013 |work=Indian Tour Operators Promotion Council |accessdate=26 September 2012 }}</ref><ref name=Chintamani>{{cite news|title=English-language newspapers that are produced from city|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2000/20000507/spectrum/main2.htm#3|newspaper=[[The Sunday Tribune]]|accessdate=26 September 2012|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121026024140/http://www.tribuneindia.com/2000/20000507/spectrum/main2.htm#3|archivedate=26 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[All India Radio]], the national, state-owned radio broadcaster, has [[AM broadcasting|AM]] radio stations in the city. Allahabad has seven [[Frequency modulation|FM]] stations, including two AIR stations: [[Gyan Vani]] and [[Vividh Bharti]], four private FM channels: [[BIG FM 92.7]], [[Red FM 93.5]], [[Fever 104 FM]] and Radio Tadka and one educational FM radio channel Radio Adan 90.4 run by [[Allahabad Agricultural Institute]].<ref name=akashwani>{{cite web|title=All India Radio Allahabad |url=http://www.airallahabad.gov.in/ |publisher=All India Radio |accessdate=15 August 2014 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006130400/http://www.airallahabad.gov.in/ |archivedate=6 October 2014 |df= }}</ref><ref name=\"radio stations\">{{cite web|title=Radio stations in city|url=http://www.asiawaves.net/india/uttar-pradesh-radio.htm#allahabad-radio|work=Asiawaves|accessdate=4 August 2012|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120331070016/http://www.asiawaves.net/india/uttar-pradesh-radio.htm#allahabad-radio|archivedate=31 March 2012}}</ref> There is a [[Doordarshan]] Kendra in the city.<ref name=\"india radio\">{{cite web|title=Doordarshan Kendra, Lajpat Rai Marg, Allahabad|url=http://ddkallahabad.freeservers.com/index.html|publisher=Doordarshan Kendra Allahabad|accessdate=15 August 2014|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140819125609/http://ddkallahabad.freeservers.com/index.html|archivedate=19 August 2014}}</ref> Regional TV channels are accessible via [[Cable television|cable subscription]], [[direct-broadcast satellite]] service or [[IPTV|Internet-based television]].<ref name=regional>{{cite web|title=Present composition of the Prasar Bharati Board |url=http://mib.nic.in/writereaddata/html_en_files/document/docu_other/ar/ar0607/ch4.pdf |publisher=Broadcasting Corporation of India |accessdate=29 September 2012 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121120111837/http://mib.nic.in/writereaddata/html_en_files/document/docu_other/ar/ar0607/ch4.pdf |archivedate=20 November 2012 }}</ref>\n\n=== Sports ===\n[[Cricket]] and [[Hockey|field hockey]] are the most popular sports in Allahabad,<ref name=Eastern>{{cite web|title=All sporting activities |url=http://www.easternuptourism.com/Allahabad.jsp |website=Eastern Uttar Pradesh Tourism |accessdate=25 September 2012 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121009064127/http://www.easternuptourism.com/Allahabad.jsp |archivedate=9 October 2012 |df= }}</ref> with [[kabaddi]], [[kho-kho]], [[gilli danda]] and [[pehlwani]] are played in rural areas near the city.<ref name=list>{{cite web|title=List of sports|url=http://www.ncr.indianrailways.gov.in/uploads/files/1326783505969-sportsmeet.pdf|work=North Central Railway|accessdate=25 September 2012|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120530045705/http://www.ncr.indianrailways.gov.in/uploads/files/1326783505969-sportsmeet.pdf|archivedate=30 May 2012}}</ref> [[Gully cricket]], also known as street cricket, is popular among city youth.<ref name=Eastern /> The famous cricket club [[Allahabad Cricketers]] has produced many national and international cricket players. Several [[sports complex]]es are used by amateur and professional athletes; these include the [[Madan Mohan Malviya Stadium]], the [[Amitabh Bachchan Sports Complex]] and the Boys' High School and College Gymnasium.<ref name=\"Sports centres\">{{cite news|title=City a hub of sports|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2009-03-02/allahabad/28032289_1_national-sports-academy-indoor-sports-gymnastics|accessdate=25 September 2012|newspaper=[[The Times of India]]|date=2 March 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130506151245/http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2009-03-02/allahabad/28032289_1_national-sports-academy-indoor-sports-gymnastics|archive-date=6 May 2013|url-status = live}}</ref> There is an international-level swimming complex in [[Georgetown, Allahabad|Georgetown]].<ref name=Swimming>{{cite news|title=Quality of sport life-An About-Face|url=http://www-cgi.cnn.com/ASIANOW/asiaweek/97/1205/cs1.html|accessdate=25 September 2012|newspaper=Asia Now|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160120005654/http://www-cgi.cnn.com/ASIANOW/asiaweek/97/1205/cs1.html|archivedate=20 January 2016}}</ref> The National Sports Academy in Jhalwa trains [[gymnasts]] for the [[Commonwealth Games]]. The [[Indira Marathon]] honours the late prime minister [[Indira Gandhi]].<ref name=Marathon>{{cite news|title=Stage set for Indira Marathon|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-11-16/allahabad/28231200_1_prize-money-prime-minister-prestigious-marathon|accessdate=25 September 2012|newspaper=[[The Times of India]]|date=16 November 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130407182231/http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-11-16/allahabad/28231200_1_prize-money-prime-minister-prestigious-marathon|archive-date=7 April 2013|url-status = live}}</ref><ref name=Athletics>{{cite news|first=Deep |last=Sharad |title=Indira Marathon faces cancellation |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/News-Feed/NM17/Now-Indira-Marathon-faces-cancellation/Article1-159481.aspx |accessdate=25 September 2012 |newspaper=[[Hindustan Times]] |date=9 October 2006 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130508221955/http://www.hindustantimes.com/News-Feed/NM17/Now-Indira-Marathon-faces-cancellation/Article1-159481.aspx |archivedate=8 May 2013 }}</ref><ref name=dominates>{{cite news|last=Vijay Pratap|first=Singh|title=Pune institute dominates Indira Marathon|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/puneinstitutedominatesindiramarathon/388110/|accessdate=25 September 2012|newspaper=[[The Indian Express]]|date=20 November 2008}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[List of people from Allahabad]]\n* [[Centre for Social Forestry and Eco-Rehabilitation]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book|last1=Cunningham|first1=Alexander|authorlink=Alexander Cunningham|title=Corpus Inscriptionum Indicarum: Inscriptions of Ashoka|date=1879|publisher=Office of the Superintendent of Government Printing|pages=[https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.35693/page/n55 37]\u201338|url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.35693 | ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last=Kane |first=P.&nbsp;V. |authorlink=Pandurang Vaman Kane |year=1953 |title=History of Dharma\u015b\u0101stra: Ancient and Medieval Religious and Civil Law in India |volume=4 |url=https://archive.org/details/HistoryOfDharmasastraancientAndMediaevalReligiousAndCivilLawV.4 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Krishnaswamy |first=C.S. |last2=Ghosh |first2=Amalananda |author-link2=Amalananda Ghosh |date=October 1935 |title=A Note on the Allahabad Pillar of A\u015boka |journal=The Journal of the Royal Asiatic Society of Great Britain and Ireland |volume=4 |issue=4 |pages=697\u2013706 |jstor=25201233 | ref=harv}}\n* ''Allahabad: A Study in Urban Geography'', by Ujagir Singh. Published by Banaras Hindu University, 1966.\n* ''Employment and Migration in Allahabad City'', by Maheshchand, Mahesh Chand, India Planning Commission. Research Programmes Committee. Published by Oxford & IBH Pub. Co., 1969.\n* ''Subah of Allahabad Under the Great Mughals, 1580\u20131707: 1580\u20131707'', by Surendra Nath Sinha. Published by Jamia Millia Islamia, 1974.\n* ''The Local Roots of Indian Politics: Allahabad, 1880\u20131920'', by [[Christopher Bayly|Christopher Alan Bayly]]. Published by Clarendon Press, 1975.\n* ''Triveni: Essays on the Cultural Heritage of Allahabad'', by D. P. Dubey, Neelam Singh, Society of Pilgrimage Studies. Published by Society of Pilgrimage Studies, 1996. {{ISBN|81-900520-2-0}}.\n* ''Magha Inscriptions in the Allahabad Museum'', by Siddheshwari Narain Roy. Published by Raka Prakashana for the Museum, 1999.\n* ''The Last Bunga