{"title_page": "Otulu, Oru West", "text_new": "<ref>https://www.citypopulation.de/php/nigeria-admin.php?adm1id=NGA017</ref>{{for|the community in Ahiara|Otulu, Ahiara}}\n{{Unsourced|date=October 2014}}\n\n'''Otulu''' is a town in Oru West local government area of [[Imo State]], [[Nigeria]]. It is located along the Owerri-Onitsha Federal Highway (which is identified as Highway A6 by Google map) in Imo State. Approaching from Owerri to Onitsha you will get to Awo-Omanma, Amiri and then Otulu after which you have Mgbidi; while from Onitsha to Owerri you have Otulu after Mgbidi. \n\n<br />\n\n== History ==\n{{Coord missing|Nigeria}}The name Otulu is derived from two Igbo words 'Otu' which means 'One' and 'Olu' which means 'voice' which when put together means 'One Voice'. The father of Otulu is Igbo n'abunkwu. He Originated from Nri in Anambra State. This is the reason why the community is known as Otulu Igbo n'abunkwu. When Igbo n'abunkwu started expanding, he and some other immigrants of his community chose the name Otulu \"One Voice\" which signifies Unity that is 'let us be united'.\n\nAccording to Chief E. Ndubuisi (personal communication, July 29, 2014), Otulu married two wives, the first wife was Lolo Ogueri Ukwu and the second wife was Lolo Oji. The first wife had two children namely Umuhu and Umuezem. The second wife had three children namely Ubahawa, Okponsu and Umuojienwe. Umuhu is the first son of Otulu, Umuezem is the second son, Ubahawa is the third son, Okponsu is the forth son and Umuojienwe is the last son. Umuhu had three children they are Umunkwa, Umudurukwu and Umuofia. Umuhu made the first community, Umuezem also made his own community with his five sons namely Umuochihe, Umuelile, Umunka, Umuaro and Umuaso. Ubahawa made his own community with his six sons they are Umuokwa, Umunabia,Umudikwa, Ubahawa Oji, Umuabuba, Umuosunkita including his two brothers Okponsu and Umuojienwe. These made up the sixteen (16) villages in Otulu. Otulu had initially one autonomous community with the sixteen villages but the recent creation of autonomous community in Imo State in the year 2003 brought about the division of the town Otulu into two different autonomous communities such that each autonomous community is headed by a traditional ruler. This is to say that Umuhu and Umuezem autonomous communities were created from the then Otulu autonomous community with the Imo State of Nigeria official gazette No.4 \u00a0Vol 28 \u00a0of 29th October 2003. The Umuhu and Umuezem autonomous communities are made up of eight (8) villages namely Umuofia, Umunka, Umuelile, Umudurukwu, Umuaro, Umuochihe, and Umuaso. While Otulu autonomous community is left with the remaining (8) villages namely Umuokwa, Ubahawa Oji, Umudikwa, Umuabuba, Umunabia, Umuosonkita, Okposu and Umuojienwe.\n\nOtulu has two Traditional Rulers namely Obi of Otulu in the person of HRH Eze Festus I. Orji and Igwe of Otulu in the person of HRH Eze Sunday B. Nnabue; ruling Otulu autonomous community and Umuhu/Umuezem autonomous communities respectively.\n\n== Demographics ==\n<nowiki>Otulu has a population of about 20,028 people living in it.{{</nowiki><ref>http://population.city/nigeria/adm/imo/</ref><nowiki>date=July 2019}}. It has two autonomous communities: Ubahawa and Umuhu/Umuezem.</nowiki>\n\nUbahawa has the following villages:\n\n# Umundikwa\n# Umunnabe\n# Ubahawa-ocha\n# Ubahawa-oji\n# Nkponsu\n# Umuabuba\n# Umuosonkita\n# Umuojienwe\n\nWhile Umuhu/Umuezem has: \n\n# Umunkwa \n# Umudurukwu\n# Umuofia\n# Umuochoihe\n# Umunka\n# Umuelile\n# Umuaro\n# Umuaso\n\nMost people in the town are typically Christians roughly split between the Anglican Church and the Roman Catholic Church. There is a huge following of Anglicanism amongst the natives of Ubahawa with the St. Stephen's Anglican Church serving as a local church as well as an archdeaconry. The Anglican church also has some few worshipers from Umuhu and Umuezem, as well as from the non-indigenes. The St. Stephen's Anglican Church, Otulu was originally established in 1914 by the Christian Missionary Society (CMS).\n\nThe Roman Catholic historically has being dominant in Umuhu and Umuezem, although it also has a sizeable following in Ubahawa. St. Christopher's Catholic Church was established in Ubahawa in the 1990s.\n\nBefore the advent of Christianity, Otulu people like many other African communities are deeply involved in their native beliefs and village deities such as Ogwugwu, Obana and Ala Umuhu. Back then, every family compound has a corner set apart for their family deity, and the head (father) of the family would offers sacrifice regularly on behalf of his family and for other needs. The chief priest does the same for the whole community. But with the advent of Christianity, Otulu now have just very few or no families who still retain this practice.\n\n== Education ==\nThere is one Secondary school in Otulu, which is called Otulu Secondary Commercial School. It was built by the people in the early 1980s. There are two government-owned primary schools namely Community Primary School Otulu and Progressive Central School Otulu. \n\n== Economy ==\nOtulu have two market squares called Afor Otulu and Orie Otulu situated at Ubahawa and Umuhu/Umuezem respectively.\n\nThe town benefits hugely from being on the Onitsha-Owerri highway, as such a lot of shops and businesses typically tend to be sited along this highway. There used to be a few manufacturing facilities located in the town in the 1990s and early 2000s, but not any more.\n\n== Tourism ==\nThere are various cultural festivals which the Otulu people are known for, such festivals includes Owu festival, Ogugu festival, which between June and July of every year, Iri-ji ( New yam festival) which is conducted mainly by the Traditional Rulers.\n\nAugust Meeting is a yearly event held by Otulu women in the month of August.\n\nThe Obana (masquerade) festival takes place in October and November every year. \n\nThe Christmas and New Year holidays are big events in Otulu. Indigenous Otuluers, resident in other parts of the world, typically travel back home (i.e. Otulu) with their family to spend time with their other relatives and friends. There are football tournaments and several outdoor parties such as wedding ceremonies and age-grade activities during this festive season.\n\n<br />{{Populated places of Imo State}}\n\n[[Category: Populated places in Imo State]]\n\n\n{{Imo-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "<ref>https://www.citypopulation.de/php/nigeria-admin.php?adm1id=NGA017</ref>{{for|the community in Ahiara|Otulu, Ahiara}}\n{{Unsourced|date=October 2014}}\n\n'''Otulu''' is a community in Oru West local government area of [[Imo State]], [[Nigeria]]. Otulu has two autonomous communities (Ubahawa & Umuhu/umuezem, \nUbahawa has the following Villages:\n\n* [[Umundikwa]]\n* [[Umunabe]]\n* [[Ubawaocha]]\n* [[Ubawaoji]]\n* [[Nkposu]]\n* [[Umuabuba]]\n* [[Umuosonkita]]\n* [[Umuojienwe]]\n\nWhile Umuhu/Umuezem has \n\n* [[Umunkwa]]\n* [[Umudurukwu]]\n* [[Umuofia]]\n* [[Umuochoihe]]\n* [[umunka]]\n* [[Umuelile]]\n* [[Umuaro]]\n* [[Umuaso]]\n\nOtulu is an ancient kingdom with a population of about 20,028 people living in it.{{<ref>http://population.city/nigeria/adm/imo/</ref>date=July 2019}}\n\nOgwugwu, Obana & Ala umuhu are the name of the village deities, and deities of this name are found in many parts of Igboland. The people of Otulu have a large market called Afo & Orie Otulu situated in Ubahawa and Umuhu/Umueze respectively. The community has two popular churches namely; Catholic and Anglican. They have one secondary School, Otulu Secondary Commercial School Otulu built by the community in the early '80s. There are two government-owned primary schools namely Community Primary School Otulu & Progressive Central School Otulu. \n\nCultural Heritage: Otulu has many cultural festivals: Owu/Ogugu Festival which comes between May/June & July of every year, Iri Ji (New Yam Festivals) which is conducted mainly by the Traditional Rulers/Kings. In October/November comes the Festival of Obana (Masquerades Festival). There are many other hosts of traditional festivals such as Okposi, Agwuisi, etc.\n\nOtulu has Two Traditional Ruers/King namely: Obi of Otulu and Igwe of Otulu. Her Traditional Palace is made up of with Ndi Nze Na Ozo and many other Eze's that made up the cabinets.\n\n{{Coord missing|Nigeria}}\n{{Populated places of Imo State}}\n\n[[Category: Populated places in Imo State]]\n\n\n{{Imo-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ez Agbor", "label": "safe", "comment": "Education", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Otulu,_Oru_West"}
{"title_page": "Zhu Wuhua", "text_new": "{{Chinese name|Zhu}}\n\n'''Zhu Wuhua''' ([[Chinese character|Chinese:]] \u6731\u7269\u534e; January 1902 &ndash; March 1998) was a Chinese electronics engineer. He was an acoustic expert and an academician of the [[Chinese Academy of Sciences]].\n\n==Biography==\nZhu was born in [[Yangzhou]], [[Jiangsu Province]], and graduated from [[Shanghai Jiao Tong University]] in 1923. He obtained his master's degree from [[MIT]] in 1924, and his doctor's degree from [[Harvard University]] in 1926. Zhu was a professor and advisor of Shanghai Jiao Tong University and a former president of the institution. Zhu was a founding member of Chinese Academy of Sciences, elected in 1955.\n\n{{Founding members of the Chinese Academy of Sciences}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zhu, Wuhua}}\n[[Category:1902 births]]\n[[Category:1998 deaths]]\n[[Category:National Southwestern Associated University faculty]]\n[[Category:Chinese electronics engineers]]\n[[Category:Educators from Yangzhou]]\n[[Category:Engineers from Jiangsu]]\n[[Category:Harbin Institute of Technology faculty]]\n[[Category:Harvard School of Engineering and Applied Sciences alumni]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Institute of Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:Members of the Chinese Academy of Sciences]]\n[[Category:Peking University faculty]]\n[[Category:People's Republic of China politicians from Jiangsu]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Shanghai Jiao Tong University]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Yangzhou]]\n[[Category:Shanghai Jiao Tong University alumni]]\n[[Category:Sun Yat-sen University faculty]]\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n{{China-academic-bio-stub}}\n{{China-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Chinese name|Zhu}}\n\n'''Zhu Wuhua''' ([[Chinese character|Chinese:]] \u6731\u7269\u534e; January 1902 &ndash; March 1998) was a Chinese electronics engineer. He was an acoustic expert and an academician of the [[Chinese Academy of Sciences]].\n\n==Biography==\nZhu was born in [[Yangzhou]], [[Jiangsu Province]], and graduated from [[Shanghai Jiao Tong University]] in 1923. He obtained his master's degree from [[MIT]] in 1924, and his doctor's degree from [[Harvard University]] in 1926. Zhu was a prefessor and advisor of Shanghai Jiao Tong University and a former president of the institution. Zhu was a founding member of Chinese Academy of Sciences, elected in 1955.\n\n{{Founding members of the Chinese Academy of Sciences}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zhu, Wuhua}}\n[[Category:1902 births]]\n[[Category:1998 deaths]]\n[[Category:National Southwestern Associated University faculty]]\n[[Category:Chinese electronics engineers]]\n[[Category:Educators from Yangzhou]]\n[[Category:Engineers from Jiangsu]]\n[[Category:Harbin Institute of Technology faculty]]\n[[Category:Harvard School of Engineering and Applied Sciences alumni]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Institute of Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:Members of the Chinese Academy of Sciences]]\n[[Category:Peking University faculty]]\n[[Category:People's Republic of China politicians from Jiangsu]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Shanghai Jiao Tong University]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Yangzhou]]\n[[Category:Shanghai Jiao Tong University alumni]]\n[[Category:Sun Yat-sen University faculty]]\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n{{China-academic-bio-stub}}\n{{China-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Will Sandberg", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zhu_Wuhua"}
{"title_page": "Alvin Ailey", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Alvin Ailey\n| image              = Alvin Ailey Ellington career.jpg\n| image_size         = 200px\n| caption            = photographed by [[Carl Van Vechten]], 1955\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1931|01|05}}\n| birth_place        = [[Rogers, Texas]], U.S.\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|1989|12|01|1931|01|05}}\n| death_place        = [[Manhattan, New York]], U.S.\n| occupation         = [[Dancer]], [[choreographer]], [[activist]]\n| years_active       = \n| awards             = [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]] [[Kennedy Center Honors]]\n}}'''Alvin Ailey''' (January 5, 1931 \u2013 December 1, 1989), a.k.a. Alvin Ailey Jr., was an African-American dancer, director, [[choreographer]], and [[activist]] who founded the [[Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater]] (AAADT), one of the most successful dance companies in the world. He created AAADT and its affiliated Ailey School as havens for nurturing black artists and expressing the universality of the African-American experience through dance. His work fused theatre, modern dance, ballet, and jazz with black vernacular, creating hope-fueled choreography that continues to spread global awareness of black life in America. Ailey's choreographic masterpiece ''[[Revelations (Alvin Ailey)|Revelations]]'' is recognized as one of the most popular and most performed ballets in the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1996-11-17-bk-65405-story.html|title='Dancing the Night Away : Alvin Ailey: A Life in Dance'. By Jennifer Dunning (Addison-Wesley) : 'The Joffrey Ballet: Robert Joffrey and the Making of an American Dance Company'. By Sasha Anawalt (Scribner's) [book reviews]|date=1996-11-17|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/12/10/arts/dance-view-alvin-ailey-believer-in-the-power-of-dance.html|title=Alvin Ailey: Believer in the Power of Dance|last=Dunning|first=Jennifer|date=1989-12-10|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-29|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/stage/2019/01/30/alvin-ailey-dance-theater-offers-a-performance-that-is-a-tribute-to-its-founder-and-to-perseverance-and-strength-in-the-black-community.html|title=For Alvin Ailey Dance Theater, the themes that inspired its founder are as relevant as ever |website=thestar.com The Star|language=en|access-date=2019-07-29|date=2019-01-30 }}</ref> In this work he blended primitive, modern and jazz elements of dance with a concern for black rural America.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Norwich|first=John Julius|title=Oxford Illustrated Encyclopedia Of The Arts|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=1990|isbn=978-0198691372|location=USA|pages=10}}</ref>  On July 15, 2008, the [[United States Congress]] passed a resolution designating AAADT a \u201cvital American cultural ambassador to the World.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/110th-congress/house-resolution/1088|title=H.Res.1088 \u2013 110th Congress (2007\u20132008): Recognizing and commending the Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater for 50 years of service as a vital American cultural ambassador to the world.|last=Nadler|first=Jerrold|date=2008-07-15|website=www.congress.gov|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/03/27/arts/dance/27aile.html|title=Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater \u2013 Dance \u2013 Celebration|last=Dunning|first=Jennifer|date=2008-03-27|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-29|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> That same year, in recognition of AAADT's 50th anniversary, then Mayor [[Michael Bloomberg]] declared December 4 \"Alvin Ailey Day\" in New York City while then Governor [[David Paterson]] honoured the organization on behalf of New York State.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/05/arts/dance/05aile.html|title=One Foot in the Present Season, One Foot in the Past|last=MacAulay|first=Alastair|date=December 4, 2008|work=The New York Times|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nalvin aliey was the worst dancer of all time if you payed for one of his shows get your money back .at 2 iclould dance better than him.\n\nLooking for greater job prospects, Ailey's mother departed for Los Angeles in 1941. He arrived a year later, enrolling at George Washington Carver Junior High School, and then graduating into [[Jefferson High School (Los Angeles, California)|Thomas Jefferson High School]]. In 1946 he had his first experience with concert dance when he saw the [[Katherine Dunham Company|Katherine Dunham Dance Company]] and [[Ballet Russe de Monte-Carlo|Ballet Russe de Monte Carlo]] perform at the Los Angeles Philharmonic Auditorium. This awakened an until then unknown spark of joy within him,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=5436144|title=Katherine Dunham Helped Teach the World to Dance|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref> though he did not become serious about dance until 1949 when his classmate and friend [[Carmen De Lavallade]] dragged him to the [[Melrose Avenue]] studio of [[Lester Horton]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://treasures.danceheritage.org/horton2|title=Lester Horton \u2013 More Resources \u00b7 DHC Treasures|website=treasures.danceheritage.org|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/theater_danc/carmen-de-lavallade-is-86-and-still-the-best-dancer-in-the-room/2017/11/30/03f05d86-cbeb-11e7-8321-481fd63f174d_story.html|title=Carmen de Lavallade is 86 and still the best dancer in the room|last=Kaufman|first=Sarah|date=|website=The Washington Post|language=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref>\n\nAiley studied a wide range of dance styles and techniques\u2014from ballet to Native American inspired movement studies\u2014at Horton's school, which was one of the first racially integrated dance schools in the United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dancespirit.com/horton-technique-2326036575.html|title=Horton Technique|date=2017-03-23|website=Dance Spirit|language=en|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alvinailey.org/alvin-ailey-american-dance-theater/lester-horton|title=Lester Horton|date=2016-04-11|website=Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater|language=en|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref> Though Horton became his mentor,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1988-12-08-8802220952-story.html|title=Alvin Ailey's Assent|last=Kisselgoff|first=Anna |agency=New York Times News Service|website=chicagotribune.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref> Ailey did not commit to dancing full-time; instead he pursued academic courses, studying [[romance language]]s and writing at [[University of California, Los Angeles|UCLA]].<ref>Judy Gitenstein, [https://books.google.com/books?id=xEJ3Awxt87IC&pg=PT21&dq=Alvin+Ailey+california+university&hl=en&sa=X&ei=V-YmVLHdKZKUaqGJgIgC&ved=0CCMQ6wEwAA#v=onepage&q=Alvin%20Ailey%20california%20university&f=false ''Alvin Ailey''], New York: The Rosen Publishing Group, 2006, p. 20.</ref><ref name=\"Dunning\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/12/02/obituaries/alvin-ailey-a-leading-figure-in-modern-dance-dies-at-58.html|title=Alvin Ailey, a Leading Figure In Modern Dance, Dies at 58|last=Dunning|first=Jennifer|date=1989-12-02|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> He continued these studies at [[San Francisco State University|San Francisco State]] in 1951. Living in San Francisco he met [[Maya Angelou]], then known as Marguerite Johnson,<ref name=\"Shepeard\" /> with whom he formed a nightclub act called \"Al and Rita\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reformer.com/stories/al-and-rita,345303|title=Al and Rita|last=Balint|first=Becca|website=The Brattleboro Reformer|language=en|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref> Eventually, he returned to study dance with Horton in Los Angeles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ubuntubiographyproject.com/2018/01/05/alvin-ailey/|title=Alvin Ailey|date=2018-01-06|language=en|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref>\n\nHe joined Horton's dance company in 1953, making his debut in Horton's ''Revue Le Bal Caribe''.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Dancing Revelations: Alvin Ailey's Embodiment of African American Culture|last=DeFrantz|first=Thomas|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2006|isbn=0195301714|location=|pages=29\u201330}}</ref> Horton died suddenly that same year in November from a heart attack, leaving the company without leadership. In order to complete the organization's pressing professional engagements, and because no one else was willing to, Ailey took over as artistic director and choreographer.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2010/sep/09/step-by-step-alvin-ailey|title=Step-by-step guide to dance: Alvin Ailey|last=Roy|first=Sanjoy|date=2010-09-09|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-07-29|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.out.com/dance/2019/4/24/alvin-ailey-finally-getting-his-flowers-30-years-too-late|title=Alvin Ailey Is Finally Getting His Flowers \u2013 30 Years Too Late|date=2019-04-24|website=www.out.com|language=en|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Carmen and ailvin.jpg|thumb|Alvin Ailey and Carmen de Lavallade (1954)]]\nIn 1954 [[Carmen De Lavallade|De Lavallade]] and Ailey were recruited by [[Herbert Ross]] to join the Broadway show, ''[[House of Flowers (musical)|House of Flowers]].'' Ross had been hired to replace George Balanchine as the show's choreographer and he wanted to use the pair, who had become known as a famous dance team in Los Angeles, as featured dancers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/02/12/archives/dance-what-ailey-thought-of-balanchine.html|title=What Ailey Thought of Balanchine|last=Ailey|first=Alvin|date=1995-02-12|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-29|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1998-may-10-ca-52251-story.html|title=The Elder Statesman of Eclectic|date=1998-05-10|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref> The show's book was written and adapted by [[Truman Capote]] from one of his novellas with music from [[Harold Arlen]] and starred [[Pearl Bailey]] and [[Diahann Carroll]]. Ailey and De Lavallade met [[Geoffrey Holder]], who performed alongside them in the chorus, during the production. Holder married De Lavallade and became a life-long artistic collaborator with Ailey.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alvinailey.org/alvin-ailey-american-dance-theater/geoffrey-holder|title=Geoffrey Holder|date=2011-12-01|website=Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater|language=en|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref> After ''House of Flowers'' closed, Ailey appeared in [[Harry Belafonte]]'s touring revue ''Sing, Man, Sing'' with [[Mary Hinkson]] as his dance partner,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thirteen.org/freetodance/biographies/hinkson.html|title=Great Performances: Free To Dance \u2013 Biographies \u2013 Mary Hinkson|website=www.thirteen.org|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref> and the 1957 Broadway musical ''[[Jamaica (musical)|Jamaica]]'', which starred [[Lena Horne]] and [[Ricardo Montalb\u00e1n]]. Drawn to dance, but unable to find a choreographer whose work fulfilled him, Ailey started gathering dancers to perform his own unique vision of dance.\n\n==Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater==\nIn 1958 Ailey founded the [[Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater]] to present his vision of honoring Black culture through dance. The company had its debut at the [[92nd Street Y]]. The performance included Ailey's first masterpiece, ''Blues Suite'', which followed men and women as they caroused and cavorted over the course of an evening while blues music played in the background until church bells began to ring, signalling a return to mundane life.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/12/17/arts/review-dance-three-suites-and-a-solo-in-the-ailey-tradition.html|title=Review/Dance; Three Suites and a Solo In the Ailey Tradition|last=Anderson|first=Jack|date=1989-12-17|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=1912037|title=Alvin Ailey's Dance Troupe at 45|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref> Two years later he premiered his most popular and critically acclaimed work, ''[[Revelations (Alvin Ailey)|Revelations]]'', again at the 92nd Street Y. In creating ''Revelations'' Ailey drew upon his \"blood memories\" of growing up in Texas surrounded by Black people, the church, spirituals, and the blues. The ballet charts the full range of feelings from the majestic \u201cI Been \u2019Buked\u201d to the rapturous \u201cWade in the Water\u201d, closing with the electrifying finale, \u201cRocka My Soul in the Bosom of Abraham.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dancemagazine.com/aileys-revelations-relevant-as-ever-2511389868.html|title=Why We Need Ailey's Revelations Now More Than Ever|date=2017-11-29|website=Dance Magazine|language=en|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/la-ca-cm-alvin-ailey-classic-20170325-story.html|title=What makes Alvin Ailey's 'Revelations' an American dance classic?|date=2017-03-25|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scpr.org/programs/the-frame/2015/04/14/42370/alvin-ailey-dance-troupe-teaches-blood-memories-to/|title=Alvin Ailey dance troupe teaches 'blood memories' to LA teens|last=Radio|first=Southern California Public|date=2015-04-14|website=Southern California Public Radio|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Alvin Ailey - Revelations.jpg|thumb|''Revelations'' performed by Alvin Ailey American Dance Theatre in 2011]]\n\nAfter this performance, and despite their success, the Ailey company struggled to find consistent bookings. Though the [[United States Department of State|US State Department]] sponsored AAADT's first international tour in 1962, which traveled across Asia\u2014with followups to Senegal in 1966 and East & West Africa in 1967\u2014the company was able to book only a few performances per season in America. After a successful week-long engagement at the Billy Rose Theatre, the company was invited to become the resident company at Brooklyn Academy of Music. The relationship did not go well and ended a few years later.\n\nIn 1970, with few bookings on the radar\u2014and on the eve of a tour to Russia as part of a cultural exchange agreement\u2014Ailey announced at a press conference that he was closing the company. In response, the State Department sponsored an Ailey tour of North Africa to tide things over. That August, the company toured to Russia where it was ecstatically received. Their performances were broadcast on Moscow television and seen by over 22 million viewers. On closing night, because the Russian audiences would not stop applauding, the company gave over 30 curtain calls. Returning home with news of this triumph, the company performed a two-week engagement at the [[ANTA Theatre|ANTA Theater]]. By the end of January 1971 performance, the entire run was sold out. After 13 years, Alvin Ailey American Dance Theatre was a monumental success. In August 1972 the company was briefly renamed Alvin Ailey City Center Dance Theater and became a resident company of [[New York City Center]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1973/04/29/archives/alvin-ailey-arsonist-modern-dance-is-getting-hot-then-in-april-of.html|title=Modern dance is getting hot|last=Cohn|first=Ellen|date=1973-04-29|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-29|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nThough Ailey's work has been met with popular and critical acclaim, there have been detractors of his theatrical style. Marcia Siegel accused the company of \"selling soul\",<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Siegel|first=Marcia|date=Mar 10, 1969|title=Selling Soul|url=https://books.google.com/?id=D-ECAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA57&lpg=PA57&dq=marcia+b+siegel.+audiences+forget+to+ask+whether+they+are+contemporary,+relevant,+profound+or+even+honest#v=onepage&q=marcia%20b%20siegel.%20audiences%20forget%20to%20ask%20whether%20they%20are%20contemporary%2C%20relevant%2C%20profound%20or%20even%20honest&f=false|journal=New York Magazine|volume= 2| issue =  10|pages=57|via=}}</ref> and of amplifying and transforming the emotivity characteristic of Graham and his modern dance teachers into \"metaphors of the American black experience\" while creating a positive stereotype of \"supremely physical, supremely sensitive beings\" at the expense of genuineness\".<ref>{{Cite news |last=Siegel | first=Marcia | url=https://www.csmonitor.com/1987/0102/lailey.html|title=The costumes and music change, but what about the dances?|date=1987-01-02|work=Christian Science Monitor|access-date=2019-07-29 | issn=0882-7729}}</ref>\n\nAiley responded to such criticism by stating, \"The black pieces we do that come from blues, spirituals and gospels are part of what I am. They are as honest and truthful as we can make them. I'm interested in putting something on stage that will have a very wide appeal without being condescending; that will reach an audience and make it part of the dance; that will get everybody into the theater. If it's art and entertainment\u2014thank God, that's what I want to be.\"\n\nWhile Ailey choreographed more than 70 ballets for his dancers, he insisted that the company perform pieces by other choreographers rather than stand as a singular vehicle for his voice. In present-day the company continues this ethos by presenting major revivals and commissioning pieces from a wide range of choreographers. The company's repertoire contains over 200 ballets.\n\nThough AAADT was formed to celebrate African American culture and to provide performances for black dancers, who were frequently denied opportunities due to racist mores of the time, Ailey proudly employed artists based solely on artistic talent and integrity, regardless of their background.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.newnownext.com/lgbt-black-history-month/01/2016/|title=9 LGBT People Of Color Who Changed History|work=LOGO News|access-date=2018-10-24}}</ref> In addition to his work as artistic director and choreographer with AADT, Ailey also choreographed ballets for other companies including American Ballet Theatre,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/04/29/arts/dance/29wilson.html|title=Sallie Wilson, 76, Dramatic Ballerina Famed for Antony Tudor Roles|last=Anderson|first=Jack|date=2008-04-29|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-29|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Joffrey Ballet, Royal Danish Ballet,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/12/04/arts/the-dance-3-works-by-ailey.html|title=The Dance: 3 Works by Ailey|last=Kisselgoff|first=Anna|date=1986-12-04|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-29|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and The Metropolitan Opera. For American Ballet Theater, he created ''The River'' (1970), one of several choreographies he set to the jazz music of [[Duke Ellington]].<ref name=\"GroveOnline\">{{GroveOnline | title=Alvin Ailey | author=Au, Susan | url=https://doi.org/10.1093/gmo/9781561592630.article.A2084768 | access-date=11 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nFrom her joining in 1965, the dancer [[Judith Jamison]] served as Ailey's muse.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/la-et-cm-alvin-ailey-60-anniversary-20190403-story.html|title=Judith Jamison joined Alvin Ailey Dance 54 years ago. She's still protecting a legacy of inclusion|date=2019-04-03|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref> In 1971 she premiered ''Cry'', which he dedicated to his mother and black women everywhere.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alvinailey.org/performances/repertory/cry|title=Cry|date=2010-03-15|website=Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater|language=en|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref> Jamison took over as artistic director following his death.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/12/23/arts/dance-view-judith-jamison-adds-spices-to-the-ailey-brew.html|title=Judith Jamison Adds Spices to The Ailey Brew|last=Kisselgoff|first=Anna|date=1990-12-23|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-29|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/fl-xpm-1990-02-11-9001240091-story.html|title=After Ailey|last=Montee|first=Kristy|website=Sun-Sentinel.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mcall.com/news/mc-xpm-1994-05-01-2979655-story.html|title=Judith Jamison keeps the Ailey Dance Vision Going|last=Munson|first=Marty |website=The Morning Call|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref> Other important figures in the company include Sylvia Waters, who in 1974, after performing with the company for six year was asked by Ailey to lead The Alvin Ailey Repertory Ensemble\u2014a junior company, known today as Ailey 2, that prepares leading students for professional dance careers\u2014<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1978/02/24/archives/dance-the-new-and-old-by-junior-ailey-troupe.html|title=Dance: The New and Old By 'Junior' Ailey Troupe|last=Anderson|first=Jack|date=1978-02-24|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-29|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/04/18/arts/dance/sylvia-waters-steps-down-at-ailey-ii.html|title=Sylvia Waters Steps Down at Ailey II|last=Kourlas|first=Gia|date=2012-04-17|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-29|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and Masazumi Chaya, who danced with the company for 15 years then became rehearsal director, and was appointed associate artistic director in 1991.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/08/arts/dance/alvin-ailey-masazumi-chaya-steps-down.html|title=Alvin Ailey's Associate Artistic Director to Step Down|last=Kourlas|first=Gia|date=2019-07-08|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-29|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alvinailey.org/alvin-ailey-american-dance-theater/masazumi-chaya|title=Masazumi Chaya|date=2010-02-09|website=Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater|language=en|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref>\n\n==Choreography==\n\n* ''Cinco Latinos'', Alvin Ailey American Dance Theatre, Kaufmann Concert Hall, New York City, 1958.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alvinailey.org/performances/repertory/cinco-latinos|title=Cinco Latinos|date=2010-03-15|website=Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater|language=en|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref>\n* ''Blues Suite'' (also see below), Alvin Ailey American Dance Theatre, Kaufmann Concert Hall, 1958.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alvinailey.org/performances/repertory/blues-suite|title=Blues Suite|date=2010-03-11|website=Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater|language=en|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref>\n* ''[[Revelations (Alvin Ailey)|Revelations]]'', Alvin Ailey American Dance Theatre, Kaufmann ConcertHall, 1960<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/02/arts/dance/02arts-REVELATIONSA_BRF.html|title=Ailey's New Season: 'Revelations' at 50|last=Bloom|first=Julie|date=2010-08-01|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n* ''Three for Now'', Alvin Ailey American Dance Theatre, Clark Center, New York City, 1960.\n* ''Knoxville: Summer of 1915'', Alvin Ailey American Dance Theatre, Clark Center, 1960.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1969/04/23/archives/alvin-ailey-ballet-on-love-and-death-danced-in-brooklyn.html|title=Alvin Ailey Ballet On Love and Death Danced in Brooklyn|last=McDonagh|first=Don|date=1969-04-23|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n* (With Carmen De Lavallade) ''Roots of the Blues'', Lewisohn Stadium, New York City, 1961.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1963/04/29/archives/alvin-ailey-offers-2-new-dance-works.html|title=Alvin Ailey Offers 2 New Dance Works|date=1963-04-29|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n* ''Hermit Songs'', Alvin Ailey American Dance Theatre, Library of Congress, Washington, D.C., 1963.\n* ''Ariadne'', [[Harkness Ballet]], Opera Comique, Paris, 1965.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1965/03/13/archives/tout-paris-sees-harkness-ballet-alvin-aileys-ariadne-bows-at-gala.html|title=Tout Paris' Sees Harkness Ballet; Alvin Ailey's 'Ariadne' Bows at Gala Benefit Opening|last=Barnes|first=Clive|date=1965-03-13|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n* ''Macumba'', Harkness Ballet, Gran Teatro del Liceo, Barcelona, Spain,1966, then produced as ''Yemanja'', Chicago Opera House, 1967.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1967/10/20/archives/alvin-ailey-theater-group-warmly-received-in-ghana.html|title=Alvin Ailey Theater Group Warmly Received in Ghana|date=1967-10-20|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n* ''Quintet'', Alvin Ailey American Dance Theatre, Church Hill Theatre, [[Edinburgh Festival]], Scotland, 1968, then Billy Rose Theatre, New York City, 1969.\n* ''Masekela Langage'', Alvin Ailey American Dance Theatre, American Dance Festival, New London, Connecticut, 1969, then Brooklyn Academy of Music, New York City, 1969.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1969/11/21/archives/dance-militant-masekela-langage.html|title=Dance: Militant 'Masekela Langage''|last=Kisselgoff|first=Anna|date=1969-11-21|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1971/01/21/archives/ailey-troupe-powerful-in-revised-dance-piece.html|title=Ailey Troupe Powerful In Reised Dance Piece|last=Kisselgoff|first=Anna|date=1971-01-21|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n* ''Streams'', Alvin Ailey American Dance Theatre, Brooklyn Academy of Music, 1970.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/05/09/arts/dance-1970-s-streams-revived-by-alvin-ailey.html|title=Dance: 1970's 'Streams' Revived by Alvin Ailey|last=Anderson|first=Jack|date=1982-05-09|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n* ''Gymnopedies'', Alvin Ailey American Dance Theatre, Brooklyn Academy of Music, 1970.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1971/04/11/archives/whats-in-store-for-us.html|title=What's in Store for Us?|last=Barnes|first=Clive|date=1971-04-11|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alvinailey.org/performances/repertory/gymnopedies|title=Gymnopedies|date=2010-03-16|website=Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater|language=en|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref>\n* ''The River'', American Ballet Theatre, [[New York State Theater]], 1970.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abt.org/ballet/the-river/|title=The River|website=American Ballet Theatre|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1970/06/26/archives/dance-unfinished-river-ballet-theater-presents-aileyellington-work.html|title=Dance: Unfinished 'River'|last=Barnes|first=Clive|date=1970-06-26|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n* ''Flowers'', Alvin Ailey American Dance Theatre, ANTA Theatre, 1971.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1971/01/27/archives/dance-no-ones-sifting-on-his-hands.html|title=Dance: No One's Sitting on His Hands|last=Kisselgoff|first=Anna|date=1971-01-27|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n* ''Myth'', Alvin Ailey American Dance Theatre, New York City Center, 1971.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1971/12/16/archives/dance-playfully-seizing-on-a-ritual-consuelo-atlas-and-3-inhabit.html|title=Dance: Playfully Seizing on a Ritual|last=Barnes|first=Clive|date=1971-12-16|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n* ''Choral Dances'', Alvin Ailey American Dance Theatre, New York City Center, 1971.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1971/12/08/archives/dance-new-ailey-season-blues-suite-and-cry-on-city-center-bill.html|title=Dance: New Ailey Season|last=Kisselgoff|first=Anna|date=1971-12-08|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1977/12/05/archives/ailey-revives-choral-dances-after-6-years.html|title=Ailey Revives 'Choral Dances' After 6 Years|last=Kisselgoff|first=Anna|date=1977-12-05|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n* ''Cry'', Alvin Ailey American Dance Theatre, New York City Center, 1971.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1971/05/05/archives/the-dance-judith-jamisons-triumph-aileys-cry-depicts-the-black.html|title=The Dance: Judith Jamison's Triumph|last=Barnes|first=Clive|date=1971-05-05|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n* ''Mingus Dances'', [[Joffrey Ballet|Robert Joffrey Company]], New York City Center, 1971.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1971/10/03/archives/joffreys-season-starts-wednesday.html|title=Joffrey's Season Starts Wednesday|last=Davis|first=Peter G.|date=1971-10-03|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n* ''Mary Lou's Mass'', Alvin Ailey American Dance Theatre, New York City Center, 1971.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1971/12/09/archives/ailey-dancers-to-give-mary-lous-mass.html|title=Ailey Dancers to Give 'Mary Lou's Mass'|last=Kisselgoff|first=Anna|date=1971-12-09|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n* ''Song for You'', Alvin Ailey American Dance Theatre, New York City Center, 1972.<ref name=\"Kisselgoff\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1972/11/20/archives/dance-love-songs-aileys-new-3part-solo-to-pop-music-is-a-showcase.html|title=Dance: 'Love Songs'|last=Kisselgoff|first=Anna|date=1972-11-20|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n* ''The Lark Ascending'', Alvin Ailey American Dance Theatre, New York City Center, 1972.\n* ''Love Songs'', Alvin Ailey City Center Dance Theater, New York City Center, 1972.<ref name=\"Kisselgoff\"/>\n* ''Shaken Angels'', 10th [[New York Dance Festival]], Delacorte Theatre, New York City, 1972.<ref name=\"Cohn\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1973/04/29/archives/alvin-ailey-arsonist-modern-dance-is-getting-hot-then-in-april-of.html|title=Modern dance is getting hot|last=Cohn|first=Ellen|date=1973-04-29|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n*''Sea Change'', American Ballet Theatre, Kennedy Center Opera House, Washington, D.C., 1972, then New York City Center, 1973.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1973/01/10/archives/dance-ballet-theaters-seachange.html|title=Dance: Ballet Theater's 'Sea\u2010Change'|last=Barnes|first=Clive|date=1973-01-10|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n*''Hidden Rites'', Alvin Ailey City Center Dance Theater, New York City Center, 1973.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1973/05/19/archives/ballet-hidden-rites-new-alvin-ailey-work-has-premiere-with-score-by.html|title=Ballet: 'Hidden Rites'|last=Kisselgoff|first=Anna|date=1973-05-19|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n*''Archipelago'', 1971,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1971/01/14/archives/ailey-reinforced-by-lynn-seymour-american-troupe-to-begin-series-at.html|title=Ailey Reinforced by Lynn Seymour|date=1971-01-14|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n*''The Mooche'', 1975,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1975/11/27/archives/dance-aileys-mooche-company-opens-run-with-revised-work.html|title=Dance: Ailey's 'Mooche'|last=Kisselgoff|first=Anna|date=1975-11-27|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n*''Night Creature'', 1975,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1975/08/14/archives/alley-displays-some-gems-of-dance.html|title=Ailey Displays Some Gems of Dance|last=Barnes|first=Clive|date=1975-08-14|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n*''Pas de \"Duke''\", 1976,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1976/07/31/archives/ballet-one-a-little-heavy-one-deft-the-brahms-quintet-by-nahat.html|title=Ballet: One a Little Heavy, One Deft The 'Brahms Quintet by Nahat Danced Alvin Ailey's 'pas de DUKE'|last=Barnes|first=Clive|date=1976-07-31|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n*''Memoria'', 1979,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1979/12/03/archives/dance-ailey-homage-to-joyce-trisler-the-program.html|title=Dance: Ailey Homage to Joyce Trisler|last=Dunning|first=Jennifer|date=1979-12-03|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n*''Phases'', 1980<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alvinailey.org/performances/repertory/phases|title=Phases|date=2010-03-16|website=Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater|language=en|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/12/13/arts/dance-ailey-company-performs-phases.html|title=Dance: Ailey Company Performs 'Phases'|last=Anderson|first=Jack|date=1983-12-13|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n*''Landscape'', 1981.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1981/12/13/arts/dance-premiere-of-ailey-landscape.html|title=Dance: Premiere of Ailey 'Landscape'|last=Kisselgoff|first=Anna|date=1981-12-13|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==Stage==\n===Acting and dancing===\n*(Broadway debut) ''House of Flowers'', Alvin Theatre, New York City, 1954 \u2013 Actor and dancer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-production/house-of-flowers-2493|title=House of Flowers \u2013 Broadway Musical \u2013 Original {{!}} IBDB|website=www.ibdb.com|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref>\n*''The Carefree Tree'', 1955 \u2013 Actor and dancer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-production/the-carefree-tree-481404|title=The Carefree Tree \u2013 Broadway Play \u2013 Original {{!}} IBDB|website=www.ibdb.com|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref>\n*''Sing, Man, Sing'', 1956 \u2013 Actor and dancer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thirteen.org/freetodance/biographies/hinkson.html|title=Great Performances: Free To Dance \u2013 Biographies \u2013 Mary Hinkson|website=www.thirteen.org|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref>\n*''[[Show Boat]]'', Marine Theatre, Jones Beach, New York, 1957 \u2013 Actor and dancer.\n*''[[Jamaica (musical)|Jamaica]]'', Imperial Theatre, New York City, 1957 \u2013 Actor and lead dance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-production/jamaica-2653|title=Jamaica \u2013 Broadway Musical \u2013 Original {{!}} IBDB|website=www.ibdb.com|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref>\n*''[[Call Me By My Rightful Name]]'', One Sheridan Square Theatre, 1961 \u2013 Paul.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://iobdb.com/Production/4026|title=Call Me By My Rightful Name \u2013 Lortel Archives|website=iobdb.com|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref>\n*''Ding Dong Bell'', Westport Country Playhouse, 1961 \u2013 Negro Political Leader.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.google.com/search?q=isbn:0870677934|title=isbn:0870677934 \u2013 Google Search|website=www.google.com|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref>\n*''Blackstone Boulevard'', ''Talking to You'', produced as double-bill in ''2 by Saroyan'', East End Theatre, New York City, 1961-62.\n*''Tiger, Tiger, Burning Bright'', Booth Theatre, 1962 \u2013 Clarence Morris.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-production/tiger-tiger-burning-bright-2973|title=Tiger, Tiger Burning Bright \u2013 Broadway Play \u2013 Original {{!}} IBDB|website=www.ibdb.com|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref>\n\n===Stage choreography===\n* ''Carmen Jones'', Theatre in the Park, 1959.\n* ''Jamaica'', Music Circus, Lambertville, New Jersey, 1959.\n* ''[[Dark of the Moon (play)|Dark of the Moon]]'', Lenox Hill Playhouse, 1960.\n* (And director) ''African Holiday'' (musical), Apollo Theatre, New York City, 1960, then produced at Howard Theatre, Washington, D.C., 1960.\n* ''Feast of Ashes'' (ballet), Robert Joffrey Company, Teatro San Carlos, Lisbon, Portugal, 1962, then produced at New York City Center, 1971.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1971/10/07/archives/-feast-of-ashes-begins-6week-joffrey-season.html|title='Feast of Ashes' Begins 6\u2010Week Joffrey Season|last=Barnes|first=Clive|date=1971-10-07|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n* ''[[Antony and Cleopatra (opera)]]'', Metropolitan Opera House, Lincoln Center, New York City, 1966.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archives.metoperafamily.org/archives/scripts/cgiip.exe/WService=BibSpeed/gisrch31.r?Term=Antony%2520and%2520Cleopatra%253A%2520Antony%2520%255BD%25EDaz,%2520Justino%255D&limit=5000&xBranch=ALL&xmtype=&xsdate=&xedate=&theterm=Antony%2520and%2520Cleopatra%253A%2520Antony%2520%255BD%25EDaz,%2520Justino%255D&xhome=&xhomepath=&x=0|title=BiblioTech PRO V3.2a|website=archives.metoperafamily.org|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref>\n* ''[[La Strada (musical)|La Strada]]'', first produced at Lunt-Fontanne Theatre, 1969.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-production/la-strada-3308|title=La Strada \u2013 Broadway Musical \u2013 Original {{!}} IBDB|website=www.ibdb.com|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref>\n*[[Leonard Bernstein]]'s ''Mass'', Metropolitan Opera House, 1972, then John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts, Washington, D.C., and Philadelphia Academy of Music, both 1972.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/1972/06/10/mass|title=Mass|last=Boutwell|first=Jane|date=1972-06-03|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en|issn=0028-792X}}</ref>\n* ''[[Carmen]]'', Metropolitan Opera, 1972.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1972/06/13/archives/ailey-will-choreograph-mets-opener-carmen.html|title=Ailey Will Choreograph Met's Opener, 'Carmen'|date=1972-06-13|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n* Choreographed ballet, ''Lord Byron'' (opera; also see below), [[Juilliard School]] of Music, New York City, 1972.<ref name=\"Dunning\"/>\n* ''[[Four Saints in Three Acts|Four Saint]]''<ref name=\"The New York Times\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1964/01/13/archives/theater-a-rousing-jericojim-crow-langston-hughes-play-with-music.html|title=Theater: A Rousing 'Jerico\u2010Jim Crow'; Langston Hughes Play With Music Opens|date=1964-01-13|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>''[[Four Saints in Three Acts|s in Three Acts]]'', Piccolo Met, New York City, 1973.<ref name=\"Cohn\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1973/02/24/archives/opera-minimets-playfulfour-saints-thomsonstein-work-retains-its.html|title=Opera: Minimet's Play ful 'Four Saints'|last=Hewitt|first=Jean|date=1973-02-24|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n===Director===\n* (With William Hairston) ''[[Jerico-Jim Crow]]'', The Sanctuary, New York City, 1964, then Greenwich Mews Theatre, 1968.<ref name=\"The New York Times\"/>\n\n==The Ailey School==\nIn 1969, Ailey founded the Alvin Ailey American Dance Center with the famed [[Martha Graham Dance Company]] principal and choreographer [[Pearl Lang]] as his co-director of the school. Their aim was to provide access to arts and dance to under-resourced communities. They started off in Brooklyn with 125 students. A year later the school relocated to Manhattan behind the [[Lincoln Center for the Performing Arts|Lincoln Center]]'s complex. In 1984, [[Denise Jefferson]] assumed directorship. Under her leadership, the school developed a Bachelor of Fine Arts Program in partnership with Fordham University in 1998. The school was renamed The Ailey School in 1999. Several years later, the school moved into The Joan Weill Center for Dance. Following Jefferson's death in 2010, [[Tracy Inman]] and [[Melanie Person]] assumed stewardship of the school as co-directors of the school. In 2012, after leading Ailey 2 for 38 years, [[Sylvia Waters]] retired. The second company's resident choreographer and associate director [[Troy Powell]] took over her role as artistic director. With the addition of the Elaine Wynn and Family Education Wing, the Ailey school is still growing and is now the largest place in New York City committed to training dancers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theaileyschool.edu/history-philosophy|title=History & Philosophy|date=2016-03-02|work=The Ailey School|access-date=2018-10-24|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nAiley loathed the label \"black choreographer\" and preferred being known simply as a choreographer. He was notoriously private about his life.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1987-05-28-8702090477-story.html|title=Vivid Memories of the Black Experience in Alvin Ailey's|last=Newspapers|first=Nancy Goldner Knight-Ridder|website=chicagotribune.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref> Though gay, he kept his romantic affairs [[Closeted|in the closet]]. Following the death of his friend Joyce Trisler, a failed relationship, and bouts of heavy drinking and cocaine use, Ailey suffered a mental breakdown in 1980. He was diagnosed as manic depressive, known today as [[bipolar disorder]]. During his rehabilitation, Judith Jamison served as co-director of AAADT.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/archive/overtaxed-by-work-and-worry-dance-master-alvin-ailey-takes-a-bad-fall-vol-13-no-20/|title=Overtaxed by Work and Worry, Dance Master Alvin Ailey Takes a Bad Fall|website=People.com|language=en|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref>\n\nAiley died from an AIDS related illness on December 1, 1989, at the age of 58.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/11/27/arts/dance/rennie-harris-alvin-ailey-sixtieth-anniversary.html|title=A Dance Homage to Alvin Ailey as His Company Turns 60|last=Kourlas|first=Gia|date=2018-11-27|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-29|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> He asked his doctor to announce that his death was caused by terminal blood [[dyscrasia]] in order to shield his mother from the stigma associated with HIV/AIDS.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newnownext.com/lgbt-black-history-month/01/2016/|title=9 LGBT People Of Color Who Changed History {{!}} NewNowNext|website=www.newnownext.com|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nIn 1968 Ailey was awarded the Guggenheim Fellowship for Creative Arts, US & Canada.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gf.org/fellows/all-fellows/alvin-ailey/|title=John Simon Guggenheim Foundation {{!}} Alvin Ailey|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref> In 1977 he received the [[Spingarn Medal]] from the [[NAACP]].<ref>[http://www.naacp.org/pages/spingarn-medal-winners \"Spingarn Medal Winners: 1915 To Today\"] {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/6PLj9XvLc?url=http://www.naacp.org/pages/spingarn-medal-winners|date=May 5, 2014}}, NAACP.</ref> He received the [[Kennedy Center Honors]] in 1988, was inducted into the [[National Museum of Dance and Hall of Fame]] in 1992,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.google.com/search?q=isbn:1438467478|title=isbn:1438467478 \u2013 Google Search|website=www.google.com|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref> inducted into the [[Legacy Walk]] in 2012,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.legacyprojectchicago.org/Alvin_Ailey_Plaque_Image.html|title=Alvin Ailey Plaque Image|website=www.legacyprojectchicago.org|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legacyprojectchicago.org/2012_INDUCTEES.html|title=2012 Inductees|author=Victor Salvo |publisher= The Legacy Project}}</ref> and posthumously received the [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]] from [[Barack Obama|President Barack Obama]] in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2014/11/10/president-obama-names-recipients-presidential-medal-freedom|title=President Obama Names Recipients of the Presidential Medal of Freedom|date=November 10, 2014|publisher=[[White House Office of the Press Secretary]]|accessdate=November 12, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019, Ailey was one of the honorees inducted in the [[Rainbow Honor Walk]], a [[List of halls and walks of fame|walk of fame]] in San Francisco's [[Castro District, San Francisco|Castro neighborhood]] noting [[LGBTQ]] people who have \"made significant contributions in their fields.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sfist.com/2014/09/02/castros_rainbow_honor_walk_dedicate/|title=Castro's Rainbow Honor Walk Dedicated Today|last=Barmann|first=Jay|date=September 2, 2014|website=SFist|publisher=SFist|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190810075052/https://sfist.com/2014/09/02/castros_rainbow_honor_walk_dedicate/|archive-date=August 10, 2019|access-date=August 15, 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ebar.com/news/news//277209|title=Castro to see more LGBT honor plaques|last=Bajko|first=Matthew S.|date=June 5, 2019|website=The [[Bay Area Reporter]]|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-08-16}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated5>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kqed.org/news/11765805/tributes-in-bronze-8-more-lgbt-heroes-join-s-f-s-rainbow-honor-walk |title=Tributes in Bronze: 8 More LGBT Heroes Join S.F.'s Rainbow Honor Walk|last=Yollin |first=Patricia |date=August 6, 2019|website=KQED: The California Report|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-08-16}}</ref>\n\nA [[Ailey (crater)|crater]] on [[Mercury (planet)|Mercury]] was named in his honor in 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://planetarynames.wr.usgs.gov/Feature/14953 |title = Ailey |publisher = [[NASA]] |work = Gazetteer of Planetary Nomenclature |accessdate = 27 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|LGBT|Biography}}\n*[[Postmodern dance]]\n*[[20th century concert dance]]\n*[[List of dance companies]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=Shepeard>{{cite news\n | last =Shepeard\n | first =Crystal\n | title =Dr. Maya Angelou: Her Lifetime of Moments Took Our Breath Away\n | newspaper =Truthout\n | location =\n | pages =\n | language =\n | publisher =\n | date =29 May 2014\n | url =http://truth-out.org/opinion/item/24025-dr-maya-angelou-her-lifetime-of-moments-took-our-breath-away\n | accessdate = 29 May 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n; Citations\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |title=Dancing Revelations: Alvin Ailey's Embodiment of African American Culture |last=DeFrantz |first=Thomas F. |year=2004 |location=New York |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-530171-7 |ref=harv}}\n<!--\n-->\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Alvin Ailey}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*[http://www.alvinailey.org Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater]\n*{{IBDB name}}\n*{{IMDb name|14617}}\n*{{iobdb name|30532}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060108130404/http://www.abt.org/education/archive/choreographers/ailey_a.html American Ballet Theater biography]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20051125073818/http://www.kennedy-center.org/calendar/index.cfm?fuseaction=showIndividual&entity_id=3507&source_type=A Kennedy Center biography]\n*''[https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=5024561 NPR: Holiday Dance at the Alvin Ailey Theater]''\n*{{Worldcat id|lccn-n92-6465}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120324054106/http://danceinteractive.jacobspillow.org/dance/alvin-ailey-repertory-ensemble?ref=artist&refcar=%2Fartist%2Fa-b Archive footage of Alvin Ailey Repertory Ensemble dancing Revelations in 1988 at Jacob's Pillow]\n*[https://danceinteractive.jacobspillow.org/alvin-ailey/i-wanna-be-ready-from-revelations/ Archival footage of Matthew Rushing performing in Alvin Ailey's ''Revelations'' in 2007 at Jacob\u2019s Pillow Dance Festival]\n*[https://danceinteractive.jacobspillow.org/alvin-ailey/wade-in-the-water-from-revelations/ Archival footage of Ailey II performing in Alvin Ailey's ''Revelations'' in 1988 at Jacob's Pillow Dance Festival]\n*[https://danceinteractive.jacobspillow.org/alvin-ailey/the-lark-ascending/ Archival footage of Dance Theatre of Harlem performing in Alvin Ailey's ''The Lark Ascending'' in 2013 at Jacob's Pillow Dance Festival]\n{{Dance}}\n{{Kennedy Center Honorees 1980s}}\n{{VH1 Trailblazer Honors}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ailey, Alvin}}\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n[[Category:1989 deaths]]\n[[Category:American choreographers]]\n[[Category:American male ballet dancers]]\n[[Category:African-American dancers]]\n[[Category:African-American choreographers]]\n[[Category:African-American male dancers]]\n[[Category:Gay artists]]\n[[Category:LGBT choreographers]]\n[[Category:LGBT dancers]]\n[[Category:Modern dance]]\n[[Category:Modern dancers]]\n[[Category:Guggenheim Fellows]]\n[[Category:Kennedy Center honorees]]\n[[Category:Presidential Medal of Freedom recipients]]\n[[Category:Spingarn Medal winners]]\n[[Category:LGBT African Americans]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from California]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Texas]]\n[[Category:People with bipolar disorder]]\n[[Category:AIDS-related deaths in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Burials at Rose Hills Memorial Park]]\n[[Category:20th-century African-American people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American artists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American dancers]]\n[[Category:People from Rogers, Texas]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Alvin Ailey\n| image              = Alvin Ailey Ellington career.jpg\n| image_size         = 200px\n| caption            = photographed by [[Carl Van Vechten]], 1955\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1931|01|05}}\n| birth_place        = [[Rogers, Texas]], U.S.\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|1989|12|01|1931|01|05}}\n| death_place        = [[Manhattan, New York]], U.S.\n| occupation         = [[Dancer]], [[choreographer]], [[activist]]\n| years_active       = \n| awards             = [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]] [[Kennedy Center Honors]]\n}}'''Alvin Ailey''' (January 5, 1931 \u2013 December 1, 1989), a.k.a. Alvin Ailey Jr., was an African-American dancer, director, [[choreographer]], and [[activist]] who founded the [[Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater]] (AAADT), one of the most successful dance companies in the world. He created AAADT and its affiliated Ailey School as havens for nurturing black artists and expressing the universality of the African-American experience through dance. His work fused theatre, modern dance, ballet, and jazz with black vernacular, creating hope-fueled choreography that continues to spread global awareness of black life in America. Ailey's choreographic masterpiece ''[[Revelations (Alvin Ailey)|Revelations]]'' is recognized as one of the most popular and most performed ballets in the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1996-11-17-bk-65405-story.html|title='Dancing the Night Away : Alvin Ailey: A Life in Dance'. By Jennifer Dunning (Addison-Wesley) : 'The Joffrey Ballet: Robert Joffrey and the Making of an American Dance Company'. By Sasha Anawalt (Scribner's) [book reviews]|date=1996-11-17|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/12/10/arts/dance-view-alvin-ailey-believer-in-the-power-of-dance.html|title=Alvin Ailey: Believer in the Power of Dance|last=Dunning|first=Jennifer|date=1989-12-10|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-29|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/stage/2019/01/30/alvin-ailey-dance-theater-offers-a-performance-that-is-a-tribute-to-its-founder-and-to-perseverance-and-strength-in-the-black-community.html|title=For Alvin Ailey Dance Theater, the themes that inspired its founder are as relevant as ever |website=thestar.com The Star|language=en|access-date=2019-07-29|date=2019-01-30 }}</ref> In this work he blended primitive, modern and jazz elements of dance with a concern for black rural America.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Norwich|first=John Julius|title=Oxford Illustrated Encyclopedia Of The Arts|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=1990|isbn=978-0198691372|location=USA|pages=10}}</ref>  On July 15, 2008, the [[United States Congress]] passed a resolution designating AAADT a \u201cvital American cultural ambassador to the World.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/110th-congress/house-resolution/1088|title=H.Res.1088 \u2013 110th Congress (2007\u20132008): Recognizing and commending the Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater for 50 years of service as a vital American cultural ambassador to the world.|last=Nadler|first=Jerrold|date=2008-07-15|website=www.congress.gov|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/03/27/arts/dance/27aile.html|title=Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater \u2013 Dance \u2013 Celebration|last=Dunning|first=Jennifer|date=2008-03-27|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-29|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> That same year, in recognition of AAADT's 50th anniversary, then Mayor [[Michael Bloomberg]] declared December 4 \"Alvin Ailey Day\" in New York City while then Governor [[David Paterson]] honoured the organization on behalf of New York State.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/05/arts/dance/05aile.html|title=One Foot in the Present Season, One Foot in the Past|last=MacAulay|first=Alastair|date=December 4, 2008|work=The New York Times|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Early years ==\nBorn in [[Rogers, Texas]], at the height of the [[Great Depression in the United States|Great Depression]] in the violently racist and segregated south, during his youth Ailey was barred from interacting with mainstream society. Abandoned by his father when he was three months old,  Ailey and his mother were forced to work in cotton fields and as domestics in white homes\u2014the only employment available to them. As an escape, Ailey found refuge in the church, sneaking out at night to watch adults dance, and in writing a journal, a practice that he maintained his entire life. Even this could not shield him from a shiftless childhood spent moving from town to town as his mother sought employment, being abandoned with relatives whenever she took off on her own, or watching her get raped at the hands of a white man when he was five years old.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9E01E3DD1530F930A15753C1A960958260|title=Frail, Strong and Dance Incarnate|author=Valerie Gladstone|date=October 23, 1996|work=The New York Times|accessdate=January 9, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blackhistorynow.com/alvin-ailey/|title=Alvin Ailey Biography at Black History Now|website=Black Heritage Commemorative Society|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref>\n\nLooking for greater job prospects, Ailey's mother departed for Los Angeles in 1941. He arrived a year later, enrolling at George Washington Carver Junior High School, and then graduating into [[Jefferson High School (Los Angeles, California)|Thomas Jefferson High School]]. In 1946 he had his first experience with concert dance when he saw the [[Katherine Dunham Company|Katherine Dunham Dance Company]] and [[Ballet Russe de Monte-Carlo|Ballet Russe de Monte Carlo]] perform at the Los Angeles Philharmonic Auditorium. This awakened an until then unknown spark of joy within him,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=5436144|title=Katherine Dunham Helped Teach the World to Dance|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref> though he did not become serious about dance until 1949 when his classmate and friend [[Carmen De Lavallade]] dragged him to the [[Melrose Avenue]] studio of [[Lester Horton]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://treasures.danceheritage.org/horton2|title=Lester Horton \u2013 More Resources \u00b7 DHC Treasures|website=treasures.danceheritage.org|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/theater_danc/carmen-de-lavallade-is-86-and-still-the-best-dancer-in-the-room/2017/11/30/03f05d86-cbeb-11e7-8321-481fd63f174d_story.html|title=Carmen de Lavallade is 86 and still the best dancer in the room|last=Kaufman|first=Sarah|date=|website=The Washington Post|language=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref>\n\nAiley studied a wide range of dance styles and techniques\u2014from ballet to Native American inspired movement studies\u2014at Horton's school, which was one of the first racially integrated dance schools in the United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dancespirit.com/horton-technique-2326036575.html|title=Horton Technique|date=2017-03-23|website=Dance Spirit|language=en|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alvinailey.org/alvin-ailey-american-dance-theater/lester-horton|title=Lester Horton|date=2016-04-11|website=Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater|language=en|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref> Though Horton became his mentor,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1988-12-08-8802220952-story.html|title=Alvin Ailey's Assent|last=Kisselgoff|first=Anna |agency=New York Times News Service|website=chicagotribune.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref> Ailey did not commit to dancing full-time; instead he pursued academic courses, studying [[romance language]]s and writing at [[University of California, Los Angeles|UCLA]].<ref>Judy Gitenstein, [https://books.google.com/books?id=xEJ3Awxt87IC&pg=PT21&dq=Alvin+Ailey+california+university&hl=en&sa=X&ei=V-YmVLHdKZKUaqGJgIgC&ved=0CCMQ6wEwAA#v=onepage&q=Alvin%20Ailey%20california%20university&f=false ''Alvin Ailey''], New York: The Rosen Publishing Group, 2006, p. 20.</ref><ref name=\"Dunning\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/12/02/obituaries/alvin-ailey-a-leading-figure-in-modern-dance-dies-at-58.html|title=Alvin Ailey, a Leading Figure In Modern Dance, Dies at 58|last=Dunning|first=Jennifer|date=1989-12-02|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> He continued these studies at [[San Francisco State University|San Francisco State]] in 1951. Living in San Francisco he met [[Maya Angelou]], then known as Marguerite Johnson,<ref name=\"Shepeard\" /> with whom he formed a nightclub act called \"Al and Rita\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reformer.com/stories/al-and-rita,345303|title=Al and Rita|last=Balint|first=Becca|website=The Brattleboro Reformer|language=en|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref> Eventually, he returned to study dance with Horton in Los Angeles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ubuntubiographyproject.com/2018/01/05/alvin-ailey/|title=Alvin Ailey|date=2018-01-06|language=en|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref>\n\nHe joined Horton's dance company in 1953, making his debut in Horton's ''Revue Le Bal Caribe''.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Dancing Revelations: Alvin Ailey's Embodiment of African American Culture|last=DeFrantz|first=Thomas|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2006|isbn=0195301714|location=|pages=29\u201330}}</ref> Horton died suddenly that same year in November from a heart attack, leaving the company without leadership. In order to complete the organization's pressing professional engagements, and because no one else was willing to, Ailey took over as artistic director and choreographer.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2010/sep/09/step-by-step-alvin-ailey|title=Step-by-step guide to dance: Alvin Ailey|last=Roy|first=Sanjoy|date=2010-09-09|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-07-29|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.out.com/dance/2019/4/24/alvin-ailey-finally-getting-his-flowers-30-years-too-late|title=Alvin Ailey Is Finally Getting His Flowers \u2013 30 Years Too Late|date=2019-04-24|website=www.out.com|language=en|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Carmen and ailvin.jpg|thumb|Alvin Ailey and Carmen de Lavallade (1954)]]\nIn 1954 [[Carmen De Lavallade|De Lavallade]] and Ailey were recruited by [[Herbert Ross]] to join the Broadway show, ''[[House of Flowers (musical)|House of Flowers]].'' Ross had been hired to replace George Balanchine as the show's choreographer and he wanted to use the pair, who had become known as a famous dance team in Los Angeles, as featured dancers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/02/12/archives/dance-what-ailey-thought-of-balanchine.html|title=What Ailey Thought of Balanchine|last=Ailey|first=Alvin|date=1995-02-12|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-29|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1998-may-10-ca-52251-story.html|title=The Elder Statesman of Eclectic|date=1998-05-10|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref> The show's book was written and adapted by [[Truman Capote]] from one of his novellas with music from [[Harold Arlen]] and starred [[Pearl Bailey]] and [[Diahann Carroll]]. Ailey and De Lavallade met [[Geoffrey Holder]], who performed alongside them in the chorus, during the production. Holder married De Lavallade and became a life-long artistic collaborator with Ailey.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alvinailey.org/alvin-ailey-american-dance-theater/geoffrey-holder|title=Geoffrey Holder|date=2011-12-01|website=Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater|language=en|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref> After ''House of Flowers'' closed, Ailey appeared in [[Harry Belafonte]]'s touring revue ''Sing, Man, Sing'' with [[Mary Hinkson]] as his dance partner,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thirteen.org/freetodance/biographies/hinkson.html|title=Great Performances: Free To Dance \u2013 Biographies \u2013 Mary Hinkson|website=www.thirteen.org|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref> and the 1957 Broadway musical ''[[Jamaica (musical)|Jamaica]]'', which starred [[Lena Horne]] and [[Ricardo Montalb\u00e1n]]. Drawn to dance, but unable to find a choreographer whose work fulfilled him, Ailey started gathering dancers to perform his own unique vision of dance.\n\n==Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater==\nIn 1958 Ailey founded the [[Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater]] to present his vision of honoring Black culture through dance. The company had its debut at the [[92nd Street Y]]. The performance included Ailey's first masterpiece, ''Blues Suite'', which followed men and women as they caroused and cavorted over the course of an evening while blues music played in the background until church bells began to ring, signalling a return to mundane life.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/12/17/arts/review-dance-three-suites-and-a-solo-in-the-ailey-tradition.html|title=Review/Dance; Three Suites and a Solo In the Ailey Tradition|last=Anderson|first=Jack|date=1989-12-17|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=1912037|title=Alvin Ailey's Dance Troupe at 45|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref> Two years later he premiered his most popular and critically acclaimed work, ''[[Revelations (Alvin Ailey)|Revelations]]'', again at the 92nd Street Y. In creating ''Revelations'' Ailey drew upon his \"blood memories\" of growing up in Texas surrounded by Black people, the church, spirituals, and the blues. The ballet charts the full range of feelings from the majestic \u201cI Been \u2019Buked\u201d to the rapturous \u201cWade in the Water\u201d, closing with the electrifying finale, \u201cRocka My Soul in the Bosom of Abraham.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dancemagazine.com/aileys-revelations-relevant-as-ever-2511389868.html|title=Why We Need Ailey's Revelations Now More Than Ever|date=2017-11-29|website=Dance Magazine|language=en|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/la-ca-cm-alvin-ailey-classic-20170325-story.html|title=What makes Alvin Ailey's 'Revelations' an American dance classic?|date=2017-03-25|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scpr.org/programs/the-frame/2015/04/14/42370/alvin-ailey-dance-troupe-teaches-blood-memories-to/|title=Alvin Ailey dance troupe teaches 'blood memories' to LA teens|last=Radio|first=Southern California Public|date=2015-04-14|website=Southern California Public Radio|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Alvin Ailey - Revelations.jpg|thumb|''Revelations'' performed by Alvin Ailey American Dance Theatre in 2011]]\n\nAfter this performance, and despite their success, the Ailey company struggled to find consistent bookings. Though the [[United States Department of State|US State Department]] sponsored AAADT's first international tour in 1962, which traveled across Asia\u2014with followups to Senegal in 1966 and East & West Africa in 1967\u2014the company was able to book only a few performances per season in America. After a successful week-long engagement at the Billy Rose Theatre, the company was invited to become the resident company at Brooklyn Academy of Music. The relationship did not go well and ended a few years later.\n\nIn 1970, with few bookings on the radar\u2014and on the eve of a tour to Russia as part of a cultural exchange agreement\u2014Ailey announced at a press conference that he was closing the company. In response, the State Department sponsored an Ailey tour of North Africa to tide things over. That August, the company toured to Russia where it was ecstatically received. Their performances were broadcast on Moscow television and seen by over 22 million viewers. On closing night, because the Russian audiences would not stop applauding, the company gave over 30 curtain calls. Returning home with news of this triumph, the company performed a two-week engagement at the [[ANTA Theatre|ANTA Theater]]. By the end of January 1971 performance, the entire run was sold out. After 13 years, Alvin Ailey American Dance Theatre was a monumental success. In August 1972 the company was briefly renamed Alvin Ailey City Center Dance Theater and became a resident company of [[New York City Center]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1973/04/29/archives/alvin-ailey-arsonist-modern-dance-is-getting-hot-then-in-april-of.html|title=Modern dance is getting hot|last=Cohn|first=Ellen|date=1973-04-29|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-29|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nThough Ailey's work has been met with popular and critical acclaim, there have been detractors of his theatrical style. Marcia Siegel accused the company of \"selling soul\",<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Siegel|first=Marcia|date=Mar 10, 1969|title=Selling Soul|url=https://books.google.com/?id=D-ECAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA57&lpg=PA57&dq=marcia+b+siegel.+audiences+forget+to+ask+whether+they+are+contemporary,+relevant,+profound+or+even+honest#v=onepage&q=marcia%20b%20siegel.%20audiences%20forget%20to%20ask%20whether%20they%20are%20contemporary%2C%20relevant%2C%20profound%20or%20even%20honest&f=false|journal=New York Magazine|volume= 2| issue =  10|pages=57|via=}}</ref> and of amplifying and transforming the emotivity characteristic of Graham and his modern dance teachers into \"metaphors of the American black experience\" while creating a positive stereotype of \"supremely physical, supremely sensitive beings\" at the expense of genuineness\".<ref>{{Cite news |last=Siegel | first=Marcia | url=https://www.csmonitor.com/1987/0102/lailey.html|title=The costumes and music change, but what about the dances?|date=1987-01-02|work=Christian Science Monitor|access-date=2019-07-29 | issn=0882-7729}}</ref>\n\nAiley responded to such criticism by stating, \"The black pieces we do that come from blues, spirituals and gospels are part of what I am. They are as honest and truthful as we can make them. I'm interested in putting something on stage that will have a very wide appeal without being condescending; that will reach an audience and make it part of the dance; that will get everybody into the theater. If it's art and entertainment\u2014thank God, that's what I want to be.\"\n\nWhile Ailey choreographed more than 70 ballets for his dancers, he insisted that the company perform pieces by other choreographers rather than stand as a singular vehicle for his voice. In present-day the company continues this ethos by presenting major revivals and commissioning pieces from a wide range of choreographers. The company's repertoire contains over 200 ballets.\n\nThough AAADT was formed to celebrate African American culture and to provide performances for black dancers, who were frequently denied opportunities due to racist mores of the time, Ailey proudly employed artists based solely on artistic talent and integrity, regardless of their background.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.newnownext.com/lgbt-black-history-month/01/2016/|title=9 LGBT People Of Color Who Changed History|work=LOGO News|access-date=2018-10-24}}</ref> In addition to his work as artistic director and choreographer with AADT, Ailey also choreographed ballets for other companies including American Ballet Theatre,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/04/29/arts/dance/29wilson.html|title=Sallie Wilson, 76, Dramatic Ballerina Famed for Antony Tudor Roles|last=Anderson|first=Jack|date=2008-04-29|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-29|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Joffrey Ballet, Royal Danish Ballet,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/12/04/arts/the-dance-3-works-by-ailey.html|title=The Dance: 3 Works by Ailey|last=Kisselgoff|first=Anna|date=1986-12-04|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-29|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and The Metropolitan Opera. For American Ballet Theater, he created ''The River'' (1970), one of several choreographies he set to the jazz music of [[Duke Ellington]].<ref name=\"GroveOnline\">{{GroveOnline | title=Alvin Ailey | author=Au, Susan | url=https://doi.org/10.1093/gmo/9781561592630.article.A2084768 | access-date=11 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nFrom her joining in 1965, the dancer [[Judith Jamison]] served as Ailey's muse.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/la-et-cm-alvin-ailey-60-anniversary-20190403-story.html|title=Judith Jamison joined Alvin Ailey Dance 54 years ago. She's still protecting a legacy of inclusion|date=2019-04-03|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref> In 1971 she premiered ''Cry'', which he dedicated to his mother and black women everywhere.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alvinailey.org/performances/repertory/cry|title=Cry|date=2010-03-15|website=Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater|language=en|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref> Jamison took over as artistic director following his death.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/12/23/arts/dance-view-judith-jamison-adds-spices-to-the-ailey-brew.html|title=Judith Jamison Adds Spices to The Ailey Brew|last=Kisselgoff|first=Anna|date=1990-12-23|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-29|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/fl-xpm-1990-02-11-9001240091-story.html|title=After Ailey|last=Montee|first=Kristy|website=Sun-Sentinel.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mcall.com/news/mc-xpm-1994-05-01-2979655-story.html|title=Judith Jamison keeps the Ailey Dance Vision Going|last=Munson|first=Marty |website=The Morning Call|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref> Other important figures in the company include Sylvia Waters, who in 1974, after performing with the company for six year was asked by Ailey to lead The Alvin Ailey Repertory Ensemble\u2014a junior company, known today as Ailey 2, that prepares leading students for professional dance careers\u2014<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1978/02/24/archives/dance-the-new-and-old-by-junior-ailey-troupe.html|title=Dance: The New and Old By 'Junior' Ailey Troupe|last=Anderson|first=Jack|date=1978-02-24|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-29|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/04/18/arts/dance/sylvia-waters-steps-down-at-ailey-ii.html|title=Sylvia Waters Steps Down at Ailey II|last=Kourlas|first=Gia|date=2012-04-17|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-29|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and Masazumi Chaya, who danced with the company for 15 years then became rehearsal director, and was appointed associate artistic director in 1991.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/08/arts/dance/alvin-ailey-masazumi-chaya-steps-down.html|title=Alvin Ailey's Associate Artistic Director to Step Down|last=Kourlas|first=Gia|date=2019-07-08|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-29|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alvinailey.org/alvin-ailey-american-dance-theater/masazumi-chaya|title=Masazumi Chaya|date=2010-02-09|website=Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater|language=en|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref>\n\n==Choreography==\n\n* ''Cinco Latinos'', Alvin Ailey American Dance Theatre, Kaufmann Concert Hall, New York City, 1958.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alvinailey.org/performances/repertory/cinco-latinos|title=Cinco Latinos|date=2010-03-15|website=Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater|language=en|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref>\n* ''Blues Suite'' (also see below), Alvin Ailey American Dance Theatre, Kaufmann Concert Hall, 1958.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alvinailey.org/performances/repertory/blues-suite|title=Blues Suite|date=2010-03-11|website=Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater|language=en|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref>\n* ''[[Revelations (Alvin Ailey)|Revelations]]'', Alvin Ailey American Dance Theatre, Kaufmann ConcertHall, 1960<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/02/arts/dance/02arts-REVELATIONSA_BRF.html|title=Ailey's New Season: 'Revelations' at 50|last=Bloom|first=Julie|date=2010-08-01|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n* ''Three for Now'', Alvin Ailey American Dance Theatre, Clark Center, New York City, 1960.\n* ''Knoxville: Summer of 1915'', Alvin Ailey American Dance Theatre, Clark Center, 1960.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1969/04/23/archives/alvin-ailey-ballet-on-love-and-death-danced-in-brooklyn.html|title=Alvin Ailey Ballet On Love and Death Danced in Brooklyn|last=McDonagh|first=Don|date=1969-04-23|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n* (With Carmen De Lavallade) ''Roots of the Blues'', Lewisohn Stadium, New York City, 1961.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1963/04/29/archives/alvin-ailey-offers-2-new-dance-works.html|title=Alvin Ailey Offers 2 New Dance Works|date=1963-04-29|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n* ''Hermit Songs'', Alvin Ailey American Dance Theatre, Library of Congress, Washington, D.C., 1963.\n* ''Ariadne'', [[Harkness Ballet]], Opera Comique, Paris, 1965.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1965/03/13/archives/tout-paris-sees-harkness-ballet-alvin-aileys-ariadne-bows-at-gala.html|title=Tout Paris' Sees Harkness Ballet; Alvin Ailey's 'Ariadne' Bows at Gala Benefit Opening|last=Barnes|first=Clive|date=1965-03-13|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n* ''Macumba'', Harkness Ballet, Gran Teatro del Liceo, Barcelona, Spain,1966, then produced as ''Yemanja'', Chicago Opera House, 1967.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1967/10/20/archives/alvin-ailey-theater-group-warmly-received-in-ghana.html|title=Alvin Ailey Theater Group Warmly Received in Ghana|date=1967-10-20|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n* ''Quintet'', Alvin Ailey American Dance Theatre, Church Hill Theatre, [[Edinburgh Festival]], Scotland, 1968, then Billy Rose Theatre, New York City, 1969.\n* ''Masekela Langage'', Alvin Ailey American Dance Theatre, American Dance Festival, New London, Connecticut, 1969, then Brooklyn Academy of Music, New York City, 1969.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1969/11/21/archives/dance-militant-masekela-langage.html|title=Dance: Militant 'Masekela Langage''|last=Kisselgoff|first=Anna|date=1969-11-21|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1971/01/21/archives/ailey-troupe-powerful-in-revised-dance-piece.html|title=Ailey Troupe Powerful In Reised Dance Piece|last=Kisselgoff|first=Anna|date=1971-01-21|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n* ''Streams'', Alvin Ailey American Dance Theatre, Brooklyn Academy of Music, 1970.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/05/09/arts/dance-1970-s-streams-revived-by-alvin-ailey.html|title=Dance: 1970's 'Streams' Revived by Alvin Ailey|last=Anderson|first=Jack|date=1982-05-09|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n* ''Gymnopedies'', Alvin Ailey American Dance Theatre, Brooklyn Academy of Music, 1970.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1971/04/11/archives/whats-in-store-for-us.html|title=What's in Store for Us?|last=Barnes|first=Clive|date=1971-04-11|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alvinailey.org/performances/repertory/gymnopedies|title=Gymnopedies|date=2010-03-16|website=Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater|language=en|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref>\n* ''The River'', American Ballet Theatre, [[New York State Theater]], 1970.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abt.org/ballet/the-river/|title=The River|website=American Ballet Theatre|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1970/06/26/archives/dance-unfinished-river-ballet-theater-presents-aileyellington-work.html|title=Dance: Unfinished 'River'|last=Barnes|first=Clive|date=1970-06-26|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n* ''Flowers'', Alvin Ailey American Dance Theatre, ANTA Theatre, 1971.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1971/01/27/archives/dance-no-ones-sifting-on-his-hands.html|title=Dance: No One's Sitting on His Hands|last=Kisselgoff|first=Anna|date=1971-01-27|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n* ''Myth'', Alvin Ailey American Dance Theatre, New York City Center, 1971.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1971/12/16/archives/dance-playfully-seizing-on-a-ritual-consuelo-atlas-and-3-inhabit.html|title=Dance: Playfully Seizing on a Ritual|last=Barnes|first=Clive|date=1971-12-16|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n* ''Choral Dances'', Alvin Ailey American Dance Theatre, New York City Center, 1971.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1971/12/08/archives/dance-new-ailey-season-blues-suite-and-cry-on-city-center-bill.html|title=Dance: New Ailey Season|last=Kisselgoff|first=Anna|date=1971-12-08|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1977/12/05/archives/ailey-revives-choral-dances-after-6-years.html|title=Ailey Revives 'Choral Dances' After 6 Years|last=Kisselgoff|first=Anna|date=1977-12-05|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n* ''Cry'', Alvin Ailey American Dance Theatre, New York City Center, 1971.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1971/05/05/archives/the-dance-judith-jamisons-triumph-aileys-cry-depicts-the-black.html|title=The Dance: Judith Jamison's Triumph|last=Barnes|first=Clive|date=1971-05-05|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n* ''Mingus Dances'', [[Joffrey Ballet|Robert Joffrey Company]], New York City Center, 1971.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1971/10/03/archives/joffreys-season-starts-wednesday.html|title=Joffrey's Season Starts Wednesday|last=Davis|first=Peter G.|date=1971-10-03|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n* ''Mary Lou's Mass'', Alvin Ailey American Dance Theatre, New York City Center, 1971.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1971/12/09/archives/ailey-dancers-to-give-mary-lous-mass.html|title=Ailey Dancers to Give 'Mary Lou's Mass'|last=Kisselgoff|first=Anna|date=1971-12-09|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n* ''Song for You'', Alvin Ailey American Dance Theatre, New York City Center, 1972.<ref name=\"Kisselgoff\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1972/11/20/archives/dance-love-songs-aileys-new-3part-solo-to-pop-music-is-a-showcase.html|title=Dance: 'Love Songs'|last=Kisselgoff|first=Anna|date=1972-11-20|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n* ''The Lark Ascending'', Alvin Ailey American Dance Theatre, New York City Center, 1972.\n* ''Love Songs'', Alvin Ailey City Center Dance Theater, New York City Center, 1972.<ref name=\"Kisselgoff\"/>\n* ''Shaken Angels'', 10th [[New York Dance Festival]], Delacorte Theatre, New York City, 1972.<ref name=\"Cohn\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1973/04/29/archives/alvin-ailey-arsonist-modern-dance-is-getting-hot-then-in-april-of.html|title=Modern dance is getting hot|last=Cohn|first=Ellen|date=1973-04-29|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n*''Sea Change'', American Ballet Theatre, Kennedy Center Opera House, Washington, D.C., 1972, then New York City Center, 1973.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1973/01/10/archives/dance-ballet-theaters-seachange.html|title=Dance: Ballet Theater's 'Sea\u2010Change'|last=Barnes|first=Clive|date=1973-01-10|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n*''Hidden Rites'', Alvin Ailey City Center Dance Theater, New York City Center, 1973.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1973/05/19/archives/ballet-hidden-rites-new-alvin-ailey-work-has-premiere-with-score-by.html|title=Ballet: 'Hidden Rites'|last=Kisselgoff|first=Anna|date=1973-05-19|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n*''Archipelago'', 1971,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1971/01/14/archives/ailey-reinforced-by-lynn-seymour-american-troupe-to-begin-series-at.html|title=Ailey Reinforced by Lynn Seymour|date=1971-01-14|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n*''The Mooche'', 1975,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1975/11/27/archives/dance-aileys-mooche-company-opens-run-with-revised-work.html|title=Dance: Ailey's 'Mooche'|last=Kisselgoff|first=Anna|date=1975-11-27|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n*''Night Creature'', 1975,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1975/08/14/archives/alley-displays-some-gems-of-dance.html|title=Ailey Displays Some Gems of Dance|last=Barnes|first=Clive|date=1975-08-14|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n*''Pas de \"Duke''\", 1976,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1976/07/31/archives/ballet-one-a-little-heavy-one-deft-the-brahms-quintet-by-nahat.html|title=Ballet: One a Little Heavy, One Deft The 'Brahms Quintet by Nahat Danced Alvin Ailey's 'pas de DUKE'|last=Barnes|first=Clive|date=1976-07-31|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n*''Memoria'', 1979,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1979/12/03/archives/dance-ailey-homage-to-joyce-trisler-the-program.html|title=Dance: Ailey Homage to Joyce Trisler|last=Dunning|first=Jennifer|date=1979-12-03|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n*''Phases'', 1980<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alvinailey.org/performances/repertory/phases|title=Phases|date=2010-03-16|website=Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater|language=en|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/12/13/arts/dance-ailey-company-performs-phases.html|title=Dance: Ailey Company Performs 'Phases'|last=Anderson|first=Jack|date=1983-12-13|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n*''Landscape'', 1981.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1981/12/13/arts/dance-premiere-of-ailey-landscape.html|title=Dance: Premiere of Ailey 'Landscape'|last=Kisselgoff|first=Anna|date=1981-12-13|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==Stage==\n===Acting and dancing===\n*(Broadway debut) ''House of Flowers'', Alvin Theatre, New York City, 1954 \u2013 Actor and dancer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-production/house-of-flowers-2493|title=House of Flowers \u2013 Broadway Musical \u2013 Original {{!}} IBDB|website=www.ibdb.com|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref>\n*''The Carefree Tree'', 1955 \u2013 Actor and dancer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-production/the-carefree-tree-481404|title=The Carefree Tree \u2013 Broadway Play \u2013 Original {{!}} IBDB|website=www.ibdb.com|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref>\n*''Sing, Man, Sing'', 1956 \u2013 Actor and dancer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thirteen.org/freetodance/biographies/hinkson.html|title=Great Performances: Free To Dance \u2013 Biographies \u2013 Mary Hinkson|website=www.thirteen.org|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref>\n*''[[Show Boat]]'', Marine Theatre, Jones Beach, New York, 1957 \u2013 Actor and dancer.\n*''[[Jamaica (musical)|Jamaica]]'', Imperial Theatre, New York City, 1957 \u2013 Actor and lead dance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-production/jamaica-2653|title=Jamaica \u2013 Broadway Musical \u2013 Original {{!}} IBDB|website=www.ibdb.com|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref>\n*''[[Call Me By My Rightful Name]]'', One Sheridan Square Theatre, 1961 \u2013 Paul.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://iobdb.com/Production/4026|title=Call Me By My Rightful Name \u2013 Lortel Archives|website=iobdb.com|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref>\n*''Ding Dong Bell'', Westport Country Playhouse, 1961 \u2013 Negro Political Leader.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.google.com/search?q=isbn:0870677934|title=isbn:0870677934 \u2013 Google Search|website=www.google.com|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref>\n*''Blackstone Boulevard'', ''Talking to You'', produced as double-bill in ''2 by Saroyan'', East End Theatre, New York City, 1961-62.\n*''Tiger, Tiger, Burning Bright'', Booth Theatre, 1962 \u2013 Clarence Morris.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-production/tiger-tiger-burning-bright-2973|title=Tiger, Tiger Burning Bright \u2013 Broadway Play \u2013 Original {{!}} IBDB|website=www.ibdb.com|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref>\n\n===Stage choreography===\n* ''Carmen Jones'', Theatre in the Park, 1959.\n* ''Jamaica'', Music Circus, Lambertville, New Jersey, 1959.\n* ''[[Dark of the Moon (play)|Dark of the Moon]]'', Lenox Hill Playhouse, 1960.\n* (And director) ''African Holiday'' (musical), Apollo Theatre, New York City, 1960, then produced at Howard Theatre, Washington, D.C., 1960.\n* ''Feast of Ashes'' (ballet), Robert Joffrey Company, Teatro San Carlos, Lisbon, Portugal, 1962, then produced at New York City Center, 1971.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1971/10/07/archives/-feast-of-ashes-begins-6week-joffrey-season.html|title='Feast of Ashes' Begins 6\u2010Week Joffrey Season|last=Barnes|first=Clive|date=1971-10-07|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n* ''[[Antony and Cleopatra (opera)]]'', Metropolitan Opera House, Lincoln Center, New York City, 1966.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archives.metoperafamily.org/archives/scripts/cgiip.exe/WService=BibSpeed/gisrch31.r?Term=Antony%2520and%2520Cleopatra%253A%2520Antony%2520%255BD%25EDaz,%2520Justino%255D&limit=5000&xBranch=ALL&xmtype=&xsdate=&xedate=&theterm=Antony%2520and%2520Cleopatra%253A%2520Antony%2520%255BD%25EDaz,%2520Justino%255D&xhome=&xhomepath=&x=0|title=BiblioTech PRO V3.2a|website=archives.metoperafamily.org|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref>\n* ''[[La Strada (musical)|La Strada]]'', first produced at Lunt-Fontanne Theatre, 1969.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-production/la-strada-3308|title=La Strada \u2013 Broadway Musical \u2013 Original {{!}} IBDB|website=www.ibdb.com|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref>\n*[[Leonard Bernstein]]'s ''Mass'', Metropolitan Opera House, 1972, then John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts, Washington, D.C., and Philadelphia Academy of Music, both 1972.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/1972/06/10/mass|title=Mass|last=Boutwell|first=Jane|date=1972-06-03|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en|issn=0028-792X}}</ref>\n* ''[[Carmen]]'', Metropolitan Opera, 1972.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1972/06/13/archives/ailey-will-choreograph-mets-opener-carmen.html|title=Ailey Will Choreograph Met's Opener, 'Carmen'|date=1972-06-13|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n* Choreographed ballet, ''Lord Byron'' (opera; also see below), [[Juilliard School]] of Music, New York City, 1972.<ref name=\"Dunning\"/>\n* ''[[Four Saints in Three Acts|Four Saint]]''<ref name=\"The New York Times\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1964/01/13/archives/theater-a-rousing-jericojim-crow-langston-hughes-play-with-music.html|title=Theater: A Rousing 'Jerico\u2010Jim Crow'; Langston Hughes Play With Music Opens|date=1964-01-13|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>''[[Four Saints in Three Acts|s in Three Acts]]'', Piccolo Met, New York City, 1973.<ref name=\"Cohn\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1973/02/24/archives/opera-minimets-playfulfour-saints-thomsonstein-work-retains-its.html|title=Opera: Minimet's Play ful 'Four Saints'|last=Hewitt|first=Jean|date=1973-02-24|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n===Director===\n* (With William Hairston) ''[[Jerico-Jim Crow]]'', The Sanctuary, New York City, 1964, then Greenwich Mews Theatre, 1968.<ref name=\"The New York Times\"/>\n\n==The Ailey School==\nIn 1969, Ailey founded the Alvin Ailey American Dance Center with the famed [[Martha Graham Dance Company]] principal and choreographer [[Pearl Lang]] as his co-director of the school. Their aim was to provide access to arts and dance to under-resourced communities. They started off in Brooklyn with 125 students. A year later the school relocated to Manhattan behind the [[Lincoln Center for the Performing Arts|Lincoln Center]]'s complex. In 1984, [[Denise Jefferson]] assumed directorship. Under her leadership, the school developed a Bachelor of Fine Arts Program in partnership with Fordham University in 1998. The school was renamed The Ailey School in 1999. Several years later, the school moved into The Joan Weill Center for Dance. Following Jefferson's death in 2010, [[Tracy Inman]] and [[Melanie Person]] assumed stewardship of the school as co-directors of the school. In 2012, after leading Ailey 2 for 38 years, [[Sylvia Waters]] retired. The second company's resident choreographer and associate director [[Troy Powell]] took over her role as artistic director. With the addition of the Elaine Wynn and Family Education Wing, the Ailey school is still growing and is now the largest place in New York City committed to training dancers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theaileyschool.edu/history-philosophy|title=History & Philosophy|date=2016-03-02|work=The Ailey School|access-date=2018-10-24|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nAiley loathed the label \"black choreographer\" and preferred being known simply as a choreographer. He was notoriously private about his life.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1987-05-28-8702090477-story.html|title=Vivid Memories of the Black Experience in Alvin Ailey's|last=Newspapers|first=Nancy Goldner Knight-Ridder|website=chicagotribune.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref> Though gay, he kept his romantic affairs [[Closeted|in the closet]]. Following the death of his friend Joyce Trisler, a failed relationship, and bouts of heavy drinking and cocaine use, Ailey suffered a mental breakdown in 1980. He was diagnosed as manic depressive, known today as [[bipolar disorder]]. During his rehabilitation, Judith Jamison served as co-director of AAADT.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/archive/overtaxed-by-work-and-worry-dance-master-alvin-ailey-takes-a-bad-fall-vol-13-no-20/|title=Overtaxed by Work and Worry, Dance Master Alvin Ailey Takes a Bad Fall|website=People.com|language=en|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref>\n\nAiley died from an AIDS related illness on December 1, 1989, at the age of 58.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/11/27/arts/dance/rennie-harris-alvin-ailey-sixtieth-anniversary.html|title=A Dance Homage to Alvin Ailey as His Company Turns 60|last=Kourlas|first=Gia|date=2018-11-27|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-29|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> He asked his doctor to announce that his death was caused by terminal blood [[dyscrasia]] in order to shield his mother from the stigma associated with HIV/AIDS.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newnownext.com/lgbt-black-history-month/01/2016/|title=9 LGBT People Of Color Who Changed History {{!}} NewNowNext|website=www.newnownext.com|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nIn 1968 Ailey was awarded the Guggenheim Fellowship for Creative Arts, US & Canada.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gf.org/fellows/all-fellows/alvin-ailey/|title=John Simon Guggenheim Foundation {{!}} Alvin Ailey|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref> In 1977 he received the [[Spingarn Medal]] from the [[NAACP]].<ref>[http://www.naacp.org/pages/spingarn-medal-winners \"Spingarn Medal Winners: 1915 To Today\"] {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/6PLj9XvLc?url=http://www.naacp.org/pages/spingarn-medal-winners|date=May 5, 2014}}, NAACP.</ref> He received the [[Kennedy Center Honors]] in 1988, was inducted into the [[National Museum of Dance and Hall of Fame]] in 1992,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.google.com/search?q=isbn:1438467478|title=isbn:1438467478 \u2013 Google Search|website=www.google.com|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref> inducted into the [[Legacy Walk]] in 2012,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.legacyprojectchicago.org/Alvin_Ailey_Plaque_Image.html|title=Alvin Ailey Plaque Image|website=www.legacyprojectchicago.org|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legacyprojectchicago.org/2012_INDUCTEES.html|title=2012 Inductees|author=Victor Salvo |publisher= The Legacy Project}}</ref> and posthumously received the [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]] from [[Barack Obama|President Barack Obama]] in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2014/11/10/president-obama-names-recipients-presidential-medal-freedom|title=President Obama Names Recipients of the Presidential Medal of Freedom|date=November 10, 2014|publisher=[[White House Office of the Press Secretary]]|accessdate=November 12, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019, Ailey was one of the honorees inducted in the [[Rainbow Honor Walk]], a [[List of halls and walks of fame|walk of fame]] in San Francisco's [[Castro District, San Francisco|Castro neighborhood]] noting [[LGBTQ]] people who have \"made significant contributions in their fields.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sfist.com/2014/09/02/castros_rainbow_honor_walk_dedicate/|title=Castro's Rainbow Honor Walk Dedicated Today|last=Barmann|first=Jay|date=September 2, 2014|website=SFist|publisher=SFist|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190810075052/https://sfist.com/2014/09/02/castros_rainbow_honor_walk_dedicate/|archive-date=August 10, 2019|access-date=August 15, 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ebar.com/news/news//277209|title=Castro to see more LGBT honor plaques|last=Bajko|first=Matthew S.|date=June 5, 2019|website=The [[Bay Area Reporter]]|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-08-16}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated5>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kqed.org/news/11765805/tributes-in-bronze-8-more-lgbt-heroes-join-s-f-s-rainbow-honor-walk |title=Tributes in Bronze: 8 More LGBT Heroes Join S.F.'s Rainbow Honor Walk|last=Yollin |first=Patricia |date=August 6, 2019|website=KQED: The California Report|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-08-16}}</ref>\n\nA [[Ailey (crater)|crater]] on [[Mercury (planet)|Mercury]] was named in his honor in 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://planetarynames.wr.usgs.gov/Feature/14953 |title = Ailey |publisher = [[NASA]] |work = Gazetteer of Planetary Nomenclature |accessdate = 27 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|LGBT|Biography}}\n*[[Postmodern dance]]\n*[[20th century concert dance]]\n*[[List of dance companies]]\n\n==References==\n{{Ref